Harry Potter was a highly unusual boy in many ways. For one thing, he hated the summer holidays more than any other time of year. For another, he really wanted to do his home\-work but was forced to do it in secret, in the dead of night. And he also happened to be a wizard.\par
It was nearly midnight, and he was lying on his stomach in bed, the blankets drawn right over his head like a tent, a flashlight in one hand and a large leather-bound book \i (A History of Magic \i0 by Bathilda Bagshot) propped open against the pillow. Harry moved the tip of his eagle-feather quill down the page, frowning as he looked for something that would help him write his essay, \ldblquote Witch Burning in the Fourteenth Century Was Completely Pointless \emdash  discuss.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The quill paused at the top of a likely-looking paragraph. Harry pushed his round glasses up the bridge of his nose, moved his flash\-light closer to the book, and read:\par
\par
\i Non-magic people (more commonly known as Muggles) were particularly afraid of magic in me\-dieval times, but not very good at recognizing it. On the rare occasion that they did catch a real witch or wizard, burning had no effect whatsoever. The witch or wizard would perform a basic Flame Freezing Charm and then pretend to shriek with pain while enjoying a gentle, tickling sensation. Indeed, Wen\-delin the Weird enjoyed being burned so much that she allowed herself to be caught no less than forty-seven times in various disguises.\lang3081\i0\par
\par
\lang1033 Harry put his quill between his teeth and reached underneath his pillow for his ink bottle and a roll of parchment. Slowly and very carefully he unscrewed the ink bottle, dipped his quill into it, and began to write, pausing every now and then to listen, because if any of the Dursleys heard the scratching of his quill on their way to the bathroom, he\rquote d probably find himself locked in the cup\-board under the stairs for the rest of the summer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Dursley family of number four, Privet Drive, was the reason that Harry never enjoyed his summer holidays. Uncle Vernon, Aunt Petunia, and their son, Dudley, were Harry\rquote s only living rela\-tives. They were Muggles, and they had a very medieval attitude toward magic. Harry\rquote s dead parents, who had been a witch and wizard themselves, were never mentioned under the Dursleys\rquote  roof. For years, Aunt Petunia and Uncle Vernon had hoped that if they kept Harry as downtrodden as possible, they would be able to squash the magic out of him. To their fury, they had been unsuc\-cessful. These days they lived in terror of anyone finding out that\lang3081  \lang1033 Harry had spent most of the last two years at Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry. The most they could do, however, was to lock away Harry\rquote s spellbooks, wand, cauldron, and broomstick at the start of the summer break, and forbid him to talk to the neighbors.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This separation from his spellbooks had been a real problem for Harry, because his teachers at Hogwarts had given him a lot of hol\-iday work. One of the essays, a particularly nasty one about shrink\-ing potions, was for Harry\rquote s least favorite teacher, Professor Snape, who would be delighted to have an excuse to give Harry detention for a month. Harry had therefore seized his chance in the first week of the holidays. While Uncle Vernon, Aunt Petunia, and Dudley had gone out into the front garden to admire Uncle Vernon\rquote s new company car (in very loud voices, so that the rest of the street would notice it too), Harry had crept downstairs, picked the lock on the cupboard under the stairs, grabbed some of his books, and hidden them in his bedroom. As long as he didn\rquote t leave spots of ink on the sheets, the Dursleys need never know that he was studying magic by night.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was particularly keen to avoid trouble with his aunt and uncle at the moment, as they were already in an especially bad mood with him, all because he\rquote d received a telephone call from a fellow wizard one week into the school vacation.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron Weasley, who was one of Harry\rquote s best friends at Hogwarts, came from a whole family of wizards. This meant that he knew a lot of things Harry didn\rquote t, but had never used a telephone before. Most unluckily it had been Uncle Vernon who had answered the call.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Vernon Dursley speaking.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, who happened to be in the room at the time, froze as he heard Ron\rquote s voice answer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote HELLO? HELLO? CAN YOU HEAR ME? I \emdash  WANT \emdash  TO \emdash  TALK \emdash  TO \emdash  HARRY \emdash  POTTER!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron was yelling so loudly that Uncle Vernon jumped and held the receiver a foot away from his ear, staring at it with an expression of mingled fury and alarm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote WHO IS THIS?\rdblquote  he roared in the direction of the mouthpiece. \ldblquote WHO ARE YOU?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote RON \emdash  WEASLEY!\rdblquote  Ron bellowed back, as though he and Uncle Vernon were speaking from opposite ends of a football field. \ldblquote I\rquote M \emdash  A \emdash  FRIEND \emdash  OF \emdash  HARRY\rquote S \emdash  FROM \emdash  SCHOOL \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Uncle Vernon\rquote s small eyes swiveled around to Harry, who was rooted to the spot.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote THERE IS NO HARRY POTTER HERE!\rdblquote  he roared, now holding the receiver at arm\rquote s length, as though frightened it might explode. \ldblquote I DON\rquote T KNOW WHAT SCHOOL YOU\rquote RE TALK\-ING ABOUT! NEVER CONTACT ME AGAIN! DON\rquote T YOU COME NEAR MY FAMILY!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he threw the receiver back onto the telephone as if drop\-ping a poisonous spider.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The fight that had followed had been one of the worst ever.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote HOW DARE YOU GIVE THIS NUMBER TO PEOPLE LIKE \emdash  PEOPLE LIKE \i YOU\i0 !\rdblquote  Uncle Vernon had roared, spray\-ing Harry with spit.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron obviously realized that he\rquote d gotten Harry into trouble, because he hadn\rquote t called again. Harry\rquote s other best friend from\lang3081  \lang1033 Hogwarts, Hermione Granger, hadn\rquote t been in touch either. Harry suspected that Ron had warned Hermione not to call, which was a pity, because Hermione, the cleverest witch in Harry\rquote s year, had Muggle parents, knew perfectly well how to use a telephone, and would probably have had enough sense not to say that she went to Hogwarts.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 So Harry had had no word from any of his wizarding friends for five long weeks, and this summer was turning out to be almost as bad as the last one. There was just one very small improvement \emdash  after swearing that he wouldn\rquote t use her to send letters to any of his friends, Harry had been allowed to let his owl, Hedwig, out at night. Uncle Vernon had given in because of the racket Hedwig made if she was locked in her cage all the time.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry finished writing about Wendelin the Weird and paused to listen again. The silence in the dark house was broken only by the distant, grunting snores of his enormous cousin, Dudley. \i It must be very late, \i0 Harry thought. His eyes were itching with tiredness. Per\-haps he\rquote d finish this essay tomorrow night. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He replaced the top of the ink bottle; pulled an old pillowcase from under his bed; put the flashlight, \i A History of Magic, \i0 his essay, quill, and ink inside it; got out of bed; and hid the lot under a loose floorboard under his bed. Then he stood up, stretched, and checked the time on the luminous alarm clock on his bedside table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was one o\rquote clock in the morning. Harry\rquote s stomach gave a funny jolt. He had been thirteen years old, without realizing it, for a whole hour.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Yet another unusual thing about Harry was how little he looked forward to his birthdays. He had never received a birthday card in\lang3081  \lang1033 his life. The Dursleys had completely ignored his last two birthdays, and he had no reason to suppose they would remember this one.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry walked across the dark room, past Hedwig\rquote s large, empty cage, to the open window. He leaned on the sill, the cool night air pleasant on his face after a long time under the blankets. Hedwig had been absent for two nights now. Harry wasn\rquote t worried about her: she\rquote d been gone this long before. But he hoped she\rquote d be back soon \emdash  she was the only living creature in this house who didn\rquote t flinch at the sight of him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, though still rather small and skinny for his age, had grown a few inches over the last year. His jet-black hair, however, was just as it always had been \emdash  stubbornly untidy, whatever he did to it. The eyes behind his glasses were bright green, and on his forehead, clearly visible through his hair, was a thin scar, shaped like a bolt of lightning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Of all the unusual things about Harry, this scar was the most ex\-traordinary of all. It was not, as the Dursleys had pretended for ten years, a souvenir of the car crash that had killed Harry\rquote s parents, be\-cause Lily and James Potter had not died in a car crash. They had been murdered, murdered by the most feared Dark wizard for a hundred years, Lord Voldemort. Harry had escaped from the same attack with nothing more than a scar on his forehead, where Volde\-mort\rquote s curse, instead of killing him, had rebounded upon its origi\-nator. Barely alive, Voldemort had fled. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Harry had come face-to-face with him at Hogwarts. Re\-membering their last meeting as he stood at the dark window, Harry had to admit he was lucky even to have reached his thir\-teenth birthday.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He scanned the starry sky for a sign of Hedwig, perhaps soaring\lang3081  \lang1033 back to him with a dead mouse dangling from her beak, expecting praise. Gazing absently over the rooftops, it was a few seconds be\-fore Harry realized what he was seeing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Silhouetted against the golden moon, and growing larger every moment, was a large, strangely lopsided creature, and it was flap\-ping in Harry\rquote s direction. He stood quite still, watching it sink lower and lower. For a split second he hesitated, his hand on the window latch, wondering whether to slam it shut. But then the bizarre creature soared over one of the street lamps of Privet Drive, and Harry, realizing what it was, leapt aside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Through the window soared three owls, two of them holding up the third, which appeared to be unconscious. They landed with a soft \i flump\i0  on Harry\rquote s bed, and the middle owl, which was large and gray, keeled right over and lay motionless. There was a large pack\-age tied to its legs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry recognized the unconscious owl at once \emdash  his name was Errol, and he belonged to the Weasley family. Harry dashed to the bed, untied the cords around Errol\rquote s legs, took off the par\-cel, and then carried Errol to Hedwig\rquote s cage. Errol opened one bleary eye, gave a feeble hoot of thanks, and began to gulp some water.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned back to the remaining owls. One of them, the large snowy female, was his own Hedwig. She, too, was carrying a parcel and looked extremely pleased with herself. She gave Harry an affectionate nip with her beak as he removed her burden, then flew across the room to join Errol.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry didn\rquote t recognize the third owl, a handsome tawny one, but he knew at once where it had come from, because in addition to a third package, it was carrying a letter bearing the Hogwarts\lang3081  \lang1033 crest. When Harry relieved this owl of its burden, it ruffled its feathers importantly, stretched its wings, and took off through the window into the night.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry sat down on his bed and grabbed Errol\rquote s package, ripped off the brown paper, and discovered a present wrapped in gold, and his first ever birthday card. Fingers trembling slightly, he opened the envelope. Two pieces of paper fell out \emdash  a letter and a news\-paper clipping.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The clipping had clearly come out of the wizarding newspaper, the \i Daily Prophet, \i0 because the people in the black-and-white pic\-ture were moving. Harry picked up the clipping, smoothed it out, and read:\par
\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc\lang1033 MINISTRY OF MAGIC EMPLOYEE\par
SCOOPS GRAND PRIZE\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033 Arthur Weasley, Head of the Misuse of Muggle Ar\-tifacts Office at the Ministry of Magic, has won the annual \i Daily Prophet\i0  Grand Prize Galleon Draw.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A delighted Mr. Weasley told the \i Daily Prophet, \i0\ldblquote We will be spending the gold on a summer holi\-day in Egypt, where our eldest son, Bill, works as a curse breaker for Gringotts Wizarding Bank.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Weasley family will be spending a month in Egypt, returning for the start of the new school year at Hogwarts, which five of the Weasley chil\-dren currently attend.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
Harry scanned the moving photograph, and a grin spread across his face as he saw all nine of the Weasleys waving furiously at him,\lang3081  \lang1033 standing in front of a large pyramid. Plump little Mrs. Weasley; tall, balding Mr. Weasley; six sons; and one daughter, all (though the black-and-white picture didn\rquote t show it) with flaming-red hair. Right in the middle of the picture was Ron, tall and gangling, with his pet rat, Scabbers, on his shoulder and his arm around his little sister, Ginny.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry couldn\rquote t think of anyone who deserved to win a large pile of gold more than the Weasleys, who were very nice and extremely poor. He picked up Ron\rquote s letter and unfolded it.\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033\i Dear Harry,\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Happy birthday!\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Look, I\rquote m really sorry about that telephone call. I hope the Muggles didn\rquote t give you a hard time. I asked Dad, and he reckons I shouldn\rquote t have shouted.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i It\rquote s amazing here in Egypt. Bill\rquote s taken us around all the tombs and you wouldn\rquote t believe the curses those old Egyptian wizards put on them. Mum wouldn\rquote t let Ginny come in the last one. There were all these mutant skeletons in there, of Muggles who\rquote d broken in and grown extra heads and stuff.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i I couldn\rquote t believe it when Dad won the \i0 Daily Prophet \i Draw. Seven hundred galleons! Most of it\rquote s gone on this trip, but they\rquote re going to buy me a new wand for next year.\lang3081\i0\par
\par
\lang1033 Harry remembered only too well the occasion when Ron\rquote s old wand had snapped. It had happened when the car the two of them had been flying to Hogwarts had crashed into a tree on the school grounds.\par
\par
\i We\rquote ll be back about a week before term starts and we\rquote ll be going up to London to get my wand and our new books. Any chance of meeting you there?\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Don\rquote t let the Muggles get you down!\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Try and come to London,\lang3081\i0\par
\i Ron\par
\i0\par
\lang1033\i PS. Percy\rquote s Head Boy. He got the letter last week.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\par
Harry glanced back at the photograph. Percy, who was in his sev\-enth and final year at Hogwarts, was looking particularly smug. He had pinned his Head Boy badge to the fez perched jauntily on top of his neat hair, his horn-rimmed glasses flashing in the Egyptian sun.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry now turned to his present and unwrapped it. Inside was what looked like a miniature glass spinning top. There was another note from Ron beneath it.\par
\par
\i Harry \i0\emdash  \i this is a Pocket Sneakoscope. If there\rquote s someone untrustworthy around, it\rquote s supposed to light up and spin. Bill says it\rquote s rubbish sold for wizard tourists and isn\rquote t reliable, because it kept lighting up at dinner last night. But he didn\rquote t realize Fred and George had put beetles in his soup.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Bye \i0\emdash\lang3081\par
\i Ron\par
\i0\par
\lang1033 Harry put the Pocket Sneakoscope on his bedside table, where it stood quite still, balanced on its point, reflecting the luminous hands of his clock. He looked at it happily for a few seconds, then picked up the parcel Hedwig had brought.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Inside this, too, there was a wrapped present, a card, and a letter, this time from Hermione.\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033\i Dear Harry,\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Ron wrote to me and told me about his phone call to your Uncle Vernon. I do hope you\rquote re all right.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i I\rquote m on holiday in France at the moment and I didn\rquote t know how I was going to send this to you \i0\emdash  \i what if they\rquote d opened it at customs? \i0\emdash  \i but then Hedwig turned up! I think she wanted to make sure you got something for your birthday for a change. I bought your present by owl-order; there was an advertisement in the \i0 Daily Prophet \i (I\rquote ve been getting it delivered; it\rquote s so good to keep up with what\rquote s going on in the wizarding world). Did you see that picture of Ron and his family a week ago? I bet he\rquote s learning loads. I\rquote m really jealous \i0\emdash  \i the ancient Egyptian wizards were fas\-cinating.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i There\rquote s some interesting local history of witchcraft here, too. I\rquote ve rewritten my whole History of Magic essay to include some of the things I\rquote ve found out. I hope it\rquote s not too long \i0\emdash  \i it\rquote s two rolls of parchment more than Professor Binns asked for.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Ron says he\rquote s going to be in London in the last week of the holidays. Can you make it? Will your aunt and uncle let you come? I really hope you can. If not, I\rquote ll see you on the Hogwarts Express on September first!\par
Love from\par
Hermonie\par
PS. Ron says Percy\rquote s Head Boy. I\rquote ll bet Percy\rquote s really pleased.\par
Ron doesn\rquote t seem too happy about it.\lang3081\i0\par
\par
\lang1033 Harry laughed as he put Hermione\rquote s letter aside and picked up her present. It was very heavy. Knowing Hermione, he was sure it would be a large book full of very difficult spells \emdash  but it wasn\rquote t. His heart gave a huge bound as he ripped back the paper and saw a sleek black leather case, with silver words stamped across it, reading \i Broomstick Servicing Kit.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wow, Hermione!\rdblquote  Harry whispered, unzipping the case to look inside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a large jar of Fleetwood\rquote s High-Finish Handle Polish, a pair of gleaming silver Tail-Twig Clippers, a tiny brass compass to clip on your broom for long journeys, and a \i Handbook of\lang3081  \lang1033 Do-It-Yourself\lang3081  \lang1033 Broomcare.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 Apart from his friends, the thing that Harry missed most about Hogwarts was Quidditch, the most popular sport in the magical world \emdash  highly dangerous, very exciting, and played on broom\-sticks. Harry happened to be a very good Quidditch player; he had been the youngest person in a century to be picked for one of the Hogwarts House teams. One of Harry\rquote s most prized possessions was his Nimbus Two Thousand racing broom.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry put the leather case aside and picked up his last parcel. He recognized the untidy scrawl on the brown paper at once: this was from Hagrid, the Hogwarts gamekeeper. He tore off the top layer of paper and glimpsed something green and leathery, but be\-fore he could unwrap it properly, the parcel gave a strange quiver, and whatever was inside it snapped loudly \emdash  as though it had jaws.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry froze. He knew that Hagrid would never send him any\-thing dangerous on purpose, but then, Hagrid didn\rquote t have a normal person\rquote s view of what was dangerous. Hagrid had been known to befriend giant spiders, buy vicious, three-headed dogs from men in pubs, and sneak illegal dragon eggs into his cabin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry poked the parcel nervously. It snapped loudly again. Harry reached for the lamp on his bedside table, gripped it firmly in one hand, and raised it over his head, ready to strike. Then he seized the rest of the wrapping paper in his other hand and pulled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And out fell \emdash  a book. Harry just had time to register its hand\-some green cover, emblazoned with the golden title \i The Monster Book of Monsters, \i0 before it flipped onto its edge and scuttled side\-ways along the bed like some weird crab.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Uh-oh,\rdblquote  Harry muttered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The book toppled off the bed with a loud clunk and shuffled rapidly across the room. Harry followed it stealthily. The book was hiding in the dark space under his desk. Praying that the Dursleys were still fast asleep, Harry got down on his hands and knees and reached toward it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ouch!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The book snapped shut on his hand and then flapped past him, still scuttling on its covers. Harry scrambled around, threw himself forward, and managed to flatten it. Uncle Vernon gave a loud, sleepy grunt in the room next door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hedwig and Errol watched interestedly as Harry clamped the struggling book tightly in his arms, hurried to his chest of drawers, and pulled out a belt, which he buckled tightly around it. The \i Monster Book \i0 shuddered angrily, but could no longer flap and snap, so Harry threw it down on the bed and reached for Hagrid\rquote s card.\par
\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Dear\lang3081  Harry,\par
\lang1033 Happy birthday!\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Think you might find this\lang3081  useful for next \lang1033  year.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Won\rquote t say no more here. Tell you when I see you.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hope the Muggles are treating you right.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 All the best,\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i0\par
It struck Harry as ominous that Hagrid thought a biting book would come in useful, but he put Hagrid\rquote s card up next to Ron\rquote s and Hermione\rquote s, grinning more broadly than ever. Now there was only the letter from Hogwarts left.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Noticing that it was rather thicker than usual, Harry slit open the envelope, pulled out the first page of parchment within, and read:\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033\i Dear Mr. Potter,\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Please note that the new school year will begin on Septem\-ber the first. The Hogwarts Express will leave from King\rquote s Cross station, platform nine and three-quarters, at eleven o\rquote clock.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Third years are permitted to visit the village of Hogsmeade on certain weekends. Please give the enclosed permission form to your parent or guardian to sign.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i A list of books for next year is enclosed.\par
Yours sincerely,\par
Professor M. McGonagall\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Deputy Headmistress\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\par
Harry pulled out the Hogsmeade permission form and looked at it, no longer grinning. It would be wonderful to visit Hogsmeade on weekends; he knew it was an entirely wizarding village, and he had never set foot there. But how on earth was he going to per\-suade Uncle Vernon or Aunt Petunia to sign the form?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked over at the alarm clock. It was now two o\rquote clock in the morning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Deciding that he\rquote d worry about the Hogsmeade form when he woke up, Harry got back into bed and reached up to cross off an\-other day on the chart he\rquote d made for himself, counting down the days left until his return to Hogwarts. Then he took off his glasses and lay down, eyes open, facing his three birthday cards.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Extremely unusual though he was, at that moment Harry Potter felt just like everyone else \emdash  glad, for the first time in his life, that it was his birthday.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\fs36\page Chapter 2\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc Aunt Marge\rquote s Big Mistake\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\fs24\par
Harry went down to breakfast the next morning to find the three Dursleys already sitting around the kitchen table. They were watching a brand-new television, a welcome-home-for-the-summer present for Dudley, who had been complaining loudly about the long walk between the fridge and the television in the liv\-ing room. Dudley had spent most of the summer in the kitchen, his piggy little eyes fixed on the screen and his five chins wobbling as he ate continually.\par
Harry sat down between Dudley and Uncle Vernon, a large, beefy man with very little neck and a lot of mustache. Far from wishing Harry a happy birthday, none of the Dursleys made any sign that they had noticed Harry enter the room, but Harry was far too used to this to care. He helped himself to a piece of toast and then looked up at the reporter on the television, who was halfway through a report on an escaped convict:\lang3081\par
