\lang1033 Harry, whose thoughts had been upstairs with the Broomstick Servicing Kit, was brought back to earth with an unpleasant bump.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aunt Marge?\rdblquote  he blurted out. \ldblquote Sh \emdash  \i she\rquote s\i0  not coming here, is she?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Aunt Marge was Uncle Vernon\rquote s sister. Even though she was not a blood relative of Harry\rquote s (whose mother had been Aunt Petunia\rquote s sister), he had been forced to call her \ldblquote Aunt\rdblquote  all his life. Aunt Marge lived in the country, in a house with a large garden, where she bred bulldogs. She didn\rquote t often stay at Privet Drive, because she couldn\rquote t bear to leave her precious dogs, but each of her visits stood out horribly vividly in Harry\rquote s mind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At Dudley\rquote s fifth birthday party, Aunt Marge had whacked Harry around the shins with her walking stick to stop him from beating Dudley at musical statues. A few years later, she had turned up at Christmas with a computerized robot for Dudley and a box of dog biscuits for Harry. On her last visit, the year before Harry started at Hogwarts, Harry had accidentally trodden on the tail of her favorite dog. Ripper had chased Harry out into the garden and up a tree, and Aunt Marge had refused to call him off until past midnight. The memory of this incident still brought tears of laugh\-ter to Dudley\rquote s eyes.\lang3081\par
