\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\fs24\par
Harry was several streets away before he collapsed onto a low wall in Magnolia Crescent, panting from the effort of dragging his trunk. He sat quite still, anger still surging through him, listening to the frantic thumping of his heart.\par
But after ten minutes alone in the dark street, a new emotion overtook him: panic. Whichever way he looked at it, he had never been in a worse fix. He was stranded, quite alone, in the dark Mug\-gle world, with absolutely nowhere to go. And the worst of it was, he had just done serious magic, which meant that he was almost certainly expelled from Hogwarts. He had broken the Decree for the Restriction of Underage Wizardry so badly, he was surprised Ministry of Magic representatives weren\rquote t swooping down on him where he sat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry shivered and looked up and down Magnolia Crescent. What was going to happen to him? Would he be arrested, or would\lang3081  \lang1033 he simply be outlawed from the wizarding world? He thought of Ron and Hermione, and his heart sank even lower. Harry was sure that, criminal or not, Ron and Hermione would want to help him now, but they were both abroad, and with Hedwig gone, he had no means of contacting them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He didn\rquote t have any Muggle money, either. There was a little wiz\-ard gold in the money bag at the bottom of his trunk, but the rest of the fortune his parents had left him was stored in a vault at Gringotts Wizarding Bank in London. He\rquote d never be able to drag his trunk all the way to London. Unless \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked down at his wand, which he was still clutching in his hand. If he was already expelled (his heart was now thumping painfully fast), a bit more magic couldn\rquote t hurt. He had the Invisi\-bility Cloak he had inherited from his father \emdash  what if he bewitched the trunk to make it feather-light, tied it to his broom\-stick, covered himself in the cloak, and flew to London? Then he could get the rest of his money out of his vault and \'85 begin his life as an outcast. It was a horrible prospect, but he couldn\rquote t sit on this wall forever, or he\rquote d find himself trying to explain to Muggle police why he was out in the dead of night with a trunkful of spell\-books and a broomstick.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry opened his trunk again and pushed the contents aside, looking for the Invisibility Cloak \emdash  but before he had found it, he straightened up suddenly, looking around him once more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A funny prickling on the back of his neck had made Harry feel he was being watched, but the street appeared to be deserted, and no lights shone from any of the large square houses.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He bent over his trunk again, but almost immediately stood up once more, his hand clenched on his wand. He had sensed rather\lang3081  \lang1033 than heard it: someone or something was standing in the narrow gap between the garage and the fence behind him. Harry squinted at the black alleyway. If only it would move, then he\rquote d know whether it was just a stray cat or \emdash  something else.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Lumos,\i0\rdblquote  Harry muttered, and a light appeared at the end of his wand, almost dazzling him. He held it high over his head, and the pebble-dashed walls of number two suddenly sparkled; the garage door gleamed, and between them Harry saw, quite distinctly, the hulking outline of something very big, with wide, gleaming eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stepped backward. His legs hit his trunk and he tripped. His wand flew out of his hand as he flung out an arm to break his fall, and he landed, hard, in the gutter \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a deafening BANG, and Harry threw up his hands to shield his eyes against a sudden blinding light \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With a yell, he rolled back onto the pavement, just in time. A second later, a gigantic pair of wheels and headlights screeched to a halt exactly where Harry had just been lying. They belonged, as Harry saw when he raised his head, to a triple-decker, violently purple bus, which had appeared out of thin air. Gold lettering over the windshield spelled \i The Knight Bus.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 For a split second, Harry wondered if he had been knocked silly by his fall. Then a conductor in a purple uniform leapt out of the bus and began to speak loudly to the night.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Welcome to the Knight Bus, emergency transport for the stranded witch or wizard. Just stick out your wand hand, step on board, and we can take you anywhere you want to go. My name is Stan Shunpike, and I will be your conductor this eve \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The conductor stopped abruptly. He had just caught sight of Harry, who was still sitting on the ground. Harry snatched up his\lang3081  \lang1033 wand again and scrambled to his feet. Close up, he saw that Stan Shunpike was only a few years older than he was, eighteen or nine\-teen at most, with large, protruding ears and quite a few pimples.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What were you doin\rquote  down there?\rdblquote  said Stan, dropping his pro\-fessional manner.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fell over,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\ldblquote  \rquote\lang1033 Choo fall over for?\rdblquote  sniggered Stan.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t do it on purpose,\rdblquote  said Harry, annoyed. One of the knees in his jeans was torn, and the hand he had thrown out to break his fall was bleeding. He suddenly remembered why he had fallen over and turned around quickly to stare at the alleyway be\-tween the garage and fence. The Knight Bus\rquote s headlamps were flooding it with light, and it was empty.\lang3081\par
\ldblquote  \rquote\lang1033 Choo lookin\rquote  at?\rdblquote  said Stan.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There was a big black thing,\rdblquote  said Harry, pointing uncertainly into the gap. \ldblquote Like a dog \'85 but massive \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked around at Stan, whose mouth was slightly open. With a feeling of unease, Harry saw Stan\rquote s eyes move to the scar on Harry\rquote s forehead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Woss that on your \rquote ead?\rdblquote  said Stan abruptly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly, flattening his hair over his scar. If the Ministry of Magic was looking for him, he didn\rquote t want to make it too easy for them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Woss your name?\rdblquote  Stan persisted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Neville Longbottom,\rdblquote  said Harry, saying the first name that came into his head. \ldblquote So \emdash  so this bus,\rdblquote  he went on quickly, hop\-ing to distract Stan, \ldblquote did you say it goes \i anywhere\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yep,\rdblquote  said Stan proudly, \ldblquote anywhere you like, long\rquote s it\rquote s on land. Can\rquote t do nuffink underwater. \rquote Ere,\rdblquote  he said, looking suspicious\lang3081  \lang1033 again, \ldblquote you \i did \i0 flag us down, dincha? Stuck out your wand \rquote and, dincha?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly. \ldblquote Listen, how much would it be to get to London?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Eleven Sickles,\rdblquote  said Stan, \ldblquote but for firteen you get \rquote ot chocolate, and for fifteen you get an \rquote ot water bottle an\rquote  a toofbrush in the color of your choice.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry rummaged once more in his trunk, extracted his money bag, and shoved some gold into Stan\rquote s hand. He and Stan then lifted his trunk, with Hedwig\rquote s cage balanced on top, up the steps of the bus.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There were no seats; instead, half a dozen brass bedsteads stood beside the curtained windows. Candles were burning in brackets beside each bed, illuminating the wood-paneled walls. A tiny wiz\-ard in a nightcap at the rear of the bus muttered, \ldblquote Not now, thanks, I\rquote m pickling some slugs\rdblquote  and rolled over in his sleep.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You \rquote ave this one,\rdblquote  Stan whispered, shoving Harry\rquote s trunk un\-der the bed right behind the driver, who was sitting in an armchair in front of the steering wheel. \ldblquote This is our driver, Ernie Prang. This is Neville Longbottom, Ern.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ernie Prang, an elderly wizard wearing very thick glasses, nod\-ded to Harry, who nervously flattened his bangs again and sat down on his bed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Take \rquote er away, Ern,\rdblquote  said Stan, sitting down in the armchair next to Ernie\rquote s.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was another tremendous BANG, and the next moment Harry found himself flat on his bed, thrown backward by the speed of the Knight Bus. Pulling himself up, Harry stared out of the dark window and saw that they were now bowling along a\lang3081  \lang1033 completely different street. Stan was watching Harry\rquote s stunned face with great enjoyment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is where we was before you flagged us down,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Where are we, Ern? Somewhere in Wales?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ar,\rdblquote  said Ernie.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How come the Muggles don\rquote t hear the bus?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Them!\rdblquote  said Stan contemptuously. \ldblquote Don\rquote  listen properly, do they? Don\rquote  look properly either. Never notice nuffink, they don\rquote .\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Best go wake up Madam Marsh, Stan,\rdblquote  said Ern. \ldblquote We\rquote ll be in Abergavenny in a minute.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Stan passed Harry\rquote s bed and disappeared up a narrow wooden staircase. Harry was still looking out of the window, feeling in\-creasingly nervous. Ernie didn\rquote t seem to have mastered the use of a steering wheel. The Knight Bus kept mounting the pavement, but it didn\rquote t hit anything; lines of lampposts, mailboxes, and trash cans jumped out of its way as it approached and back into position once it had passed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Stan came back downstairs, followed by a faintly green witch wrapped in a traveling cloak.\lang3081\par
\ldblquote  \rquote\lang1033 Ere you go, Madam Marsh,\rdblquote  said Stan happily as Ern stamped on the brake and the beds slid a foot or so toward the front of the bus. Madam Marsh clamped a handkerchief to her mouth and tot\-tered down the steps. Stan threw her bag out after her and rammed the doors shut; there was another loud BANG, and they were thun\-dering down a narrow country lane, trees leaping out of the way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry wouldn\rquote t have been able to sleep even if he had been trav\-eling on a bus that didn\rquote t keep banging loudly and jumping a hun\-dred miles at a time. His stomach churned as he fell back to\lang3081  \lang1033 wondering what was going to happen to him, and whether the Dursleys had managed to get Aunt Marge off the ceiling yet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Stan had unfurled a copy of the \i Daily Prophet\i0  and was now read\-ing with his tongue between his teeth. A large photograph of a sunken-faced man with long, matted hair blinked slowly at Harry from the front page. He looked strangely familiar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That man!\rdblquote  Harry said, forgetting his troubles for a moment. \ldblquote He was on the Muggle news!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Stanley turned to the front page and chuckled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sirius Black,\rdblquote  he said, nodding. \lang3081\ldblquote  \rquote\lang1033 Course\lang3081  \rquote\lang1033 e was on the Muggle news, Neville, where you been?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He gave a superior sort of chuckle at the blank look on Harry\rquote s face, removed the front page, and handed it to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You oughta read the papers more, Neville.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry held the paper up to the candlelight and read:\lang3081\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc\lang1033 BLACK STILL AT LARGE\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033 Sirius Black, possibly the most infamous prisoner ever to be held in Azkaban fortress, is still eluding capture, the Ministry of Magic confirmed today.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We are doing all we can to recapture Black,\rdblquote  said the Minister of Magic, Cornelius Fudge, this morning, \ldblquote and we beg the magical community to remain calm.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge has been criticized by some members of the International Federation of Warlocks for in\-forming the Muggle Prime Minister of the crisis.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, really, I had to, don\rquote t you know,\rdblquote  said an\lang3081  \lang1033 irritable Fudge. \ldblquote Black is mad. He\rquote s a danger to anyone who crosses him, magic or Muggle. I have the Prime Minister\rquote s assurance that he will not breathe a word of Black\rquote s true identity to anyone. And let\rquote s face it \emdash  who\rquote d believe him if he did?\rdblquote\par
While Muggles have been told that Black is car\-rying a gun (a kind of metal wand that Muggles use to kill each other), the magical community lives in fear of a massacre like that of twelve years ago, when Black murdered thirteen people with a single curse.\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 Harry looked into the shadowed eyes of Sirius Black, the only part of the sunken face that seemed alive. Harry had never met a vampire, but he had seen pictures of them in his Defense Against the Dark Arts classes, and Black, with his waxy white skin, looked just like one.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Scary-lookin\rquote  fing, inee?\rdblquote  said Stan, who had been watching Harry read.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He murdered \i thirteen people\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Harry, handing the page back to Stan, \ldblquote with \i one curse\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yep,\rdblquote  said Stan, \ldblquote in front of witnesses an\rquote  all. Broad daylight. Big trouble it caused, dinnit, Ern?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ar,\rdblquote  said Ern darkly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Stan swiveled in his armchair, his hands on the back, the better to look at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Black woz a big supporter of You-Know-\rquote Oo,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What, Voldemort?\rdblquote  said Harry, without thinking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Even Stan\rquote s pimples went white; Ern jerked the steering wheel\lang3081  \lang1033 so hard that a whole farmhouse had to jump aside to avoid the bus.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You outta your tree?\rdblquote  yelped Stan. \ldblquote  \rquote Choo say \rquote is name for?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  said Harry hastily. \ldblquote Sorry, I \emdash  I forgot \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Forgot!\rdblquote  said Stan weakly. \ldblquote Blimey, my \rquote eart\rquote s goin\rquote  that fast \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So \emdash  so Black was a supporter of You-Know-Who?\rdblquote  Harry prompted apologetically.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Stan, still rubbing his chest. \ldblquote Yeah, that\rquote s right. Very close to You-Know-\rquote Oo, they say. Anyway, when little \rquote Arry Potter got the better of You-Know-\rquote Oo \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry nervously flattened his bangs down again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  all You-Know-\rquote Oo\rquote s supporters was tracked down, wasn\rquote t they, Ern? Most of \rquote em knew it was all over, wiv You-Know-\rquote Oo gone, and they came quiet. But not Sirius Black. I \rquote eard he thought \rquote e\rquote d be second-in-command once You-Know-\rquote Oo \rquote ad taken over.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anyway, they cornered Black in the middle of a street full of Muggles an\rquote  Black took out \rquote is wand and \rquote e blasted \rquote alf the street apart, an\rquote  a wizard got it, an\rquote  so did a dozen Muggles what got in the way. \rquote Orrible, eh? An\rquote  you know what Black did then?\rdblquote  Stan continued in a dramatic whisper.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Laughed\i0 ,\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 said Stan. \ldblquote Jus\rquote  stood there an\rquote  laughed. An\rquote  when re\-inforcements from the Ministry of Magic got there, \rquote e went wiv \rquote em quiet as anyfink, still laughing \rquote is \rquote ead off. \rquote Cos \rquote e\rquote s mad, inee, Ern? Inee mad?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If he weren\rquote t when he went to Azkaban, he will be now,\rdblquote  said\lang3081  \lang1033 Ern in his slow voice. \ldblquote I\rquote d blow meself up before I set foot in that place. Serves him right, mind you \'85 after what he did. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They \rquote ad a job coverin\rquote  it up, din\rquote  they, Ern?\rdblquote  Stan said. \ldblquote  \rquote Ole street blown up an\rquote  all them Muggles dead. What was it they said \rquote ad \rquote appened, Ern?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Gas explosion,\rdblquote  grunted Ernie.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote An\rquote  now \rquote e\rquote s out,\rdblquote  said Stan, examining the newspaper pic\-ture of Black\rquote s gaunt face again. \ldblquote Never been a breakout from Azkaban before, \rquote as there, Ern? Beats me \rquote ow \rquote e did it. Frightenin\rquote , eh? Mind, I don\rquote t fancy \rquote is chances against them Azkaban guards, eh, Ern?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ernie suddenly shivered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Talk about summat else, Stan, there\rquote s a good lad. Them Azka\-ban guards give me the collywobbles.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Stan put the paper away reluctantly, and Harry leaned against the window of the Knight Bus, feeling worse than ever. He couldn\rquote t help imagining what Stan might be telling his passengers in a few nights\rquote  time.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Ear about that \rquote Arry Potter? Blew up \rquote is aunt! We \rquote ad \rquote im \rquote ere on the Knight Bus, di\rquote n\rquote t we, Ern? \rquote E was tryin\rquote  to run for it. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He, Harry, had broken wizard law just like Sirius Black. Was in\-flating Aunt Marge bad enough to land him in Azkaban? Harry didn\rquote t know anything about the wizard prison, though everyone he\rquote d ever heard speak of it did so in the same fearful tone. Hagrid, the Hogwarts gamekeeper, had spent two months there only last year. Harry wouldn\rquote t soon forget the look of terror on Hagrid\rquote s face when he had been told where he was going, and Hagrid was one of the bravest people Harry knew.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Knight Bus rolled through the darkness, scattering bushes and wastebaskets, telephone booths and trees, and Harry lay, restless and miserable, on his feather bed. After a while, Stan remembered that Harry had paid for hot chocolate, but poured it all over Harry\rquote s pillow when the bus moved abruptly from Angle\-sey to Aberdeen. One by one, wizards and witches in dressing gowns and slippers descended from the upper floors to leave the bus. They all looked very pleased to go.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Finally, Harry was the only passenger left.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right then, Neville,\rdblquote  said Stan, clapping his hands, \ldblquote where\-abouts in London?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Diagon Alley,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Righto,\rdblquote  said Stan. \ldblquote  \rquote Old tight, then \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 BANG!\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were thundering along Charing Cross Road. Harry sat up and watched buildings and benches squeezing themselves out of the Knight Bus\rquote s way. The sky was getting a little lighter. He would lie low for a couple of hours, go to Gringotts the moment it opened, then set off\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  where, he didn\rquote t know.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ern slammed on the brakes and the Knight Bus skidded to a halt in front of a small and shabby-looking pub, the Leaky Cauldron, behind which lay the magical entrance to Diagon Alley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  Harry said to Ern.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He jumped down the steps and helped Stan lower his trunk and Hedwig\rquote s cage onto the pavement.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote  \rquote Bye then!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Stan wasn\rquote t paying attention. Still standing in the doorway to the bus, he was goggling at the shadowy entrance to the Leaky Cauldron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i There\i0  you are, Harry,\rdblquote  said a voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Before Harry could turn, he felt a hand on his shoulder. At the same time, Stan shouted, \ldblquote Blimey! Ern, come \rquote ere! Come \i\rquote ere\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked up at the owner of the hand on his shoulder and felt a bucketful of ice cascade into his stomach \emdash  he had walked right into Cornelius Fudge, the Minister of Magic himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Stan leapt onto the pavement beside them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What didja call Neville, Minister?\rdblquote  he said excitedly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge, a portly little man in a long, pinstriped cloak, looked cold and exhausted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Neville?\rdblquote  he repeated, frowning. \ldblquote This is Harry Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I knew it!\rdblquote  Stan shouted gleefully. \ldblquote Ern! Ern! Guess \rquote oo Neville is, Ern! \rquote E\rquote s \rquote Arry Potter! I can see \rquote is scar!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Fudge testily, \ldblquote well, I\rquote m very glad the Knight Bus picked Harry up, but he and I need to step inside the Leaky Caul\-dron now \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge increased the pressure on Harry\rquote s shoulder, and Harry found himself being steered inside the pub. A stooping figure bear\-ing a lantern appeared through the door behind the bar. It was Tom, the wizened, toothless landlord.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ve got him, Minister!\rdblquote  said Tom. \ldblquote Will you be wanting anything? Beer? Brandy?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Perhaps a pot of tea,\rdblquote  said Fudge, who still hadn\rquote t let go of Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a loud scraping and puffing from behind them, and Stan and Ern appeared, carrying Harry\rquote s trunk and Hedwig\rquote s cage and looking around excitedly.\lang3081\par
\ldblquote  \rquote\lang1033 Ow come you di\rquote n\rquote t tell us \rquote oo you are, eh, Neville?\rdblquote  said Stan,\lang3081  \lang1033 beaming at Harry, while Ernie\rquote s owlish face peered interestedly over Stan\rquote s shoulder.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And a\lang3081  \lang1033\i private\i0  parlor, please, Tom,\rdblquote  said Fudge pointedly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Bye,\rdblquote  Harry said miserably to Stan and Ern as Tom beckoned Fudge toward the passage that led from the bar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Bye, Neville!\rdblquote  called Stan.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge marched Harry along the narrow passage after Tom\rquote s lantern, and then into a small parlor. Tom clicked his fingers, a fire burst into life in the grate, and he bowed himself out of the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sit down, Harry,\rdblquote  said Fudge, indicating a chair by the fire.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry sat down, feeling goose bumps rising up his arms despite the glow of the fire. Fudge took off his pinstriped cloak and tossed it aside, then hitched up the trousers of his bottle-green suit and sat down opposite Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am Cornelius Fudge, Harry. The Minister of Magic.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry already knew this, of course; he had seen Fudge once be\-fore, but as he had been wearing his father\rquote s Invisibility Cloak at the time, Fudge wasn\rquote t to know that.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Tom the innkeeper reappeared, wearing an apron over his night\-shirt and bearing a tray of tea and crumpets. He placed the tray on a table between Fudge and Harry and left the parlor, closing the door behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Harry,\rdblquote  said Fudge, pouring out tea, \ldblquote you\rquote ve had us all in a right flap, I don\rquote t mind telling you. Running away from your aunt and uncle\rquote s house like that! I\rquote d started to think \'85 but you\rquote re safe, and that\rquote s what matters.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge buttered himself a crumpet and pushed the plate toward Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Eat, Harry, you look dead on your feet. Now then \'85 You will be pleased to hear that we have dealt with the unfortunate blowing-up of Miss Marjorie Dursley. Two members of the Ac\-cidental Magic Reversal Squad were dispatched to Privet Drive a few hours ago. Miss Dursley has been punctured and her memory has been modified. She has no recollection of the incident at all. So that\rquote s that, and no harm done.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge smiled at Harry over the rim of his teacup, rather like an uncle surveying a favorite nephew. Harry, who couldn\rquote t believe his ears, opened his mouth to speak, couldn\rquote t think of anything to say, and closed it again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, you\rquote re worrying about the reaction of your aunt and un\-cle?\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote Well, I won\rquote t deny that they are extremely angry, Harry, but they are prepared to take you back next summer as long as you stay at Hogwarts for the Christmas and Easter holidays.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry unstuck his throat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \i always \i0 stay at Hogwarts for the Christmas and Easter holi\-days,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote and I don\rquote t ever want to go back to Privet Drive.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, now, I\rquote m sure you\rquote ll feel differently once you\rquote ve calmed down,\rdblquote  said Fudge in a worried tone. \ldblquote They are your family, after all, and I\rquote m sure you are fond of each other \emdash  er \emdash  \i very\i0  deep down.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It didn\rquote t occur to Harry to put Fudge right. He was still waiting to hear what was going to happen to him now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So all that remains,\rdblquote  said Fudge, now buttering himself a sec\-ond crumpet, \ldblquote is to decide where you\rquote re going to spend the last three weeks of your vacation. I suggest you take a room here at the Leaky Cauldron and \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Hang on,\rdblquote  blurted Harry. \ldblquote What about my punishment?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge blinked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Punishment?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I broke the law!\rdblquote  Harry said. \ldblquote The Decree for the Restriction of Underage Wizardry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, my dear boy, we\rquote re not going to punish you for a little thing like that!\rdblquote  cried Fudge, waving his crumpet impatiently. \ldblquote It was an accident! We don\rquote t send people to Azkaban just for blowing up their aunts!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But this didn\rquote t tally at all with Harry\rquote s past dealings with the Ministry of Magic.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Last year, I got an official warning just because a house-elf smashed a pudding in my uncle\rquote s house!\rdblquote  he told Fudge, frowning. \ldblquote The Ministry of Magic said I\rquote d be expelled from Hogwarts if there was any more magic there!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Unless Harry\rquote s eyes were deceiving him, Fudge was suddenly looking awkward.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Circumstances change, Harry. \'85 We have to take into ac\-count \'85 in the present climate \'85 Surely you don\rquote t \i want\i0  to be ex\-pelled?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course I don\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well then, what\rquote s all the fuss about?\rdblquote  laughed Fudge. \ldblquote Now, have a crumpet, Harry, while I go and see if Tom\rquote s got a room for you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge strode out of the parlor and Harry stared after him. There was something extremely odd going on. Why had Fudge been waiting for him at the Leaky Cauldron, if not to punish him for what he\rquote d done? And now Harry came to think of it, surely it wasn\rquote t\lang3081  \lang1033 usual for the Minister of Magic \i himself\i0  to get involved in matters of underage magic?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge came back, accompanied by Tom the innkeeper.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Room eleven\rquote s free, Harry,\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote I think you\rquote ll be very comfortable. Just one thing, and I\rquote m sure you\rquote ll understand \'85 I don\rquote t want you wandering off into Muggle London, all right? Keep to Diagon Alley. And you\rquote re to be back here before dark each night. Sure you\rquote ll understand. Tom will be keeping an eye on you for me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  said Harry slowly, \ldblquote but why \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t want to lose you again, do we?\rdblquote  said Fudge with a hearty laugh. \ldblquote No, no \'85 best we know where you are. \'85 I mean \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge cleared his throat loudly and picked up his pinstriped cloak.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I\rquote ll be off, plenty to do, you know. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Have you had any luck with Black yet?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge\rquote s finger slipped on the silver fastenings of his cloak.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s that? Oh, you\rquote ve heard \emdash  well, no, not yet, but it\rquote s only a matter of time. The Azkaban guards have never yet failed \'85 and they are angrier than I\rquote ve ever seen them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge shuddered slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, I\rquote ll say good-bye.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He held out his hand and Harry, shaking it, had a sudden idea.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  Minister? Can I ask you something?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Certainly,\rdblquote  said Fudge with a smile.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, third years at Hogwarts are allowed to visit Hogsmeade, but my aunt and uncle didn\rquote t sign the permission form. D\rquote you think you could \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge was looking uncomfortable.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote No, no, I\rquote m very sorry, Harry, but as I\rquote m not your parent or guardian \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But you\rquote re the Minister of Magic,\rdblquote  said Harry eagerly. \ldblquote If you gave me permission \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I\rquote m sorry, Harry, but rules are rules,\rdblquote  said Fudge flatly. \ldblquote Perhaps you\rquote ll be able to visit Hogsmeade next year. In fact, I think it\rquote s best if you don\rquote t\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 yes \'85 well, I\rquote ll be off. Enjoy your stay, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And with a last smile and shake of Harry\rquote s hand, Fudge left the room. Tom now moved forward, beaming at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If you\rquote ll follow me, Mr. Potter,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote I\rquote ve already taken your things up. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry followed Tom up a handsome wooden staircase to a door with a brass number eleven on it, which Tom unlocked and opened for him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Inside was a very comfortable-looking bed, some highly pol\-ished oak furniture, a cheerfully crackling fire and, perched on top of the wardrobe \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hedwig!\rdblquote  Harry gasped.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The snowy owl clicked her beak and fluttered down onto Harry\rquote s arm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very smart owl you\rquote ve got there,\rdblquote  chuckled Tom. \ldblquote Arrived about five minutes after you did. If there\rquote s anything you need, Mr. Potter, don\rquote t hesitate to ask.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He gave another bow and left.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry sat on his bed for a long time, absentmindedly stroking Hedwig. The sky outside the window was changing rapidly from deep, velvety blue to cold, steely gray and then, slowly, to pink shot\lang3081  \lang1033 with gold. Harry could hardly believe that he\rquote d left Privet Drive only a few hours ago, that he wasn\rquote t expelled, and that he was now facing three Dursley-free weeks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s been a very weird night, Hedwig,\rdblquote  he yawned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And without even removing his glasses, he slumped back onto his pillows and fell asleep.\lang3081\par
