\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\fs24\par
It took Harry several days to get used to his strange new freedom. Never before had he been able to get up whenever he wanted or eat whatever he fancied. He could even go wherever he pleased, as long as it was in Diagon Alley, and as this long cobbled street was packed with the most fascinating wizarding shops in the world, Harry felt no desire to break his word to Fudge and stray back into the Muggle world.\par
Harry ate breakfast each morning in the Leaky Cauldron, where he liked watching the other guests: funny little witches from the country, up for a day\rquote s shopping; venerable-looking wizards argu\-ing over the latest article in \i Transfiguration Today\i0 ; wild-looking warlocks; raucous dwarfs; and once, what looked suspiciously like a hag, who ordered a plate of raw liver from behind a thick woollen balaclava.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After breakfast Harry would go out into the backyard, take out\lang3081  \lang1033 his wand, tap the third brick from the left above the trash bin, and stand back as the archway into Diagon Alley opened in the wall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry spent the long sunny days exploring the shops and eating under the brightly colored umbrellas outside cafes, where his fellow diners were showing one another their purchases (\lang3081\ldblquote\lang1033 it\rquote s a lunascope, old boy \emdash  no more messing around with moon charts, see?\lang3081\rdblquote\lang1033 ) or else discussing the case of Sirius Black (\lang3081\ldblquote\lang1033 personally, I won\rquote t let any of the children out alone until he\rquote s back in Azkaban\lang3081\rdblquote\lang1033 ). Harry didn\rquote t have to do his homework under the blankets by flashlight any\-more; now he could sit in the bright sunshine outside Florean Fortescue\rquote s Ice Cream Parlor, finishing all his essays with occasional help from Florean Fortescue himself, who, apart from knowing a great deal about medieval witch burnings, gave Harry free sundaes every half an hour.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Once Harry had refilled his money bag with gold Galleons, sil\-ver Sickles, and bronze Knuts from his vault at Gringotts, he had to exercise a lot of self-control not to spend the whole lot at once. He had to keep reminding himself that he had five years to go at Hog\-warts, and how it would feel to ask the Dursleys for money for spellbooks, to stop himself from buying a handsome set of solid gold Gobstones (a wizarding game rather like marbles, in which the stones squirt a nasty-smelling liquid into the other player\rquote s face when they lose a point). He was sorely tempted, too, by the perfect, moving model of the galaxy in a large glass ball, which would have meant he never had to take another Astronomy lesson. But the thing that tested Harry\rquote s resolution most appeared in his favorite shop, Quality Quidditch Supplies, a week after he\rquote d arrived at the Leaky Cauldron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Curious to know what the crowd in the shop was staring at, Harry edged his way inside and squeezed in among the excited witches and wizards until he glimpsed a newly erected podium, on which was mounted the most magnificent broom he had ever seen in his life.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Just come out \emdash  prototype \emdash\rdblquote  a square-jawed wizard was telling his companion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s the fastest broom in the world, isn\rquote t it, Dad?\rdblquote  squeaked a boy younger than Harry, who was swinging off his father\rquote s arm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Irish International Side\rquote s just put in an order for seven of these beauties!\rdblquote  the proprietor of the shop told the crowd. \ldblquote And they\rquote re favorites for the World Cup!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A large witch in front of Harry moved, and he was able to read the sign next to the broom:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc\lang3081 THE FIREBOLT\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\i This state-of-the-art racing broom sports a stream-lined, superfine handle of ash, treated with a diamond-hard polish and hand-numbered with its own registration number. Each individually selected birch twig in the broomtail has been honed to aerodynamic perfection, giving the Firebolt unsurpassable balance and pinpoint precision. The Firebolt has an acceleration of 150 miles an hour in ten seconds and incorporates an unbreakable Braking Charm. Price on request.\par
\i0\par
\lang1033 Price on request \'85 Harry didn\rquote t like to think how much gold the Firebolt would cost. He had never wanted anything as much in his\lang3081  \lang1033 whole life \emdash  but he had never lost a Quidditch match on his Nim\-bus Two Thousand, and what was the point in emptying his Gringotts vault for the Firebolt, when he had a very good broom already? Harry didn\rquote t ask for the price, but he returned, almost every day after that, just to look at the Firebolt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There were, however, things that Harry needed to buy. He went to the Apothecary to replenish his store of potions ingredients, and as his school robes were now several inches too short in the arm and leg, he visited Madam Malkin\rquote s Robes for All Occasions and bought new ones. Most important of all, he had to buy his new schoolbooks, which would include those for his two new subjects, Care of Magical Creatures and Divination.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry got a surprise as he looked in at the bookshop window. Instead of the usual display of gold-embossed spellbooks the size of paving slabs, there was a large iron cage behind the glass that held about a hundred copies of \i The Monster Book of Monsters.\i0  Torn pages were flying everywhere as the books grappled with each other, locked together in furious wrestling matches and snapping aggressively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry pulled his booklist out of his pocket and consulted it for the first time. \i The Monster Book of Monsters\i0  was listed as the re\-quired book for Care of Magical Creatures. Now Harry under\-stood why Hagrid had said it would come in useful. He felt relieved; he had been wondering whether Hagrid wanted help with some terrifying new pet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As Harry entered Flourish and Blotts, the manager came hurry\-ing toward him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hogwarts?\rdblquote  he said abruptly. \ldblquote Come to get your new books?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote I need \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get out of the way,\rdblquote  said the manager impatiently, brushing Harry aside. He drew on a pair of very thick gloves, picked up a large, knobbly walking stick, and proceeded toward the door of the \i Monster Books\rquote\i0  cage.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hang on,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly, \ldblquote I\rquote ve already got one of those.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Have you?\rdblquote  A look of enormous relief spread over the manager\rquote s face. \ldblquote Thank heavens for that. I\rquote ve been bitten five times already this morning \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A loud ripping noise rent the air; two of the \i Monster Books\i0  had seized a third and were pulling it apart.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stop it! Stop it!\rdblquote  cried the manager, poking the walking stick through the bars and knocking the books apart. \ldblquote I\rquote m never stocking them again, never! It\rquote s been bedlam! I thought we\rquote d seen the worst when we bought two hundred copies of the \i Invisible Book of Invisi\-bility\i0  \emdash  cost a fortune, and we never found them. \'85 Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 is there anything else I can help you with?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, looking down his booklist, \ldblquote I need \i Unfogging the Future\i0  by Cassandra Vablatsky.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, starting Divination, are you?\rdblquote  said the manager, stripping off his gloves and leading Harry into the back of the shop, where there was a corner devoted to fortune-telling. A small table was stacked with volumes such as \i Predicting the Unpredictable: Insulate Yourself Against Shocks\i0  and \i Broken Balls: When Fortunes Turn Foul.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here you are,\rdblquote  said the manager, who had climbed a set of steps to take down a thick, black-bound book. \ldblquote\i Unfogging the Future.\i0  Very good guide to all your basic fortune-telling methods \emdash  palm\-istry, crystal balls, bird entrails \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Harry wasn\rquote t listening. His eyes had fallen on another book,\lang3081  \lang1033 which was among a display on a small table: \i Death Omens: What to Do When You Know the Worst Is Coming.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I wouldn\rquote t read that if I were you,\rdblquote  said the manager lightly, looking to see what Harry was staring at. \ldblquote You\rquote ll start see\-ing death omens everywhere. It\rquote s enough to frighten anyone to death.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Harry continued to stare at the front cover of the book; it showed a black dog large as a bear, with gleaming eyes. It looked oddly familiar. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The manager pressed \i Unfogging the Future\i0  into Harry\rquote s hands.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anything else?\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, tearing his eyes away from the dog\rquote s and dazedly consulting his booklist. \ldblquote Er \emdash  I need \i Intermediate Trans\-figuration\i0  and \i The Standard Book of Spells, Grade Three.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry emerged from Flourish and Blotts ten minutes later with his new books under his arms and made his way back to the Leaky Cauldron, hardly noticing where he was going and bumping into several people.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He tramped up the stairs to his room, went inside, and tipped his books onto his bed. Somebody had been in to tidy; the win\-dows were open and sun was pouring inside. Harry could hear the buses rolling by in the unseen Muggle street behind him and the sound of the invisible crowd below in Diagon Alley. He caught sight of himself in the mirror over the basin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It can\rquote t have been a death omen,\rdblquote  he told his reflection defi\-antly. \ldblquote I was panicking when I saw that thing in Magnolia Crescent. \'85 It was probably just a stray dog. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He raised his hand automatically and tried to make his hair lie flat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re fighting a losing battle there, dear,\rdblquote  said his mirror in a wheezy voice.\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 As the days slipped by, Harry started looking wherever he went for a sign of Ron or Hermione. Plenty of Hogwarts students were ar\-riving in Diagon Alley now, with the start of term so near. Harry met Seamus Finnigan and Dean Thomas, his fellow Gryffindors, in Quality Quidditch Supplies, where they too were ogling the Fire\-bolt; he also ran into the real Neville Longbottom, a round-faced, forgetful boy, outside Flourish and Blotts. Harry didn\rquote t stop to chat; Neville appeared to have mislaid his booklist and was being told off by his very formidable-looking grandmother. Harry hoped she never found out that he\rquote d pretended to be Neville while on the run from the Ministry of Magic.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry woke on the last day of the holidays, thinking that he would at least meet Ron and Hermione tomorrow, on the Hog\-warts Express. He got up, dressed, went for a last look at the Fire\-bolt, and was just wondering where he\rquote d have lunch, when someone yelled his name and he turned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry! HARRY!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were there, both of them, sitting outside Florean Fortes\-cue\rquote s Ice Cream Parlor \emdash  Ron looking incredibly freckly Her\-mione very brown, both waving frantically at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Finally!\rdblquote  said Ron, grinning at Harry as he sat down. \ldblquote We went to the Leaky Cauldron, but they said you\rquote d left, and we went to Flourish and Blotts, and Madam Malkin\rquote s, and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I got all my school stuff last week,\rdblquote  Harry explained. \ldblquote And how come you knew I\rquote m staying at the Leaky Cauldron?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dad,\rdblquote  said Ron simply.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley, who worked at the Ministry of Magic, would of course have heard the whole story of what had happened to Aunt Marge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you \i really\i0  blow up your aunt, Harry?\rdblquote  said Hermione in a very serious voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t mean to,\rdblquote  said Harry while Ron roared with laughter. \ldblquote I just \emdash  lost control.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s not funny, Ron,\rdblquote  said Hermione sharply. \ldblquote Honestly, I\rquote m amazed Harry wasn\rquote t expelled.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So am I,\rdblquote  admitted Harry. \ldblquote Forget expelled, I thought I was go\-ing to be arrested.\rdblquote  He looked at Ron. \ldblquote Your dad doesn\rquote t know why Fudge let me off, does he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Probably \rquote cause it\rquote s you, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  shrugged Ron, still chuckling. \ldblquote Famous Harry Potter and all that. I\rquote d hate to see what the Min\-istry\rquote d do to \i me\i0  if I blew up an aunt. Mind you, they\rquote d have to dig me up first, because Mum would\rquote ve killed me. Anyway, you can ask Dad yourself this evening. We\rquote re staying at the Leaky Cauldron tonight too! So you can come to King\rquote s Cross with us tomorrow! Hermione\rquote s there as well!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione nodded, beaming. \ldblquote Mum and Dad dropped me off this morning with all my Hogwarts things.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excellent!\rdblquote  said Harry happily. \ldblquote So, have you got all your new books and stuff?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look at this,\rdblquote  said Ron, pulling a long thin box out of a bag and opening it. \ldblquote Brand-new wand. Fourteen inches, willow, con\-taining one unicorn tail-hair. And we\rquote ve got all our books \emdash\rdblquote  He pointed at a large bag under his chair. \ldblquote What about those \i Monster Books,\i0  eh? The assistant nearly cried when we said we wanted two.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s all that, Hermione?\rdblquote  Harry asked, pointing at not one but three bulging bags in the chair next to her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I\rquote m taking more new subjects than you, aren\rquote t I?\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Those are my books for Arithmancy, Care of Magical Creatures, Divination, Study of Ancient Runes, Muggle Studies \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you doing Muggle Studies for?\rdblquote  said Ron, rolling his eyes at Harry. \ldblquote You\rquote re Muggle-born! Your mum and dad are Mug\-gles! You already know all about Muggles!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But it\rquote ll be fascinating to study them from the wizarding point of view,\rdblquote  said Hermione earnestly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you planning to eat or sleep at all this year, Hermione?\rdblquote  asked Harry, while Ron sniggered. Hermione ignored them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve still got ten Galleons,\rdblquote  she said, checking her purse. \ldblquote It\rquote s my birthday in September, and Mum and Dad gave me some money to get myself an early birthday present.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How about a nice \i book\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Ron innocently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I don\rquote t think so,\rdblquote  said Hermione composedly. \ldblquote I really want an owl. I mean, Harry\rquote s got Hedwig and you\rquote ve got Errol \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I haven\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Errol\rquote s a family owl. All I\rquote ve got is Scab\-bers.\rdblquote  He pulled his pet rat out of his pocket. \ldblquote And I want to get him checked over,\rdblquote  he added, placing Scabbers on the table in front of them. \ldblquote I don\rquote t think Egypt agreed with him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Scabbers was looking thinner than usual, and there was a defi\-nite droop to his whiskers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s a magical creature shop just over there,\rdblquote  said Harry, who knew Diagon Alley very well by now. \ldblquote You could see if they\rquote ve got anything for Scabbers, and Hermione can get her owl.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 So they paid for their ice cream and crossed the street to the Magical Menagerie.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There wasn\rquote t much room inside. Every inch of wall was hidden by cages. It was smelly and very noisy because the occupants of these cages were all squeaking, squawking, jabbering, or hissing. The witch behind the counter was already advising a wizard on the care of double-ended newts, so Harry, Ron, and Hermione waited, examining the cages.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A pair of enormous purple toads sat gulping wetly and feasting on dead blowflies. A gigantic tortoise with a jewel-encrusted shell was glittering near the window. Poisonous orange snails were ooz\-ing slowly up the side of their glass tank, and a fat white rabbit kept changing into a silk top hat and back again with a loud popping noise. Then there were cats of every color, a noisy cage of ravens, a basket of funny custard-colored furballs that were humming loudly, and on the counter, a vast cage of sleek black rats that were playing some sort of skipping game using their long, bald tails.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The double-ended newt wizard left, and Ron approached the counter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s my rat,\rdblquote  he told the witch. \ldblquote He been a bit off-color ever since I brought him back from Egypt.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bang him on the counter,\rdblquote  said the witch, pulling a pair of heavy black spectacles out of her pocket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron lifted Scabbers out of his inside pocket and placed him next to the cage of his fellow rats, who stopped their skipping tricks and scuffled to the wire for a better look.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Like nearly everything Ron owned, Scabbers the rat was second\-hand (he had once belonged to Ron\rquote s brother Percy) and a bit\lang3081  \lang1033 battered. Next to the glossy rats in the cage, he looked especially woebegone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hm,\rdblquote  said the witch, picking up Scabbers. \ldblquote How old is this rat?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dunno,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Quite old. He used to belong to my brother.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What powers does he have?\rdblquote  said the witch, examining Scab\-bers closely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash\rdblquote  The truth was that Scabbers had never shown the faintest trace of interesting powers. The witch\rquote s eyes moved from Scabbers\rquote s tattered left ear to his front paw, which had a toe miss\-ing, and tutted loudly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s been through the mill, this one,\rdblquote  she said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He was like that when Percy gave him to me,\rdblquote  said Ron defen\-sively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote An ordinary common or garden rat like this can\rquote t be expected to live longer than three years or so,\rdblquote  said the witch. \ldblquote Now, if you were looking for something a bit more hard-wearing, you might like one of these \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She indicated the black rats, who promptly started skipping again. Ron muttered, \ldblquote Show-offs.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, if you don\rquote t want a replacement, you can try this rat tonic,\rdblquote  said the witch, reaching under the counter and bringing out a small red bottle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote How much \emdash  OUCH!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron buckled as something huge and orange came soaring from the top of the highest cage, landed on his head, and then propelled itself, spitting madly, at Scabbers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote NO, CROOKSHANKS, NO!\rdblquote  cried the witch, but Scabbers shot from between her hands like a bar of soap, landed splay-legged on the floor, and then scampered for the door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Scabbers!\rdblquote  Ron shouted, racing out of the shop after him; Harry followed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It took them nearly ten minutes to catch Scabbers, who had taken refuge under a wastepaper bin outside Quality Quidditch Supplies. Ron stuffed the trembling rat back into his pocket and straightened up, massaging his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What \i was\i0  that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was either a very big cat or quite a small tiger,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where\rquote s Hermione?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Probably getting her owl \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They made their way back up the crowded street to the Magical Menagerie. As they reached it, Hermione came out, but she wasn\rquote t carrying an owl. Her arms were clamped tightly around the enor\-mous ginger cat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You \i bought\i0  that monster?\rdblquote  said Ron, his mouth hanging open.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s \i gorgeous,\i0  isn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  said Hermione, glowing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 That was a matter of opinion, thought Harry. The cat\rquote s ginger fur was thick and fluffy, but it was definitely a bit bowlegged and its face looked grumpy and oddly squashed, as though it had run headlong into a brick wall. Now that Scabbers was out of sight, however, the cat was purring contentedly in Hermione\rquote s arms.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione, that thing nearly scalped me!\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He didn\rquote t mean to, did you, Crookshanks?\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And what about Scabbers?\rdblquote  said Ron, pointing at the lump in his chest pocket. \ldblquote He needs rest and relaxation! How\rquote s he going to get it with that thing around?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That reminds me, you forgot your rat tonic,\rdblquote  said Hermione, slapping the small red bottle into Ron\rquote s hand. \ldblquote And stop \i worrying,\i0  Crookshanks will be sleeping in my dormitory and Scabbers in yours, what\rquote s the problem? Poor Crookshanks, that witch said he\rquote d been in there for ages; no one wanted him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wonder why,\rdblquote  said Ron sarcastically as they set off toward the Leaky Cauldron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They found Mr. Weasley sitting in the bar, reading the \i Daily Prophet.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  he said, smiling as he looked up. \ldblquote How are you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fine, thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry as he, Ron, and Hermione joined Mr. Weasley with all their shopping.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley put down his paper, and Harry saw the now famil\-iar picture of Sirius Black staring up at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They still haven\rquote t caught him, then?\rdblquote  he asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, looking extremely grave. \ldblquote They\rquote ve pulled us all off our regular jobs at the Ministry to try and find him, but no luck so far.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Would we get a reward if we caught him?\rdblquote  asked Ron. \ldblquote It\rquote d be good to get some more money \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t be ridiculous, Ron,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, who on closer in\-spection looked very strained. \ldblquote Black\rquote s not going to be caught by a thirteen-year-old wizard. It\rquote s the Azkaban guards who\rquote ll get him back, you mark my words.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At that moment Mrs. Weasley entered the bar, laden with shop\-ping bags and followed by the twins, Fred and George, who were about to start their fifth year at Hogwarts; the newly elected Head Boy, Percy; and the Weasleys\rquote  youngest child and only girl, Ginny.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ginny, who had always been very taken with Harry, seemed even more heartily embarrassed than usual when she saw him, per\-haps because he had saved her life during their previous year at Hogwarts. She went very red and muttered \ldblquote hello\rdblquote  without look\-ing at him. Percy, however, held out his hand solemnly as though he and Harry had never met and said, \ldblquote Harry. How nice to see you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hello, Percy,\rdblquote  said Harry, trying not to laugh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I hope you\rquote re well?\rdblquote  said Percy pompously, shaking hands. It was rather like being introduced to the mayor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well, thanks \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  said Fred, elbowing Percy out of the way and bowing deeply. \ldblquote Simply \i splendid\i0  to see you, old boy \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Marvelous,\rdblquote  said George, pushing Fred aside and seizing Harry\rquote s hand in turn. \ldblquote Absolutely spiffing.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Percy scowled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s enough, now,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mum!\rdblquote  said Fred as though he\rquote d only just spotted her and seiz\-ing her hand too. \ldblquote How really corking to see you \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I said, that\rquote s enough,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, depositing her shop\-ping in an empty chair. \ldblquote Hello, Harry, dear. I suppose you\rquote ve heard our exciting news?\rdblquote  She pointed to the brand-new silver badge on Percy\rquote s chest. \ldblquote Second Head Boy in the family!\rdblquote  she said, swelling with pride.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And last,\rdblquote  Fred muttered under his breath.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t doubt that,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, frowning suddenly. \ldblquote I notice they haven\rquote t made you two prefects.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do we want to be prefects for?\rdblquote  said George, looking re\-volted at the very idea. \ldblquote It\rquote d take all the fun out of life.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ginny giggled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You want to set a better example for your sister!\rdblquote  snapped Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ginny\rquote s got other brothers to set her an example, Mother,\rdblquote  said Percy loftily. \ldblquote I\rquote m going up to change for dinner. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He disappeared and George heaved a sigh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We tried to shut him in a pyramid,\rdblquote  he told Harry. \ldblquote But Mum spotted us.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 Dinner that night was a very enjoyable affair. Tom the innkeeper put three tables together in the parlor, and the seven Weasleys, Harry, and Hermione ate their way through five delicious courses.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How\rquote re we getting to King\rquote s Cross tomorrow, Dad?\rdblquote  asked Fred as they dug into a sumptuous chocolate pudding.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Ministry\rquote s providing a couple of cars,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Everyone looked up at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  said Percy curiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s because of you, Perce,\rdblquote  said George seriously. \ldblquote And there\rquote ll be little flags on the hoods, with HB on them \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  for Humongous Bighead,\rdblquote  said Fred.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Everyone except Percy and Mrs. Weasley snorted into their pud\-ding.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why are the Ministry providing cars, Father?\rdblquote  Percy asked again, in a dignified voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, as we haven\rquote t got one anymore,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, \ldblquote\emdash  and as I work there, they\rquote re doing me a favor \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His voice was casual, but Harry couldn\rquote t help noticing that Mr. Weasley\rquote s ears had gone red, just like Ron\rquote s did when he was under pressure.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good thing, too,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley briskly. \ldblquote Do you realize how much luggage you\rquote ve all got between you? A nice sight you\rquote d be on the Muggle Underground. \'85 You are all packed, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron hasn\rquote t put all his new things in his trunk yet,\rdblquote  said Percy, in a long-suffering voice. \ldblquote He\rquote s dumped them on my bed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote d better go and pack properly, Ron, because we won\rquote t have much time in the morning,\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley called down the table. Ron scowled at Percy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After dinner everyone felt very full and sleepy. One by one they made their way upstairs to their rooms to check their things for the next day. Ron and Percy were next door to Harry. He had just closed and locked his own trunk when he heard angry voices through the wall, and went to see what was going on.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door of number twelve was ajar and Percy was shouting.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was \i here,\i0  on the bedside table, I took it off for polishing \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I haven\rquote t touched it, all right?\rdblquote  Ron roared back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s up?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My Head Boy badge is gone,\rdblquote  said Percy, rounding on Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So\rquote s Scabbers\rquote s rat tonic,\rdblquote  said Ron, throwing things out of his trunk to look. \ldblquote I think I might\rquote ve left it in the bar \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re not going anywhere till you\rquote ve found my badge!\rdblquote  yelled Percy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll get Scabbers\rquote s stuff, I\rquote m packed,\rdblquote  Harry said to Ron, and he went downstairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was halfway along the passage to the bar, which was now very dark, when he heard another pair of angry voices coming from the parlor. A second later, he recognized them as Mr. and Mrs.\lang3081  \lang1033 Weasleys\rquote . He hesitated, not wanting them to know he\rquote d heard them arguing, when the sound of his own name made him stop, then move closer to the parlor door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 makes no sense not to tell him,\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley was saying heatedly. \ldblquote Harry\rquote s got a right to know. I\rquote ve tried to tell Fudge, but he insists on treating Harry like a child. He\rquote s thirteen years old and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Arthur, the truth would terrify him!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley shrilly. \ldblquote Do you really want to send Harry back to school with that hang\-ing over him? For heaven\rquote s sake, he\rquote s \i happy\i0  not knowing!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t want to make him miserable, I want to put him on his guard!\rdblquote  retorted Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote You know what Harry and Ron are like, wandering off by themselves \emdash  they\rquote ve even ended up in the Forbidden Forest! But Harry mustn\rquote t do that this year! When I think what could have happened to him that night he ran away from home! If the Knight Bus hadn\rquote t picked him up, I\rquote m prepared to bet he would have been dead before the Ministry found him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But he\rquote s \i not \i0 dead, he\rquote s fine, so what\rquote s the point \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Molly, they say Sirius Black\rquote s mad, and maybe he is, but he was clever enough to escape from Azkaban, and that\rquote s supposed to be impossible. It\rquote s been a month, and no one\rquote s seen hide nor hair of him, and I don\rquote t care what Fudge keeps telling the \i Daily Prophet,\i0  we\rquote re no nearer catching Black than inventing self-spelling wands. The only thing we know for sure is what Black\rquote s after \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But Harry will be perfectly safe at Hogwarts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We thought Azkaban was perfectly safe. If Black can break out of Azkaban, he can break into Hogwarts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But no one\rquote s really sure that Black\rquote s after Harry \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a thud on wood, and Harry was sure Mr. Weasley had banged his fist on the table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Molly, how many times do I have to tell you? They didn\rquote t report it in the press because Fudge wanted it kept quiet, but Fudge went out to Azkaban the night Black escaped. The guards told Fudge that Black\rquote s been talking in his sleep for a while now. Always the same words: \lang3081\lquote\lang1033 He\lang3081\rquote\lang1033 s at Hogwarts \'85 he\lang3081\rquote\lang1033 s at Hogwarts.\lang3081\rquote\lang1033  Black is de\-ranged, Molly, and he wants Harry dead. If you ask me, he thinks murdering Harry will bring You-Know-Who back to power. Black lost everything the night Harry stopped You-Know-Who, and he\rquote s had twelve years alone in Azkaban to brood on that. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a silence. Harry leaned still closer to the door, desper\-ate to hear more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Arthur, you must do what you think is right. But you\rquote re forgetting Albus Dumbledore. I don\rquote t think anything could hurt Harry at Hogwarts while Dumbledore\rquote s headmaster. I suppose he knows about all this?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course he knows. We had to ask him if he minds the Azka\-ban guards stationing themselves around the entrances to the school grounds. He wasn\rquote t happy about it, but he agreed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not happy? Why shouldn\rquote t he be happy, if they\rquote re there to catch Black?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore isn\rquote t fond of the Azkaban guards,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley heavily. \ldblquote Nor am I, if it comes to that \'85 but when you\rquote re dealing with a wizard like Black, you sometimes have to join forces with those you\rquote d rather avoid.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If they save Harry \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  then I will never say another word against them,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley wearily. \ldblquote It\rquote s late, Molly, we\rquote d better go up. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry heard chairs move. As quietly as he could, he hurried down the passage to the bar and out of sight. The parlor door opened, and a few seconds later footsteps told him that Mr. and Mrs. Weasley were climbing the stairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The bottle of rat tonic was lying under the table they had sat at earlier. Harry waited until he heard Mr. and Mrs. Weasley\rquote s bed\-room door close, then headed back upstairs with the bottle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fred and George were crouching in the shadows on the landing, heaving with laughter as they listened to Percy dismantling his and Ron\rquote s room in search of his badge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve got it,\rdblquote  Fred whispered to Harry. \ldblquote We\rquote ve been improv\-ing it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The badge now read \i Bighead Boy.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 Harry forced a laugh, went to give Ron the rat tonic, then shut himself in his room and lay down on his bed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 So Sirius Black was after him. This explained everything. Fudge had been lenient with him because he was so relieved to find him alive. He\rquote d made Harry promise to stay in Diagon Alley where there were plenty of wizards to keep an eye on him. And he was sending two Ministry cars to take them all to the station tomorrow, so that the Weasleys could look after Harry until he was on the train.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry lay listening to the muffled shouting next door and won\-dered why he didn\rquote t feel more scared. Sirius Black had murdered thirteen people with one curse; Mr. and Mrs. Weasley obviously thought Harry would be panic-stricken if he knew the truth. But Harry happened to agree wholeheartedly with Mrs. Weasley that the safest place on earth was wherever Albus Dumbledore hap\-pened to be. Didn\rquote t people always say that Dumbledore was the\lang3081  \lang1033 only person Lord Voldemort had ever been afraid of? Surely Black, as Voldemort\rquote s right-hand man, would be just as frightened of him?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then there were these Azkaban guards everyone kept talking about. They seemed to scare most people senseless, and if they were stationed all around the school, Black\rquote s chances of getting inside seemed very remote.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 No, all in all, the thing that bothered Harry most was the fact that his chances of visiting Hogsmeade now looked like zero. No\-body would want Harry to leave the safety of the castle until Black was caught; in fact, Harry suspected his every move would be care\-fully watched until the danger had passed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He scowled at the dark ceiling. Did they think he couldn\rquote t look after himself? He\rquote d escaped Lord Voldemort three times; he wasn\rquote t completely useless. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Unbidden, the image of the beast in the shadows of Magnolia Crescent crossed his mind. \i What to do when you know the worst is coming. \'85\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m \i not\i0  going to be murdered,\rdblquote  Harry said out loud.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s the spirit, dear,\rdblquote  said his mirror sleepily.\lang3081\par
