Tom woke Harry the next morning with his usual toothless grin and a cup of tea. Harry got dressed and was just per\-suading a disgruntled Hedwig to get back into her cage when Ron banged his way into the room, pulling a sweatshirt over his head and looking irritable.\par
\ldblquote The sooner we get on the train, the better,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote At least I can get away from Percy at Hogwarts. Now he\rquote s accusing me of dripping tea on his photo of Penelope Clearwater. You know,\rdblquote  Ron grimaced, \ldblquote his \i girlfriend.\i0  She\rquote s hidden her face under the frame be\-cause her nose has gone all blotchy. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve got something to tell you,\rdblquote  Harry began, but they were in\-terrupted by Fred and George, who had looked in to congratulate Ron on infuriating Percy again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They headed down to breakfast, where Mr. Weasley was reading the front page of the \i Daily Prophet\i0  with a furrowed brow and Mrs.\lang3081  \lang1033 Weasley was telling Hermione and Ginny about a love potion she\rquote d made as a young girl. All three of them were rather giggly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What were you saying?\rdblquote  Ron asked Harry as they sat down.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Later,\rdblquote  Harry muttered as Percy stormed in.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had no chance to speak to Ron or Hermione in the chaos of leaving; they were too busy heaving all their trunks down the Leaky Cauldron\rquote s narrow staircase and piling them up near the door, with Hedwig and Hermes, Percy\rquote s screech owl, perched on top in their cages. A small wickerwork basket stood beside the heap of trunks, spitting loudly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s all right, Crookshanks,\rdblquote  Hermione cooed through the wicker\-work. \ldblquote I\rquote ll let you out on the train.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You won\rquote t,\rdblquote  snapped Ron. \ldblquote What about poor Scabbers, eh?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He pointed at his chest, where a large lump indicated that Scab\-bers was curled up in his pocket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley, who had been outside waiting for the Ministry cars, stuck his head inside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re here,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Harry, come on.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley marched Harry across the short stretch of pave\-ment toward the first of two old-fashioned dark green cars, each of which was driven by a furtive-looking wizard wearing a suit of emerald velvet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In you get, Harry,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, glancing up and down the crowded street.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry got into the back of the car and was shortly joined by Hermione, Ron, and, to Ron\rquote s disgust, Percy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The journey to King\rquote s Cross was very uneventful compared with Harry\rquote s trip on the Knight Bus. The Ministry of Magic cars seemed\lang3081  \lang1033 almost ordinary, though Harry noticed that they could slide through gaps that Uncle Vernon\rquote s new company car certainly couldn\rquote t have managed. They reached King\rquote s Cross with twenty minutes to spare; the Ministry drivers found them trolleys, un\-loaded their trunks, touched their hats in salute to Mr. Weasley, and drove away, somehow managing to jump to the head of an un\-moving line at the traffic lights.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley kept close to Harry\rquote s elbow all the way into the station.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right then,\rdblquote  he said, glancing around them. \ldblquote Let\rquote s do this in pairs, as there are so many of us. I\rquote ll go through first with Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley strolled toward the barrier between platforms nine and ten, pushing Harry\rquote s trolley and apparently very interested in the InterCity 125 that had just arrived at platform nine. With a meaningful look at Harry, he leaned casually against the barrier. Harry imitated him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In a moment, they had fallen sideways through the solid metal onto platform nine and three-quarters and looked up to see the Hogwarts Express, a scarlet steam engine, puffing smoke over a platform packed with witches and wizards seeing their children onto the train.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Percy and Ginny suddenly appeared behind Harry. They were panting and had apparently taken the barrier at a run.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, there\rquote s Penelope!\rdblquote  said Percy, smoothing his hair and going pink again. Ginny caught Harry\rquote s eye, and they both turned away to hide their laughter as Percy strode over to a girl with long, curly hair, walking with his chest thrown out so that she couldn\rquote t miss his shiny badge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Once the remaining Weasleys and Hermione had joined them, Harry and Ron led the way to the end of the train, past packed compartments, to a carriage that looked quite empty. They loaded the trunks onto it, stowed Hedwig and Crookshanks in the luggage rack, then went back outside to say good-bye to Mr. and Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley kissed all her children, then Hermione, and finally, Harry. He was embarrassed, but really quite pleased, when she gave him an extra hug.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do take care, won\rquote t you, Harry?\rdblquote  she said as she straightened up, her eyes oddly bright. Then she opened her enormous handbag and said, \ldblquote I\rquote ve made you all sandwiches. \'85 Here you are, Ron \'85 no, they\rquote re not corned beef. \'85 Fred? Where\rquote s Fred? Here you are, dear. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley quietly, \ldblquote come over here a mo\-ment.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He jerked his head toward a pillar, and Harry followed him be\-hind it, leaving the others crowded around Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s something I\rquote ve got to tell you before you leave \emdash\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, in a tense voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s all right, Mr. Weasley,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I already know.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know? How could you know?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  er \emdash  I heard you and Mrs. Weasley talking last night. I couldn\rquote t help hearing,\rdblquote  Harry added quickly. \ldblquote Sorry \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s not the way I\rquote d have chosen for you to find out,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, looking anxious.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No \emdash  honestly, it\rquote s okay. This way, you haven\rquote t broken your word to Fudge and I know what\rquote s going on.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, you must be very scared \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not,\rdblquote  said Harry sincerely. \ldblquote\i Really,\i0\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 he added, because Mr. Weasley was looking disbelieving. \ldblquote I\rquote m not trying to be a hero, but seriously, Sirius Black can\rquote t be worse than Voldemort, can he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley flinched at the sound of the name but over\-looked it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, I knew you were, well, made of stronger stuff than Fudge seems to think, and I\rquote m obviously pleased that you\rquote re not scared, but \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Arthur!\rdblquote  called Mrs. Weasley, who was now shepherding the rest onto the train. \ldblquote Arthur, what are you doing? It\rquote s about to go!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s coming, Molly!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley but he turned back to Harry and kept talking in a lower and more hurried voice. \ldblquote Listen, I want you to give me your word \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  that I\rquote ll be a good boy and stay in the castle?\rdblquote  said Harry gloomily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not entirely,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, who looked more serious than Harry had ever seen him. \ldblquote Harry, swear to me you won\rquote t go \i looking \i0 for Black.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stared. \ldblquote What?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a loud whistle. Guards were walking along the train, slamming all the doors shut.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Promise me, Harry,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, talking more quickly still, \ldblquote that whatever happens \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why would I go looking for someone I know wants to kill me?\rdblquote  said Harry blankly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Swear to me that whatever you might hear \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Arthur, quickly!\rdblquote  cried Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Steam was billowing from the train; it had started to move. Harry ran to the compartment door and Ron threw it open and\lang3081  \lang1033 stood back to let him on. They leaned out of the window and waved at Mr. and Mrs. Weasley until the train turned a corner and blocked them from view.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I need to talk to you in private,\rdblquote  Harry muttered to Ron and Hermione as the train picked up speed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Go away, Ginny,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, that\rquote s nice,\rdblquote  said Ginny huffily, and she stalked off.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, Ron, and Hermione set off down the corridor, looking for an empty compartment, but all were full except for the one at the very end of the train.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This had only one occupant, a man sitting fast asleep next to the window. Harry, Ron, and Hermione checked on the threshold. The Hogwarts Express was usually reserved for students and they had never seen an adult there before, except for the witch who pushed the food cart.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The stranger was wearing an extremely shabby set of wizard\rquote s robes that had been darned in several places. He looked ill and ex\-hausted. Though quite young, his light brown hair was flecked with gray.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who d\rquote you reckon he is?\rdblquote  Ron hissed as they sat down and slid the door shut, taking the seats farthest away from the window.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor R. J. Lupin,\rdblquote  whispered Hermione at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How d\rquote you know that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s on his case,\rdblquote  she replied, pointing at the luggage rack over the man\rquote s head, where there was a small, battered case held to\-gether with a large quantity of neatly knotted string. The name \i Professor R. J. Lupin\i0  was stamped across one corner in peeling letters.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wonder what he teaches?\rdblquote  said Ron, frowning at Professor Lupin\rquote s pallid profile.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s obvious,\rdblquote  whispered Hermione. \ldblquote There\rquote s only one va\-cancy, isn\rquote t there? Defense Against the Dark Arts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, Ron, and Hermione had already had two Defense Against the Dark Arts teachers, both of whom had lasted only one year. There were rumors that the job was jinxed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I hope he\rquote s up to it,\rdblquote  said Ron doubtfully. \ldblquote He looks like one good hex would finish him off, doesn\rquote t he? Anyway\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  He turned to Harry. \ldblquote What were you going to tell us?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry explained all about Mr. and Mrs. Weasley\rquote s argument and the warning Mr. Weasley had just given him. When he\rquote d finished, Ron looked thunderstruck, and Hermione had her hands over her mouth. She finally lowered them to say, \ldblquote Sirius Black escaped to come after \i you\i0 ? Oh, Harry \'85 you\rquote ll have to be really, really care\-ful. Don\rquote t go looking for trouble, Harry \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t go looking for trouble,\rdblquote  said Harry, nettled. \ldblquote Trouble usually finds \i me.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How thick would Harry have to be, to go looking for a nutter who wants to kill him?\rdblquote  said Ron shakily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were taking the news worse than Harry had expected. Both Ron and Hermione seemed to be much more frightened of Black than he was.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No one knows how he got out of Azkaban,\rdblquote  said Ron uncom\-fortably. \ldblquote No one\rquote s ever done it before. And he was a top-security prisoner too.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But they\rquote ll catch him, won\rquote t they?\rdblquote  said Hermione earnestly. \ldblquote I mean, they\rquote ve got all the Muggles looking out for him too. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s that noise?\rdblquote  said Ron suddenly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A faint, tinny sort of whistle was coming from somewhere. They looked all around the compartment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s coming from your trunk, Harry,\rdblquote  said Ron, standing up and reaching into the luggage rack. A moment later he had pulled the Pocket Sneakoscope out from between Harry\rquote s robes. It was spin\-ning very fast in the palm of Ron\rquote s hand and glowing brilliantly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is that a \i Sneakoscope\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Hermione interestedly, standing up for a better look.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85 mind you, it\rquote s a very cheap one,\rdblquote  Ron said. \ldblquote It went haywire just as I was tying it to Errol\rquote s leg to send it to Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Were you doing anything untrustworthy at the time?\rdblquote  said Hermione shrewdly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No! Well \'85 I wasn\rquote t supposed to be using Errol. You know he\rquote s not really up to long journeys \'85 but how else was I supposed to get Harry\rquote s present to him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stick it back in the trunk,\rdblquote  Harry advised as the Sneakoscope whistled piercingly, \ldblquote or it\rquote ll wake him up.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He nodded toward Professor Lupin. Ron stuffed the Sneako\-scope into a particularly horrible pair of Uncle Vernon\rquote s old socks, which deadened the sound, then closed the lid of the trunk on it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We could get it checked in Hogsmeade,\rdblquote  said Ron, sitting back down. \ldblquote They sell that sort of thing in Dervish and Banges, magical instruments and stuff. Fred and George told me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do you know much about Hogsmeade?\rdblquote  asked Hermione keenly. \ldblquote I\rquote ve read it\rquote s the only entirely non-Muggle settlement in Britain \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I think it is,\rdblquote  said Ron in an offhand sort of way,\lang3081  \lang1033\ldblquote but that\rquote s not why I want to go. I just want to get inside Honey\-dukes!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s that?\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s this sweetshop,\rdblquote  said Ron, a dreamy look coming over his face, \ldblquote where they\rquote ve got \i everything. \'85\i0  Pepper Imps \emdash  they make you smoke at the mouth \emdash  and great fat Chocoballs full of straw\-berry mousse and clotted cream, and really excellent sugar quills, which you can suck in class and just look like you\rquote re thinking what to write next \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But Hogsmeade\rquote s a very interesting place, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  Hermione pressed on eagerly. \ldblquote In \i Sites of Historical Sorcery\i0  it says the inn was the headquarters for the 1612 goblin rebellion, and the Shrieking Shack\rquote s supposed to be the most severely haunted building in Britain \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and massive sherbet balls that make you levitate a few inches off the ground while you\rquote re sucking them,\rdblquote  said Ron, who was plainly not listening to a word Hermione was saying.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione looked around at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Won\rquote t it be nice to get out of school for a bit and explore Hogsmeade?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Spect it will,\rdblquote  said Harry heavily. \ldblquote You\rquote ll have to tell me when you\rquote ve found out.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you mean?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t go. The Dursleys didn\rquote t sign my permission form, and Fudge wouldn\rquote t either.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron looked horrified.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i You\rquote re not allowed to come\i0 ? But \emdash  no way \emdash  McGonagall or someone will give you permission \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry gave a hollow laugh. Professor McGonagall, head of Gryffindor House, was very strict.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  or we can ask Fred and George, they know every secret pas\-sage out of the castle \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron!\rdblquote  said Hermione sharply. \ldblquote I don\rquote t think Harry should be sneaking out of school with Black on the loose \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I expect that\rquote s what McGonagall will say when I ask for permission,\rdblquote  said Harry bitterly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But if \i we\rquote re\i0  with him,\rdblquote  said Ron spiritedly to Hermione, \ldblquote Black wouldn\rquote t dare \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, Ron, don\rquote t talk rubbish,\rdblquote  snapped Hermione. \ldblquote Black\rquote s al\-ready murdered a whole bunch of people in the middle of a crowded street. Do you really think he\rquote s going to worry about at\-tacking Harry just because \i we\rquote re\i0  there?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was fumbling with the straps of Crookshanks\rquote s basket as she spoke.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t let that thing out!\rdblquote  Ron said, but too late; Crookshanks leapt lightly from the basket, stretched, yawned, and sprang onto Ron\rquote s knees; the lump in Ron\rquote s pocket trembled and he shoved Crookshanks angrily away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get out of here!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron, don\rquote t!\rdblquote  said Hermione angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron was about to answer back when Professor Lupin stirred. They watched him apprehensively, but he simply turned his head the other way, mouth slightly open, and slept on.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Hogwarts Express moved steadily north and the scenery outside the window became wilder and darker while the clouds overhead thickened. People were chasing backward and forward past the door of their compartment. Crookshanks had now settled\lang3081  \lang1033 in an empty seat, his squashed face turned toward Ron, his yellow eyes on Ron\rquote s top pocket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At one o\rquote clock, the plump witch with the food cart arrived at the compartment door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you think we should wake him up?\rdblquote  Ron asked awkwardly, nodding toward Professor Lupin. \ldblquote He looks like he could do with some food.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione approached Professor Lupin cautiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  Professor?\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Excuse me \emdash  Professor?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He didn\rquote t move.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry, dear,\rdblquote  said the witch as she handed Harry a large stack of Cauldron Cakes. \ldblquote If he\rquote s hungry when he wakes, I\rquote ll be up front with the driver.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I suppose he \i is\i0  asleep?\rdblquote  said Ron quietly as the witch slid the compartment door closed. \ldblquote I mean \emdash  he hasn\rquote t died, has he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no, he\rquote s breathing,\rdblquote  whispered Hermione, taking the Caul\-dron Cake Harry passed her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He might not be very good company, but Professor Lupin\rquote s pres\-ence in their compartment had its uses. Midafternoon, just as it had started to rain, blurring the rolling hills outside the window, they heard footsteps in the corridor again, and their three least fa\-vorite people appeared at the door: Draco Malfoy, flanked by his cronies, Vincent Crabbe and Gregory Goyle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Draco Malfoy and Harry had been enemies ever since they had met on their very first train journey to Hogwarts. Malfoy, who had a pale, pointed, sneering face, was in Slytherin House; he played Seeker on the Slytherin Quidditch team, the same position that Harry played on the Gryffindor team. Crabbe and Goyle seemed to exist to do Malfoy\rquote s bidding. They were both wide and\lang3081  \lang1033 musclely; Crabbe was taller, with a pudding-bowl haircut and a very thick neck; Goyle had short, bristly hair and long, gorilla-ish arms.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, look who it is,\rdblquote  said Malfoy in his usual lazy drawl, pulling open the compartment door. \ldblquote Potty and the Weasel.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Crabbe and Goyle chuckled trollishly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I heard your father finally got his hands on some gold this sum\-mer, Weasley,\rdblquote  said Malfoy. \ldblquote Did your mother die of shock?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron stood up so quickly he knocked Crookshanks\rquote s basket to the floor. Professor Lupin gave a snort.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who\rquote s that?\rdblquote  said Malfoy, taking an automatic step backward as he spotted Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote New teacher,\rdblquote  said Harry, who got to his feet, too, in case he needed to hold Ron back. \ldblquote What were you saying, Malfoy?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy\rquote s pale eyes narrowed; he wasn\rquote t fool enough to pick a fight right under a teacher\rquote s nose.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote C\rquote mon,\rdblquote  he muttered resentfully to Crabbe and Goyle, and they disappeared.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Ron sat down again, Ron massaging his knuckles.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not going to take any crap from Malfoy this year,\rdblquote  he said angrily. \ldblquote I mean it. If he makes one more crack about my family, I\rquote m going to get hold of his head and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron made a violent gesture in midair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron,\rdblquote  hissed Hermione, pointing at Professor Lupin, \ldblquote be \i care\-ful\i0  \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Professor Lupin was still fast asleep.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The rain thickened as the train sped yet farther north; the windows were now a solid, shimmering gray, which gradually\lang3081  \lang1033 darkened until lanterns flickered into life all along the corridors and over the luggage racks. The train rattled, the rain hammered, the wind roared, but still, Professor Lupin slept.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We must be nearly there,\rdblquote  said Ron, leaning forward to look past Professor Lupin at the now completely black window.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The words had hardly left him when the train started to slow down.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Great,\rdblquote  said Ron, getting up and walking carefully past Profes\-sor Lupin to try and see outside. \ldblquote I\rquote m starving. I want to get to the feast. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We can\rquote t be there yet,\rdblquote  said Hermione, checking her watch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So why\rquote re we stopping?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The train was getting slower and slower. As the noise of the pis\-tons fell away, the wind and rain sounded louder than ever against the windows.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, who was nearest the door, got up to look into the corri\-dor. All along the carriage, heads were sticking curiously out of their compartments.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The train came to a stop with a jolt, and distant thuds and bangs told them that luggage had fallen out of the racks. Then, without warning, all the lamps went out and they were plunged into total darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s going on?\rdblquote  said Ron\rquote s voice from behind Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ouch!\rdblquote  gasped Hermione. \ldblquote Ron, that was my foot!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt his way back to his seat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you think we\rquote ve broken down?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dunno \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a squeaking sound, and Harry saw the dim black\lang3081  \lang1033 outline of Ron, wiping a patch clean on the window and peer\-ing out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s something moving out there,\rdblquote  Ron said. \ldblquote I think people are coming aboard. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The compartment door suddenly opened and someone fell painfully over Harry\rquote s legs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry \emdash  d\rquote you know what\rquote s going on? \emdash  Ouch \emdash  sorry \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hullo, Neville,\rdblquote  said Harry, feeling around in the dark and pulling Neville up by his cloak.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry? Is that you? What\rquote s happening?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No idea \emdash  sit down \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a loud hissing and a yelp of pain; Neville had tried to sit on Crookshanks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m going to go and ask the driver what\rquote s going on,\rdblquote  came Hermione\rquote s voice. Harry felt her pass him, heard the door slide open again, and then a thud and two loud squeals of pain.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who\rquote s that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who\rquote s \i that\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ginny?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you doing?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was looking for Ron \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come in and sit down \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not here!\rdblquote  said Harry hurriedly. \ldblquote\i I\rquote m\i0  here!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ouch!\rdblquote  said Neville.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Quiet!\rdblquote  said a hoarse voice suddenly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Lupin appeared to have woken up at last. Harry could hear movements in his corner. None of them spoke.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a soft, crackling noise, and a shivering light filled the compartment. Professor Lupin appeared to be holding a handful of flames. They illuminated his tired, gray face, but his eyes looked alert and wary.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stay where you are,\rdblquote  he said in the same hoarse voice, and he got slowly to his feet with his handful of fire held out in front of him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But the door slid slowly open before Lupin could reach it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Standing in the doorway, illuminated by the shivering flames in Lupin\rquote s hand, was a cloaked figure that towered to the ceiling. Its face was completely hidden beneath its hood. Harry\rquote s eyes darted downward, and what he saw made his stomach contract. There was a hand protruding from the cloak and it was glistening, grayish, slimy-looking, and scabbed, like something dead that had decayed in water. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But it was visible only for a split second. As though the creature beneath the cloak sensed Harry\rquote s gaze, the hand was suddenly with\-drawn into the folds of its black cloak.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then the thing beneath the hood, whatever it was, drew a long, slow, rattling breath, as though it were trying to suck some\-thing more than air from its surroundings.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 An intense cold swept over them all. Harry felt his own breath catch in his chest. The cold went deeper than his skin. It was inside his chest, it was inside his very heart. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s eyes rolled up into his head. He couldn\rquote t see. He was drowning in cold. There was a rushing in his ears as though of water. He was being dragged downward, the roaring growing louder \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then, from far away, he heard screaming, terrible, terrified, pleading screams. He wanted to help whoever it was, he tried to move his arms, but couldn\rquote t\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 a thick white fog was swirling around him, inside him \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry! Harry! Are you all right?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Someone was slapping his face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote W \emdash  what?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry opened his eyes; there were lanterns above him, and the floor was shaking \emdash  the Hogwarts Express was moving again and the lights had come back on. He seemed to have slid out of his seat onto the floor. Ron and Hermione were kneeling next to him, and above them he could see Neville and Professor Lupin watching. Harry felt very sick; when he put up his hand to push his glasses back on, he felt cold sweat on his face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron and Hermione heaved him back onto his seat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you okay?\rdblquote  Ron asked nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, looking quickly toward the door. The hooded creature had vanished. \ldblquote What happened? Where\rquote s that \emdash  that thing? Who screamed?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No one screamed,\rdblquote  said Ron, more nervously still.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked around the bright compartment. Ginny and Neville looked back at him, both very pale.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But I heard screaming \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A loud snap made them all jump. Professor Lupin was breaking an enormous slab of chocolate into pieces.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here,\rdblquote  he said to Harry, handing him a particularly large piece. \ldblquote Eat it. It\rquote ll help.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry took the chocolate but didn\rquote t eat it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What was that thing?\rdblquote  he asked Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A dementor,\rdblquote  said Lupin, who was now giving chocolate to everyone else. \ldblquote One of the dementors of Azkaban.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Everyone stared at him. Professor Lupin crumpled up the empty chocolate wrapper and put it in his pocket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Eat,\rdblquote  he repeated. \ldblquote It\rquote ll help. I need to speak to the driver, ex\-cuse me \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He strolled past Harry and disappeared into the corridor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you sure you\rquote re okay, Harry?\rdblquote  said Hermione, watching Harry anxiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t get it. \'85 What happened?\rdblquote  said Harry, wiping more sweat off his face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well \emdash  that thing \emdash  the dementor \emdash  stood there and looked around (I mean, I think it did, I couldn\rquote t see its face) \emdash  and you \emdash  you \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought you were having a fit or something,\rdblquote  said Ron, who still looked scared. \ldblquote You went sort of rigid and fell out of your seat and started twitching \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And Professor Lupin stepped over you, and walked toward the dementor, and pulled out his wand,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote and he said, \lang3081\lquote\lang1033 None of us is hiding Sirius Black under our cloaks. Go.\lang3081\rquote\lang1033  But the dementor didn\rquote t move, so Lupin muttered something, and a silvery thing shot out of his wand at it, and it turned around and sort of glided away. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was horrible,\rdblquote  said Neville, in a higher voice than usual. \ldblquote Did you feel how cold it got when it came in?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I felt weird,\rdblquote  said Ron, shifting his shoulders uncomfortably. \ldblquote Like I\rquote d never be cheerful again. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ginny, who was huddled in her corner looking nearly as bad as Harry felt, gave a small sob; Hermione went over and put a com\-forting arm around her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But didn\rquote t any of you \emdash  fall off your seats?\rdblquote  said Harry awk\-wardly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Ron, looking anxiously at Harry again. \ldblquote Ginny was shaking like mad, though. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry didn\rquote t understand. He felt weak and shivery, as though he were recovering from a bad bout of flu; he also felt the beginnings of shame. Why had he gone to pieces like that, when no one else had?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Lupin had come back. He paused as he entered, looked around, and said, with a small smile, \ldblquote I haven\rquote t poisoned that chocolate, you know. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry took a bite and to his great surprise felt warmth spread suddenly to the tips of his fingers and toes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ll be at Hogwarts in ten minutes,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin. \ldblquote Are you all right, Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry didn\rquote t ask how Professor Lupin knew his name.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fine,\rdblquote  he muttered, embarrassed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They didn\rquote t talk much during the remainder of the journey. At long last, the train stopped at Hogsmeade station, and there was a great scramble to get outside; owls hooted, cats meowed, and Neville\rquote s pet toad croaked loudly from under his hat. It was freez\-ing on the tiny platform; rain was driving down in icy sheets.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Firs\rquote  years this way!\rdblquote  called a familiar voice. Harry, Ron, and Hermione turned and saw the gigantic outline of Hagrid at the other end of the platform, beckoning the terrified-looking new stu\-dents forward for their traditional journey across the lake.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All righ\rquote , you three?\rdblquote  Hagrid yelled over the heads of the crowd. They waved at him, but had no chance to speak to him because the mass of people around them was shunting them away along the platform. Harry, Ron, and Hermione followed the rest of the school along the platform and out onto a rough mud track, where at least a hundred stagecoaches awaited the remaining students, each pulled, Harry could only assume, by an invisible horse, be\-cause when they climbed inside and shut the door, the coach set off all by itself, bumping and swaying in procession.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The coach smelled faintly of mold and straw. Harry felt better since the chocolate, but still weak. Ron and Hermione kept look\-ing at him sideways, as though frightened he might collapse again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As the carriage trundled toward a pair of magnificent wrought iron gates, flanked with stone columns topped with winged boars, Harry saw two more towering, hooded dementors, standing guard on either side. A wave of cold sickness threatened to engulf him again; he leaned back into the lumpy seat and closed his eyes until they had passed the gates. The carriage picked up speed on the long, sloping drive up to the castle; Hermione was leaning out of the tiny window, watching the many turrets and towers draw nearer. At last, the carriage swayed to a halt, and Hermione and Ron got out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As Harry stepped down, a drawling, delighted voice sounded in his ear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\i  fainted,\i0  Potter? Is Longbottom telling the truth? You actu\-ally \i fainted\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy elbowed past Hermione to block Harry\rquote s way up the stone steps to the castle, his face gleeful and his pale eyes glinting maliciously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shove off, Malfoy,\rdblquote  said Ron, whose jaw was clenched.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you faint as well, Weasley?\rdblquote  said Malfoy loudly. \ldblquote Did the scary old dementor frighten you too, Weasley?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is there a problem?\rdblquote  said a mild voice. Professor Lupin had just gotten out of the next carriage.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy gave Professor Lupin an insolent stare, which took in the patches on his robes and the delapidated suitcase. With a tiny hint of sarcasm in his voice, he said, \ldblquote Oh, no \emdash  er \emdash  \i Professor,\i0\rdblquote  then he smirked at Crabbe and Goyle and led them up the steps into the castle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione prodded Ron in the back to make him hurry, and the three of them joined the crowd swarming up the steps, through the giant oak front doors, into the cavernous entrance hall, which was lit with flaming torches, and housed a magnificent marble staircase that led to the upper floors.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door into the Great Hall stood open at the right; Harry fol\-lowed the crowd toward it, but had barely glimpsed the enchanted ceiling, which was black and cloudy tonight, when a voice called, \ldblquote Potter! Granger! I want to see you both!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Hermione turned around, surprised. Professor McGonagall, Transfiguration teacher and head of Gryffindor House, was calling over the heads of the crowd. She was a stern-looking witch who wore her hair in a tight bun; her sharp eyes were framed with square spectacles. Harry fought his way over to her with a feeling of foreboding: Professor McGonagall had a way of making him feel he must have done something wrong.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s no need to look so worried \emdash  I just want a word in my office,\rdblquote  she told them. \ldblquote Move along there, Weasley.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron  stared  as   Professor  McGonagall  ushered  Harry  and\lang3081  \lang1033 Hermione away from the chattering crowd; they accompanied her across the entrance hall, up the marble staircase, and along a corridor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Once they were in her office, a small room with a large, wel\-coming fire, Professor McGonagall motioned Harry and Her\-mione to sit down. She settled herself behind her desk and said abruptly, \ldblquote Professor Lupin sent an owl ahead to say that you were taken ill on the train, Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Before Harry could reply, there was a soft knock on the door and Madam Pomfrey, the nurse, came bustling in.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt himself going red in the face. It was bad enough that he\rquote d passed out, or whatever he had done, without everyone mak\-ing all this fuss.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m fine,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote I don\rquote t need anything \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, it\rquote s you, is it?\rdblquote  said Madam Pomfrey, ignoring this and bending down to stare closely at him. \ldblquote I suppose you\rquote ve been doing something dangerous again?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was a dementor, Poppy,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They exchanged a dark look, and Madam Pomfrey clucked dis\-approvingly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Setting dementors around a school,\rdblquote  she muttered, pushing back Harry\rquote s hair and feeling his forehead. \ldblquote He won\rquote t be the last one who collapses. Yes, he\rquote s all clammy. Terrible things, they are, and the effect they have on people who are already delicate \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not delicate!\rdblquote  said Harry crossly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course you\rquote re not,\rdblquote  said Madam Pomfrey absentmindedly, now taking his pulse.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What does he need?\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall crisply. \ldblquote Bed rest? Should he perhaps spend tonight in the hospital wing?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m \i fine\i0 !\rdblquote  said Harry, jumping up. The thought of what Draco Malfoy would say if he had to go to the hospital wing was torture.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, he should have some chocolate, at the very least,\rdblquote  said Madam Pomfrey, who was now trying to peer into Harry\rquote s eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve already had some,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Professor Lupin gave me some. He gave it to all of us.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did he, now?\rdblquote  said Madam Pomfrey approvingly. \ldblquote So we\rquote ve fi\-nally got a Defense Against the Dark Arts teacher who knows his remedies?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you sure you feel all right, Potter?\rdblquote  Professor McGonagall said sharply.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Yes\i0 ,\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well. Kindly wait outside while I have a quick word with Miss Granger about her course schedule, then we can go down to the feast together.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry went back into the corridor with Madam Pomfrey, who left for the hospital wing, muttering to herself. He had to wait only a few minutes; then Hermione emerged looking very happy about something, followed by Professor McGonagall, and the three of them made their way back down the marble staircase to the Great Hall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was a sea of pointed black hats; each of the long House tables was lined with students, their faces glimmering by the light of thousands of candles, which were floating over the tables in mid\-air. Professor Flitwick, who was a tiny little wizard with a shock of white hair, was carrying an ancient hat and a three-legged stool out of the hall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said Hermione softly, \ldblquote we\rquote ve missed the Sorting!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 New students at Hogwarts were sorted into Houses by trying on the Sorting Hat, which shouted out the House they were best suited to (Gryffindor, Ravenclaw, Hufflepuff, or Slytherin). Profes\-sor McGonagall strode off toward her empty seat at the staff table, and Harry and Hermione set off in the other direction, as quietly as possible, toward the Gryffindor table. People looked around at them as they passed along the back of the hall, and a few of them pointed at Harry. Had the story of his collapsing in front of the de\-mentor traveled that fast?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He and Hermione sat down on either side of Ron, who had saved them seats.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What was all that about?\rdblquote  he muttered to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry started to explain in a whisper, but at that moment the headmaster stood up to speak, and he broke off.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Dumbledore, though very old, always gave an impres\-sion of great energy. He had several feet of long silver hair and beard, half-moon spectacles, and an extremely crooked nose. He was often described as the greatest wizard of the age, but that wasn\rquote t why Harry respected him. You couldn\rquote t help trusting Albus Dum\-bledore, and as Harry watched him beaming around at the stu\-dents, he felt really calm for the first time since the dementor had entered the train compartment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Welcome!\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, the candlelight shimmering on his beard. \ldblquote Welcome to another year at Hogwarts! I have a few things to say to you all, and as one of them is very serious, I think it best to get it out of the way before you become befuddled by our excellent feast. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore cleared his throat and continued, \ldblquote As you will all\lang3081  \lang1033 be aware after their search of the Hogwarts Express, our school is presently playing host to some of the dementors of Azkaban, who are here on Ministry of Magic business.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He paused, and Harry remembered what Mr. Weasley had said about Dumbledore not being happy with the dementors guarding the school.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They are stationed at every entrance to the grounds,\rdblquote  Dumble\-dore continued, \ldblquote and while they are with us, I must make it plain that nobody is to leave school without permission. Dementors are not to be fooled by tricks or disguises \emdash  or even Invisibility Cloaks,\rdblquote  he added blandly, and Harry and Ron glanced at each other. \ldblquote It is not in the nature of a dementor to understand pleading or excuses. I therefore warn each and every one of you to give them no reason to harm you. I look to the prefects, and our new Head Boy and Girl, to make sure that no student runs afoul of the de\-mentors,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Percy, who was sitting a few seats down from Harry, puffed out his chest again and stared around impressively. Dumbledore paused again; he looked very seriously around the hall, and nobody moved or made a sound.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote On a happier note,\rdblquote  he continued, \ldblquote I am pleased to welcome two new teachers to our ranks this year.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote First, Professor Lupin, who has kindly consented to fill the post of Defense Against the Dark Arts teacher.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was some scattered, rather unenthusiastic applause. Only those who had been in the compartment on the train with Profes\-sor Lupin clapped hard, Harry among them. Professor Lupin looked particularly shabby next to all the other teachers in their best robes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look at Snape!\rdblquote  Ron hissed in Harry\rquote s ear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Snape, the Potions master, was staring along the staff table at Professor Lupin. It was common knowledge that Snape wanted the Defense Against the Dark Arts job, but even Harry, who hated Snape, was startled at the expression twisting his thin, sallow face. It was beyond anger: it was loathing. Harry knew that expression only too well; it was the look Snape wore every time he set eyes on Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As to our second new appointment,\rdblquote  Dumbledore continued as the lukewarm applause for Professor Lupin died away. \ldblquote Well, I am sorry to tell you that Professor Kettleburn, our Care of Magical Creatures teacher, retired at the end of last year in order to enjoy more time with his remaining limbs. However, I am delighted to say that his place will be filled by none other than Rubeus Hagrid, who has agreed to take on this teaching job in addition to his gamekeeping duties.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, Ron, and Hermione stared at one another, stunned. Then they joined in with the applause, which was tumultuous at the Gryffindor table in particular. Harry leaned forward to see Hagrid, who was ruby-red in the face and staring down at his enor\-mous hands, his wide grin hidden in the tangle of his black beard.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We should\rquote ve known!\rdblquote  Ron roared, pounding the table. \ldblquote Who else would have assigned us a biting book?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, Ron, and Hermione were the last to stop clapping, and as Professor Dumbledore started speaking again, they saw that Hagrid was wiping his eyes on the tablecloth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I think that\rquote s everything of importance,\rdblquote  said Dumble\-dore. \ldblquote Let the feast begin!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The golden plates and goblets before them filled suddenly with\lang3081  \lang1033 food and drink. Harry, suddenly ravenous, helped himself to everything he could reach and began to eat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was a delicious feast; the hall echoed with talk, laughter, and the clatter of knives and forks. Harry, Ron, and Hermione, how\-ever, were eager for it to finish so that they could talk to Hagrid. They knew how much being made a teacher would mean to him. Hagrid wasn\rquote t a fully qualified wizard; he had been expelled from Hogwarts in his third year for a crime he had not committed. It had been Harry, Ron, and Hermione who had cleared Hagrid\rquote s name last year.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At long last, when the last morsels of pumpkin tart had melted from the golden platters, Dumbledore gave the word that it was time for them all to go to bed, and they got their chance.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Congratulations, Hagrid!\rdblquote  Hermione squealed as they reached the teachers\rquote  table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All down ter you three,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, wiping his shining face on his napkin as he looked up at them. \ldblquote Can\rquote  believe it \'85 great man, Dumbledore \'85 came straight down to me hut after Professor Kettleburn said he\rquote d had enough. \'85 It\rquote s what I always wanted. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Overcome with emotion, he buried his face in his napkin, and Professor McGonagall shooed them away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, Ron, and Hermione joined the Gryffindors streaming up the marble staircase and, very tired now, along more corridors, up more and more stairs, to the hidden entrance to Gryffindor Tower. A large portrait of a fat lady in a pink dress asked them, \ldblquote Pass\-word?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Coming through, coming through!\rdblquote  Percy called from behind the crowd. \ldblquote The new password\rquote s \lang3081\lquote\lang1033 Fortuna Major\lang3081\rquote\lang1033 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh no,\rdblquote  said Neville Longbottom sadly. He always had trouble remembering the passwords.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Through the portrait hole and across the common room, the girls and boys divided toward their separate staircases. Harry climbed the spiral stair with no thought in his head except how glad he was to be back. They reached their familiar, circular dormitory with its five four-poster beds, and Harry, looking around, felt he was home at last.\lang3081\par
