\lang1033\ldblquote Careful, Potter, there\rquote s a dementor behind you \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oooooooh!\rdblquote  squealed Lavender Brown, pointing toward the opposite side of the paddock.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Trotting toward them were a dozen of the most bizarre creatures Harry had ever seen. They had the bodies, hind legs, and tails of horses, but the front legs, wings, and heads of what seemed to be\lang3081  \lang1033 giant eagles, with cruel, steel-colored beaks and large, brilliantly or\-ange eyes. The talons on their front legs were half a foot long and deadly looking. Each of the beasts had a thick leather collar around its neck, which was attached to a long chain, and the ends of all of these were held in the vast hands of Hagrid, who came jogging into the paddock behind the creatures.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Gee up, there!\rdblquote  he roared, shaking the chains and urging the creatures toward the fence where the class stood. Everyone drew back slightly as Hagrid reached them and tethered the creatures to the fence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hippogriffs!\rdblquote  Hagrid roared happily, waving a hand at them. \ldblquote Beau\rquote iful, aren\rquote  they?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry could sort of see what Hagrid meant. Once you got over the first shock of seeing something that was half horse, half bird, you started to appreciate the hippogriffs\rquote  gleaming coats, changing smoothly from feather to hair, each of them a different color: stormy gray, bronze, pinkish roan, gleaming chestnut, and inky black.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, rubbing his hands together and beaming around, \ldblquote if yeh wan\rquote  ter come a bit nearer \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 No one seemed to want to. Harry, Ron, and Hermione, how\-ever, approached the fence cautiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, firs\rquote  thing yeh gotta know abou\rquote  hippogriffs is, they\rquote re proud,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote Easily offended, hippogriffs are. Don\rquote t never insult one, \rquote cause it might be the last thing yeh do.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy, Crabbe, and Goyle weren\rquote t listening; they were talking in an undertone and Harry had a nasty feeling they were plotting how best to disrupt the lesson.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeh always wait fer the hippogriff ter make the firs\rquote  move,\rdblquote  Hagrid continued. \ldblquote It\rquote s polite, see? Yeh walk toward him, and yeh bow, an\rquote  yeh wait. If he bows back, yeh\rquote re allowed ter touch him. If he doesn\rquote  bow, then get away from him sharpish, \rquote cause those talons hurt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right \emdash  who wants ter go first?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Most of the class backed farther away in answer. Even Harry, Ron, and Hermione had misgivings. The hippogriffs were tossing their fierce heads and flexing their powerful wings; they didn\rquote t seem to like being tethered like this.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No one?\rdblquote  said Hagrid, with a pleading look.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll do it,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was an intake of breath from behind him, and both Lavender and Parvati whispered, \ldblquote Oooh, no, Harry, remember your tea leaves!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry ignored them. He climbed over the paddock fence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good man, Harry!\rdblquote  roared Hagrid. \ldblquote Right then \emdash  let\rquote s see how yeh get on with Buckbeak.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He untied one of the chains, pulled the gray hippogriff away from its fellows, and slipped off its leather collar. The class on the other side of the paddock seemed to be holding its breath. Malfoy\rquote s eyes were narrowed maliciously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Easy, now, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hagrid quietly. \ldblquote Yeh\rquote ve got eye contact, now try not ter blink. \'85 Hippogriffs don\rquote  trust yeh if yeh blink too much. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s eyes immediately began to water, but he didn\rquote t shut them. Buckbeak had turned his great, sharp head and was staring at Harry with one fierce orange eye.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tha\rquote s it,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote Tha\rquote s it, Harry \'85 now, bow \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry didn\rquote t feel much like exposing the back of his neck to Buckbeak, but he did as he was told. He gave a short bow and then looked up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The hippogriff was still staring haughtily at him. It didn\rquote t move.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, sounding worried. \ldblquote Right \emdash  back away, now, Harry, easy does it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But then, to Harry\rquote s enormous surprise, the hippogriff suddenly bent its scaly front knees and sank into what was an unmistakable bow.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well done, Harry!\rdblquote  said Hagrid, ecstatic. \ldblquote Right \emdash  yeh can touch him! Pat his beak, go on!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Feeling that a better reward would have been to back away, Harry moved slowly toward the hippogriff and reached out toward it. He patted the beak several times and the hippogriff closed its eyes lazily, as though enjoying it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The class broke into applause, all except for Malfoy, Crabbe, and Goyle, who were looking deeply disappointed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Righ\rquote  then, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote I reckon he might\rquote  let yeh ride him!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This was more than Harry had bargained for. He was used to a broomstick; but he wasn\rquote t sure a hippogriff would be quite the same.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeh climb up there, jus\rquote  behind the wing joint,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, \ldblquote an\rquote  mind yeh don\rquote  pull any of his feathers out, he won\rquote  like that. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry put his foot on the top of Buckbeak\rquote s wing and hoisted himself onto its back. Buckbeak stood up. Harry wasn\rquote t sure where to hold on; everything in front of him was covered with feathers.\par
\ldblquote Go on, then!\rdblquote  roared Hagrid, slapping the hippogriff\rquote s hind\-quarters.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Without warning, twelve-foot wings flapped open on either side of Harry; he just had time to seize the hippogriff around the neck before he was soaring upward. It was nothing like a broomstick, and Harry knew which one he preferred; the hippogriff\rquote s wings beat uncomfortably on either side of him, catching him under his legs and making him feel he was about to be thrown off; the glossy feathers slipped under his fingers and he didn\rquote t dare get a stronger grip; instead of the smooth action of his Nimbus Two Thousand, he now felt himself rocking backward and forward as the hindquar\-ters of the hippogriff rose and fell with its wings.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Buckbeak flew him once around the paddock and then headed back to the ground; this was the bit Harry had been dreading; he leaned back as the smooth neck lowered, feeling he was going to slip off over the beak, then felt a heavy thud as the four ill-assorted feet hit the ground. He just managed to hold on and push himself straight again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good work, Harry!\rdblquote  roared Hagrid as everyone except Malfoy, Crabbe, and Goyle cheered. \ldblquote Okay, who else wants a go?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Emboldened by Harry\rquote s success, the rest of the class climbed cautiously into the paddock. Hagrid untied the hippogriffs one by one, and soon people were bowing nervously, all over the paddock. Neville ran repeatedly backward from his, which didn\rquote t seem to want to bend its knees. Ron and Hermione practiced on the chest\-nut, while Harry watched.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy, Crabbe, and Goyle had taken over Buckbeak. He had bowed to Malfoy, who was now patting his beak, looking dis\-dainful.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is very easy,\rdblquote  Malfoy drawled, loud enough for Harry to hear him. \ldblquote I knew it must have been, if Potter could do it. \'85 I bet you\rquote re not dangerous at all, are you?\rdblquote  he said to the hippogriff. \ldblquote Are you, you great ugly brute?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It happened in a flash of steely talons; Malfoy let out a high-pitched scream and next moment, Hagrid was wrestling Buckbeak back into his collar as he strained to get at Malfoy, who lay curled in the grass, blood blossoming over his robes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m dying!\rdblquote  Malfoy yelled as the class panicked. \ldblquote I\rquote m dying, look at me! It\rquote s killed me!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yer not dyin\rquote !\rdblquote  said Hagrid, who had gone very white. \ldblquote Some\-one help me \emdash  gotta get him outta here \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione ran to hold open the gate as Hagrid lifted Malfoy eas\-ily. As they passed, Harry saw that there was a long, deep gash on Malfoy\rquote s arm; blood splattered the grass and Hagrid ran with him, up the slope toward the castle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Very shaken, the Care of Magical Creatures class followed at a walk. The Slytherins were all shouting about Hagrid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They should fire him straight away!\rdblquote  said Pansy Parkinson, who was in tears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was Malfoy\rquote s fault!\rdblquote  snapped Dean Thomas. Crabbe and Goyle flexed their muscles threateningly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They all climbed the stone steps into the deserted entrance hall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m going to see if he\rquote s okay!\rdblquote  said Pansy, and they all watched her run up the marble staircase. The Slytherins, still muttering about Hagrid, headed away in the direction of their dungeon common room; Harry, Ron, and Hermione proceeded upstairs to Gryffindor Tower.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you think he\rquote ll be all right?\rdblquote  said Hermione nervously.\lang3081\par
\ldblquote  \rquote\lang1033 Course he will. Madam Pomfrey can mend cuts in about a sec\-ond,\rdblquote  said Harry, who had had far worse injuries mended magically by the nurse.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was a really bad thing to happen in Hagrid\rquote s first class, though, wasn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Ron, looking worried. \ldblquote Trust Malfoy to mess things up for him. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were among the first to reach the Great Hall at dinner\-time, hoping to see Hagrid, but he wasn\rquote t there.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They \i wouldn\rquote t\lang3081\i0  \lang1033 fire him, would they?\rdblquote  said Hermione anxiously, not touching her steak-and-kidney pudding.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote d better not,\rdblquote  said Ron, who wasn\rquote t eating either.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was watching the Slytherin table. A large group including Crabbe and Goyle was huddled together, deep in conversation. Harry was sure they were cooking up their own version of how Malfoy had been injured.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you can\rquote t say it wasn\rquote t an interesting first day back,\rdblquote  said Ron gloomily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They went up to the crowded Gryffindor common room after dinner and tried to do the homework Professor McGonagall had given them, but all three of them kept breaking off and glancing out of the tower window.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s a light on in Hagrid\rquote s window,\rdblquote  Harry said suddenly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron looked at his watch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If we hurried, we could go down and see him. It\rquote s still quite early. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  Hermione said slowly, and Harry saw her glance at him.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m allowed to walk across the \i grounds,\i0\rdblquote  he said pointedly. \ldblquote Sirius Black hasn\rquote t got past the dementors yet, has he?\rdblquote\par
So they put their things away and headed out of the portrait hole, glad to meet nobody on their way to the front doors, as they weren\rquote t entirely sure they were supposed to be out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The grass was still wet and looked almost black in the twilight. When they reached Hagrid\rquote s hut, they knocked, and a voice growled, \ldblquote C\rquote min.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid was sitting in his shirtsleeves at his scrubbed wooden table; his boarhound, Fang, had his head in Hagrid\rquote s lap. One look told them that Hagrid had been drinking a lot; there was a pewter tankard almost as big as a bucket in front of him, and he seemed to be having difficulty getting them into focus.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Spect it\rquote s a record,\rdblquote  he said thickly, when he recognized them. \ldblquote Don\rquote  reckon they\rquote ve ever had a teacher who lasted on\rquote y a day be\-fore.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You haven\rquote t been fired, Hagrid!\rdblquote  gasped Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not yet,\rdblquote  said Hagrid miserably, taking a huge gulp of whatever was in the tankard. \ldblquote But \rquote s only a matter o\rquote  time, i\rquote n\rquote t it, after Malfoy\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How is he?\rdblquote  said Ron as they all sat down. \ldblquote It wasn\rquote t serious, was it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Madam Pomfrey fixed him best she could,\rdblquote  said Hagrid dully, \ldblquote but he\rquote s sayin\rquote  it\rquote s still agony\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 covered in ban\-dages \'85 moanin\rquote  \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s faking it,\rdblquote  said Harry at once. \ldblquote Madam Pomfrey can mend anything. She regrew half my bones last year. Trust Malfoy to milk it for all it\rquote s worth.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote School gov\rquote nors have bin told, o\rquote  course,\rdblquote  said Hagrid miser\-ably. \ldblquote They reckon I started too big. Shoulda left hippogriffs fer later \'85 done flobberworms or summat. \'85 Jus\rquote  thought it\rquote d make a good firs\rquote  lesson. \'85 \rquote S all my fault. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s all \i Malfoy\rquote s\i0  fault, Hagrid!\rdblquote  said Hermione earnestly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re witnesses,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote You said hippogriffs attack if you insult them. It\rquote s Malfoy\rquote s problem that he wasn\rquote t listening. We\rquote ll tell Dumbledore what really happened.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, don\rquote t worry, Hagrid, we\rquote ll back you up,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Tears leaked out of the crinkled corners of Hagrid\rquote s beetle-black eyes. He grabbed both Harry and Ron and pulled them into a bone-breaking hug.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think you\rquote ve had enough to drink, Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Hermione firmly. She took the tankard from the table and went outside to empty it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ar, maybe she\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, letting go of Harry and Ron, who both staggered away, rubbing their ribs. Hagrid heaved himself out of his chair and followed Hermione unsteadily outside. They heard a loud splash.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s he done?\rdblquote  said Harry nervously as Hermione came back in with the empty tankard.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stuck his head in the water barrel,\rdblquote  said Hermione, putting the tankard away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid came back, his long hair and beard sopping wet, wiping the water out of his eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tha\rquote s better,\rdblquote  he said, shaking his head like a dog and drench\-ing them all. \ldblquote Listen, it was good of yeh ter come an\rquote  see me, I really \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid stopped dead, staring at Harry as though he\rquote d only just realized he was there.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote WHAT D\rquote YEH THINK YOU\rquote RE DOIN\rquote , EH?\rdblquote  he roared, so suddenly that they jumped a foot in the air. \ldblquote YEH\rquote RE NOT TO GO WANDERIN\rquote  AROUND AFTER DARK, HARRY! AN\rquote  YOU TWO! LETTIN\rquote  HIM!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid strode over to Harry, grabbed his arm, and pulled him to the door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote C\rquote mon!\rdblquote  Hagrid said angrily. \ldblquote I\rquote m takin\rquote  yer all back up ter school, an\rquote  don\rquote  let me catch yeh walkin\rquote  down ter see me after dark again. I\rquote m not worth that!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
