Malfoy didn\rquote t reappear in classes until late on Thursday morning, when the Slytherins and Gryffindors were halfway through double Potions. He swaggered into the dungeon, his right arm covered in bandages and bound up in a sling, acting, in Harry\rquote s opinion, as though he were the heroic survivor of some dreadful battle.\par
\ldblquote How is it, Draco?\rdblquote  simpered Pansy Parkinson. \ldblquote Does it hurt much?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Malfoy, putting on a brave sort of grimace. But Harry saw him wink at Crabbe and Goyle when Pansy had looked away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Settle down, settle down,\rdblquote  said Professor Snape idly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Ron scowled at each other; Snape wouldn\rquote t have said \ldblquote settle down\rdblquote  if \i they\rquote d\i0  walked in late, he\rquote d have given them deten\-tion. But Malfoy had always been able to get away with anything in\lang3081  \lang1033 Snape\rquote s classes; Snape was head of Slytherin House, and generally favored his own students above all others.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were making a new potion today, a Shrinking Solution. Malfoy set up his cauldron right next to Harry and Ron, so that they were preparing their ingredients on the same table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sir,\rdblquote  Malfoy called, \ldblquote sir, I\rquote ll need help cutting up these daisy roots, because of my arm \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Weasley, cut up Malfoy\rquote s roots for him,\rdblquote  said Snape without looking up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron went brick red.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s nothing wrong with your arm,\rdblquote  he hissed at Malfoy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy smirked across the table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Weasley, you heard Professor Snape; cut up these roots.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron seized his knife, pulled Malfoy\rquote s roots toward him, and be\-gan to chop them roughly, so that they were all different sizes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor,\rdblquote  drawled Malfoy, \ldblquote Weasley\rquote s mutilating my roots, sir.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape approached their table, stared down his hooked nose at the roots, then gave Ron an unpleasant smile from beneath his long, greasy black hair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Change roots with Malfoy, Weasley.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But, sir \emdash  !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron had spent the last quarter of an hour carefully shredding his own roots into exactly equal pieces.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Now,\i0\rdblquote  said Snape in his most dangerous voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron shoved his own beautifully cut roots across the table at Malfoy, then took up the knife again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And, sir, I\rquote ll need this shrivelfig skinned,\rdblquote  said Malfoy, his voice full of malicious laughter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Potter, you can skin Malfoy\rquote s shrivelfig,\rdblquote  said Snape, giving Harry the look of loathing he always reserved just for him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry took Malfoy\rquote s shrivelfig as Ron began trying to repair the damage to the roots he now had to use. Harry skinned the shriv\-elfig as fast as he could and flung it back across the table at Malfoy without speaking. Malfoy was smirking more broadly than ever.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Seen your pal Hagrid lately?\rdblquote  he asked them quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote None of your business,\rdblquote  said Ron jerkily, without looking up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid he won\rquote t be a teacher much longer,\rdblquote  said Malfoy in a tone of mock sorrow. \ldblquote Father\rquote s not very happy about my injury \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Keep talking, Malfoy, and I\rquote ll give you a real injury,\rdblquote  snarled Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  he\rquote s complained to the school governors. \i And\i0  to the Min\-istry of Magic. Father\rquote s got a lot of influence, you know. And a last\-ing injury like this\rdblquote  \emdash  he gave a huge, fake sigh \emdash  \ldblquote who knows if my arm\rquote ll ever be the same again?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So that\rquote s why you\rquote re putting it on,\rdblquote  said Harry, accidentally be\-heading a dead caterpillar because his hand was shaking in anger. \ldblquote To try to get Hagrid fired.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Malfoy, lowering his voice to a whisper, \ldblquote\i partly,\i0  Potter. But there are other benefits too. Weasley, slice my caterpil\-lars for me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A few cauldrons away, Neville was in trouble. Neville regularly went to pieces in Potions lessons; it was his worst subject, and his great fear of Professor Snape made things ten times worse. His po\-tion, which was supposed to be a bright, acid green, had turned \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Orange, Longbottom,\rdblquote  said Snape, ladling some up and allow\-ing it to splash back into the cauldron, so that everyone could see. \ldblquote Orange. Tell me, boy, does anything penetrate that thick skull of\lang3081  \lang1033 yours? Didn\rquote t you hear me say, quite clearly, that only one rat spleen was needed? Didn\rquote t I state plainly that a dash of leech juice would suffice? What do I have to do to make you understand, Longbottom?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville was pink and trembling. He looked as though he was on the verge of tears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Please, sir,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote please, I could help Neville put it right \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t remember asking you to show off, Miss Granger,\rdblquote  said Snape coldly, and Hermione went as pink as Neville. \ldblquote Longbot\-tom, at the end of this lesson we will feed a few drops of this potion to your toad and see what happens. Perhaps that will encourage you to do it properly.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape moved away, leaving Neville breathless with fear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Help me!\rdblquote  he moaned to Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hey, Harry,\rdblquote  said Seamus Finnigan, leaning over to borrow Harry\rquote s brass scales, \ldblquote have you heard? \i Daily Prophet\i0  this morning \emdash  they reckon Sirius Black\rquote s been sighted.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where?\rdblquote  said Harry and Ron quickly. On the other side of the table, Malfoy looked up, listening closely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not too far from here,\rdblquote  said Seamus, who looked excited. \ldblquote It was a Muggle who saw him. \lang3081\rquote\lang1033 Course, she didn\rquote t really understand. The Muggles think he\rquote s just an ordinary criminal, don\rquote t they? So she phoned the telephone hot line. By the time the Ministry of Magic got there, he was gone.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not too far from here \'85 ,\rdblquote  Ron repeated, looking significantly at Harry. He turned around and saw Malfoy watching closely. \ldblquote What, Malfoy? Need something else skinned?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Malfoy\rquote s eyes were shining malevolently, and they were fixed on Harry. He leaned across the table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thinking of trying to catch Black single-handed, Potter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, that\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Harry offhandedly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy\rquote s thin mouth was curving in a mean smile.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course, if it was me,\rdblquote  he said quietly, \ldblquote I\rquote d have done some\-thing before now. I wouldn\rquote t be staying in school like a good boy, I\rquote d be out there looking for him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you talking about, Malfoy?\rdblquote  said Ron roughly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t you \i know,\i0  Potter?\rdblquote  breathed Malfoy, his pale eyes nar\-rowed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Know what?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy let out a low, sneering laugh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe you\rquote d rather not risk your neck,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Want to leave it to the dementors, do you? But if it was me, I\rquote d want revenge. I\rquote d hunt him down myself.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i What are you talking about\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Harry angrily, but at that moment Snape called, \ldblquote You should have finished adding your ingredients by now; this potion needs to stew before it can be drunk, so clear away while it simmers and then we\rquote ll test Long\-bottom\rquote s. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Crabbe and Goyle laughed openly, watching Neville sweat as he stirred his potion feverishly. Hermione was muttering instructions to him out of the corner of her mouth, so that Snape wouldn\rquote t see. Harry and Ron packed away their unused ingredients and went to wash their hands and ladles in the stone basin in the corner.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What did Malfoy mean?\rdblquote  Harry muttered to Ron as he stuck his hands under the icy jet that poured from the gargoyle\rquote s mouth.\lang3081  \lang1033\ldblquote Why would I want revenge on Black? He hasn\rquote t done anything to me \emdash  yet.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s making it up,\rdblquote  said Ron savagely. \ldblquote He\rquote s trying to make you do something stupid. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The end of the lesson in sight, Snape strode over to Neville, who was cowering by his cauldron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Everyone gather \rquote round,\rdblquote  said Snape, his black eyes glittering, \ldblquote and watch what happens to Longbottom\rquote s toad. If he has managed to produce a Shrinking Solution, it will shrink to a tadpole. If, as I don\rquote t doubt, he has done it wrong, his toad is likely to be poi\-soned.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Gryffindors watched fearfully. The Slytherins looked ex\-cited. Snape picked up Trevor the toad in his left hand and dipped a small spoon into Neville\rquote s potion, which was now green. He trickled a few drops down Trevor\rquote s throat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a moment of hushed silence, in which Trevor gulped; then there was a small pop, and Trevor the tadpole was wriggling in Snape\rquote s palm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Gryffindors burst into applause. Snape, looking sour, pulled a small bottle from the pocket of his robe, poured a few drops on top of Trevor, and he reappeared suddenly, fully grown.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Five points from Gryffindor,\rdblquote  said Snape, which wiped the smiles from every face. \ldblquote I told you not to help him, Miss Granger. Class dismissed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, Ron, and Hermione climbed the steps to the entrance hall. Harry was still thinking about what Malfoy had said, while Ron was seething about Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Five points from Gryffindor because the potion was all right!\lang3081  \lang1033 Why didn\rquote t you lie, Hermione? You should\rquote ve said Neville did it all by himself!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione didn\rquote t answer. Ron looked around.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where is she?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned too. They were at the top of the steps now, watch\-ing the rest of the class pass them, heading for the Great Hall and lunch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She was right behind us,\rdblquote  said Ron, frowning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy passed them, walking between Crabbe and Goyle. He smirked at Harry and disappeared.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There she is,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione was panting slightly, hurrying up the stairs; one hand clutched her bag, the other seemed to be tucking something down the front of her robes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How did you do that?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Hermione, joining them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote One minute you were right behind us, the next moment, you were back at the bottom of the stairs again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  Hermione looked slightly confused. \ldblquote Oh \emdash  I had to go back for something. Oh no \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A seam had split on Hermione\rquote s bag. Harry wasn\rquote t surprised; he could see that it was crammed with at least a dozen large and heavy books.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why are you carrying all these around with you?\rdblquote  Ron asked her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know how many subjects I\rquote m taking,\rdblquote  said Hermione breathlessly. \ldblquote Couldn\rquote t hold these for me, could you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But \emdash\rdblquote  Ron was turning over the books she had handed him,\lang3081  \lang1033 looking at the covers. \ldblquote You haven\rquote t got any of these subjects today. It\rquote s only Defense Against the Dark Arts this afternoon.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes,\rdblquote  said Hermione vaguely, but she packed all the books back into her bag just the same. \ldblquote I hope there\rquote s something good for lunch, I\rquote m starving,\rdblquote  she added, and she marched off toward the Great Hall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you get the feeling Hermione\rquote s not telling us something?\rdblquote  Ron asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 Professor Lupin wasn\rquote t there when they arrived at his first Defense Against the Dark Arts lesson. They all sat down, took out their books, quills, and parchment, and were talking when he finally en\-tered the room. Lupin smiled vaguely and placed his tatty old briefcase on the teacher\rquote s desk. He was as shabby as ever but looked healthier than he had on the train, as though he had had a few square meals.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good afternoon,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Would you please put all your books back in your bags. Today\rquote s will be a practical lesson. You will need only your wands.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A few curious looks were exchanged as the class put away their books. They had never had a practical Defense Against the Dark Arts before, unless you counted the memorable class last year when their old teacher had brought a cageful of pixies to class and set them loose.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right then,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin, when everyone was ready. \ldblquote If you\rquote d follow me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Puzzled but interested, the class got to its feet and followed Pro\-fessor Lupin out of the classroom. He led them along the deserted\lang3081  \lang1033 corridor and around a corner, where the first thing they saw was Peeves the Poltergeist, who was floating upside down in midair and stuffing the nearest keyhole with chewing gum.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Peeves didn\rquote t look up until Professor Lupin was two feet away; then he wiggled his curly-toed feet and broke into song.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Loony, loopy Lupin,\rdblquote  Peeves sang. \ldblquote Loony, loopy Lupin, loony, loopy Lupin \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Rude and unmanageable as he almost always was, Peeves usually showed some respect toward the teachers. Everyone looked quickly at Professor Lupin to see how he would take this; to their surprise, he was still smiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote d take that gum out of the keyhole if I were you, Peeves,\rdblquote  he said pleasantly. \ldblquote Mr. Filch won\rquote t be able to get in to his brooms.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Filch was the Hogwarts caretaker, a bad-tempered, failed wizard who waged a constant war against the students and, indeed, Peeves. However, Peeves paid no attention to Professor Lupin\rquote s words, ex\-cept to blow a loud wet raspberry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Lupin gave a small sigh and took out his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is a useful little spell,\rdblquote  he told the class over his shoulder. \ldblquote Please watch closely.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He raised the wand to shoulder height, said, \ldblquote\i Waddiwasi\i0 !\rdblquote  and pointed it at Peeves.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With the force of a bullet, the wad of chewing gum shot out of the keyhole and straight down Peeves\rquote s left nostril; he whirled up\-right and zoomed away, cursing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cool, sir!\rdblquote  said Dean Thomas in amazement.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you, Dean,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin, putting his wand away again. \ldblquote Shall we proceed?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They set off again, the class looking at shabby Professor Lupin with increased respect. He led them down a second corridor and stopped, right outside the staffroom door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Inside, please,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin, opening it and standing back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The staffroom, a long, paneled room full of old, mismatched chairs, was empty except for one teacher. Professor Snape was sit\-ting in a low armchair, and he looked around as the class filed in. His eyes were glittering and there was a nasty sneer playing around his mouth. As Professor Lupin came in and made to close the door behind him, Snape said, \ldblquote Leave it open, Lupin. I\rquote d rather not wit\-ness this.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He got to his feet and strode past the class, his black robes bil\-lowing behind him. At the doorway he turned on his heel and said, \ldblquote Possibly no one\rquote s warned you, Lupin, but this class contains Neville Longbottom. I would advise you not to entrust him with anything difficult. Not unless Miss Granger is hissing instructions in his ear.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville went scarlet. Harry glared at Snape; it was bad enough that he bullied Neville in his own classes, let alone doing it in front of other teachers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Lupin had raised his eyebrows.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was hoping that Neville would assist me with the first stage of the operation,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote and I am sure he will perform it ad\-mirably.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville\rquote s face went, if possible, even redder. Snape\rquote s lip curled, but he left, shutting the door with a snap.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, then,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin, beckoning the class toward the end of the room, where there was nothing but an old wardrobe\lang3081  \lang1033 where the teachers kept their spare robes. As Professor Lupin went to stand next to it, the wardrobe gave a sudden wobble, banging off the wall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing to worry about,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin calmly because a few people had jumped backward in alarm. \ldblquote There\rquote s a boggart in there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Most people seemed to feel that this \i was\i0  something to worry about. Neville gave Professor Lupin a look of pure terror, and Seamus Finnigan eyed the now rattling doorknob apprehensively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Boggarts like dark, enclosed spaces,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin. \ldblquote Wardrobes, the gap beneath beds, the cupboards under sinks \emdash  I\rquote ve even met one that had lodged itself in a grandfather clock. \i This \i0 one moved in yesterday afternoon, and I asked the headmaster if the staff would leave it to give my third years some practice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, the first question we must ask ourselves is, what \i is\i0  a bog\-gart?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione put up her hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s a shape-shifter,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote It can take the shape of whatever it thinks will frighten us most.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Couldn\rquote t have put it better myself,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin, and Hermione glowed. \ldblquote So the boggart sitting in the darkness within has not yet assumed a form. He does not yet know what will frighten the person on the other side of the door. Nobody knows what a boggart looks like when he is alone, but when I let him out, he will immediately become whatever each of us most fears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This means,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin, choosing to ignore Neville\rquote s small sputter of terror, \ldblquote that we have a huge advantage over the boggart before we begin. Have you spotted it, Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Trying to answer a question with Hermione next to him,\lang3081  \lang1033 bobbing up and down on the balls of her feet with her hand in the air, was very off-putting, but Harry had a go.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  because there are so many of us, it won\rquote t know what shape it should be?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Precisely,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin, and Hermione put her hand down, looking a little disappointed. \ldblquote It\rquote s always best to have com\-pany when you\rquote re dealing with a boggart. He becomes confused. Which should he become, a headless corpse or a flesh-eating slug? I once saw a boggart make that very mistake \emdash  tried to frighten two people at once and turned himself into half a slug. Not re\-motely frightening.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The charm that repels a boggart is simple, yet it requires force of mind. You see, the thing that really finishes a boggart is \i laughter. \i0 What you need to do is force it to assume a shape that you find amusing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We will practice the charm without wands first. After me, please \'85 \i riddikulus\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Riddikulus\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 said the class together.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin. \ldblquote Very good. But that was the easy part, I\rquote m afraid. You see, the word alone is not enough. And this is where you come in, Neville.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The wardrobe shook again, though not as much as Neville, who walked forward as though he were heading for the gallows.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right, Neville,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin. \ldblquote First things first: what would you say is the thing that frightens you most in the world?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville\rquote s lips moved, but no noise came out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Didn\rquote t catch that, Neville, sorry,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin cheer\-fully\lang3081 .\par
\lang1033 Neville looked around rather wildly, as though begging someone\lang3081  \lang1033 to help him, then said, in barely more than a whisper, \ldblquote Professor Snape.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nearly everyone laughed. Even Neville grinned apologetically. Professor Lupin, however, looked thoughtful.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Snape \'85 hmmm \'85 Neville, I believe you live with your grandmother?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  yes,\rdblquote  said Neville nervously. \ldblquote But \emdash  I don\rquote t want the boggart to turn into her either.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no, you misunderstand me,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin, now smiling. \ldblquote I wonder, could you tell us what sort of clothes your grandmother usually wears?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville looked startled, but said, \ldblquote Well \'85 always the same hat. A tall one with a stuffed vulture on top. And a long dress \'85 green, normally \'85 and sometimes a fox-fur scarf.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And a handbag?\rdblquote  prompted Professor Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A big red one,\rdblquote  said Neville.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right then,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin. \ldblquote Can you picture those clothes very clearly, Neville? Can you see them in your mind\rquote s eye?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Neville uncertainly, plainly wondering what was coming next.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote When the boggart bursts out of this wardrobe, Neville, and sees you, it will assume the form of Professor Snape,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote And you will raise your wand \emdash  thus \emdash  and cry \lang3081\lquote\lang1033\i Riddikulus\lang3081\i0\rquote\lang1033  \emdash  and concentrate hard on your grandmother\rquote s clothes. If all goes well, Professor Boggart Snape will be forced into that vulture-topped hat, and that green dress, with that big red handbag.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a great shout of laughter. The wardrobe wobbled more violently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If Neville is successful, the boggart is likely to shift his attention\lang3081  \lang1033 to each of us in turn,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin. \ldblquote I would like all of you to take a moment now to think of the thing that scares you most, and imagine how you might force it to look comical. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The room went quiet. Harry thought \'85 What scared him most in the world?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His first thought was Lord Voldemort \emdash  a Voldemort returned to full strength. But before he had even started to plan a possible counterattack on a boggart-Voldemort, a horrible image came floating to the surface of his mind. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A rotting, glistening hand, slithering back beneath a black cloak \'85 a long, rattling breath from an unseen mouth \'85 then a cold so penetrating it felt like drowning. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry shivered, then looked around, hoping no one had no\-ticed. Many people had their eyes shut tight. Ron was muttering to himself, \ldblquote Take its legs off.\rdblquote  Harry was sure he knew what that was about. Ron\rquote s greatest fear was spiders.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Everyone ready?\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt a lurch of fear. He wasn\rquote t ready. How could you make a dementor less frightening? But he didn\rquote t want to ask for more time; everyone else was nodding and rolling up their sleeves.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Neville, we\rquote re going to back away,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin. \ldblquote Let you have a clear field, all right? I\rquote ll call the next person for\-ward. \'85 Everyone back, now, so Neville can get a clear shot \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They all retreated, backed against the walls, leaving Neville alone beside the wardrobe. He looked pale and frightened, but he had pushed up the sleeves of his robes and was holding his wand ready.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote On the count of three, Neville,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin, who was\lang3081  \lang1033 pointing his own wand at the handle of the wardrobe. \ldblquote One \emdash  two \emdash  three \emdash  \i now\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A jet of sparks shot from the end of Professor Lupin\rquote s wand and hit the doorknob. The wardrobe burst open. Hook-nosed and menacing, Professor Snape stepped out, his eyes flashing at Neville.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville backed away, his wand up, mouthing wordlessly. Snape was bearing down upon him, reaching inside his robes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i R\i0  \emdash  \i r\i0  \emdash  \i riddikulus\i0 !\rdblquote  squeaked Neville.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a noise like a whip crack. Snape stumbled; he was wear\-ing a long, lace-trimmed dress and a towering hat topped with a moth-eaten vulture, and he was swinging a huge crimson handbag.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a roar of laughter; the boggart paused, confused, and Professor Lupin shouted, \ldblquote Parvati! Forward!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Parvati walked forward, her face set. Snape rounded on her. There was another crack, and where he had stood was a blood\-stained, bandaged mummy; its sightless face was turned to Parvati and it began to walk toward her very slowly, dragging its feet, its stiff arms rising \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Riddikulus\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 cried Parvati.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A bandage unraveled at the mummy\rquote s feet; it became entangled, fell face forward, and its head rolled off.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Seamus!\rdblquote  roared Professor Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Seamus darted past Parvati.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Crack\i0 ! Where the mummy had been was a woman with floor-length black hair and a skeletal, green-tinged face \emdash  a banshee. She opened her mouth wide and an unearthly sound filled the room, a long, wailing shriek that made the hair on Harry\rquote s head stand on end \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Riddikulus\i0 !\rdblquote  shouted Seamus.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The banshee made a rasping noise and clutched her throat; her voice was gone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Crack\i0 ! The banshee turned into a rat, which chased its tail in a circle, then \emdash  \i crack\i0 ! \emdash  became a rattlesnake, which slithered and writhed before \emdash  \i crack\i0 !\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  becoming a single, bloody eyeball.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s confused!\rdblquote  shouted Lupin. \ldblquote We\rquote re getting there! Dean!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dean hurried forward.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Crack\i0 !\lang3081  \lang1033 The eyeball became a severed hand, which flipped over and began to creep along the floor like a crab.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Riddikulus\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 yelled Dean.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a snap, and the hand was trapped in a mousetrap.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excellent! Ron, you next!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron leapt forward.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Crack\i0 !\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Quite a few people screamed. A giant spider, six feet tall and cov\-ered in hair, was advancing on Ron, clicking its pincers menac\-ingly. For a moment, Harry thought Ron had frozen. Then \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Riddikulus\i0 !\rdblquote  bellowed Ron, and the spider\rquote s legs vanished; it rolled over and over; Lavender Brown squealed and ran out of its way and it came to a halt at Harry\rquote s feet. He raised his wand, ready, but \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here!\rdblquote  shouted Professor Lupin suddenly, hurrying forward.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Crack\i0 !\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The legless spider had vanished. For a second, everyone looked wildly around to see where it was. Then they saw a silvery-white orb hanging in the air in front of Lupin, who said, \ldblquote\i Riddikulus\i0 !\rdblquote  al\-most lazily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Crack\i0 !\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Forward, Neville, and finish him off!\rdblquote  said Lupin as the boggart landed on the floor as a cockroach. \i Crack\i0 ! Snape was back. This time Neville charged forward looking determined.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Riddikulus\i0 !\rdblquote  he shouted, and they had a split second\rquote s view of Snape in his lacy dress before Neville let out a great \lang3081\ldblquote\lang1033 Ha!\lang3081\rdblquote\lang1033  of laugh\-ter, and the boggart exploded, burst into a thousand tiny wisps of smoke, and was gone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excellent!\rdblquote  cried Professor Lupin as the class broke into applause. \ldblquote Excellent, Neville. Well done, everyone. \'85 Let me see \'85 five points to Gryffindor for every person to tackle the bog\-gart \emdash  ten for Neville because he did it twice \'85 and five each to Hermione and Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But I didn\rquote t do anything,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You and Hermione answered my questions correctly at the start of the class, Harry,\rdblquote  Lupin said lightly. \ldblquote Very well, everyone, an ex\-cellent lesson. Homework, kindly read the chapter on boggarts and summarize it for me \'85 to be handed in on Monday. That will be all.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Talking excitedly, the class left the staffroom. Harry, however, wasn\rquote t feeling cheerful. Professor Lupin had deliberately stopped him from tackling the boggart. Why? Was it because he\rquote d seen Harry collapse on the train, and thought he wasn\rquote t up to much? Had he thought Harry would pass out again?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But no one else seemed to have noticed anything.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you see me take that banshee?\rdblquote  shouted Seamus.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And the hand!\rdblquote  said Dean, waving his own around.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And Snape in that hat!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And my mummy!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wonder why Professor Lupin\rquote s frightened of crystal balls?\rdblquote  said Lavender thoughtfully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was the best Defense Against the Dark Arts lesson we\rquote ve ever had, wasn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Ron excitedly as they made their way back to the classroom to get their bags.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He seems like a very good teacher,\rdblquote  said Hermione approvingly. \ldblquote But I wish I could have had a turn with the boggart \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What would it have been for you?\rdblquote  said Ron, sniggering. \ldblquote A piece of homework that only got nine out of\lang3081  \lang1033 ten?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
