In no time at all, Defense Against the Dark Arts had become most people\rquote s favorite class. Only Draco Malfoy and his gang of Slytherins had anything bad to say about Professor Lupin.\par
\ldblquote Look at the state of his robes,\rdblquote  Malfoy would say in a loud whisper as Professor Lupin passed. \ldblquote He dresses like our old house-elf.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But no one else cared that Professor Lupin\rquote s robes were patched and frayed. His next few lessons were just as interesting as the first. After boggarts, they studied Red Caps, nasty little goblinlike creatures that lurked wherever there had been bloodshed: in the dungeons of castles and the potholes of deserted battlefields, waiting to bludgeon those who had gotten lost. From Red Caps they moved on to kappas, creepy water-dwellers that looked like scaly monkeys, with webbed hands itching to strangle unwitting waders in their ponds.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry only wished he was as happy with some of his other\lang3081  \lang1033 classes. Worst of all was Potions. Snape was in a particularly vin\-dictive mood these days, and no one was in any doubt why. The story of the boggart assuming Snape\rquote s shape, and the way that Neville had dressed it in his grandmother\rquote s clothes, had traveled through the school like wildfire. Snape didn\rquote t seem to find it funny. His eyes flashed menacingly at the very mention of Professor Lupin\rquote s name, and he was bullying Neville worse than ever.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was also growing to dread the hours he spent in Professor Trelawney\rquote s stifling tower room, deciphering lopsided shapes and symbols, trying to ignore the way Professor Trelawney\rquote s enormous eyes filled with tears every time she looked at him. He couldn\rquote t like Professor Trelawney, even though she was treated with respect bor\-dering on reverence by many of the class. Parvati Patil and Laven\-der Brown had taken to haunting Professor Trelawney\rquote s tower room at lunchtimes, and always returned with annoyingly superior looks on their faces, as though they knew things the others didn\rquote t. They had also started using hushed voices whenever they spoke to Harry, as though he were on his deathbed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nobody really liked Care of Magical Creatures, which, after the action-packed first class, had become extremely dull. Hagrid seemed to have lost his confidence. They were now spending lesson after lesson learning how to look after flobberworms, which had to be some of the most boring creatures in existence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why would anyone \i bother\i0  looking after them?\rdblquote  said Ron, after yet another hour of poking shredded lettuce down the flobber\-worms\rquote  slimy throats.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At the start of October, however, Harry had something else to occupy him, something so enjoyable it more than made up for his\lang3081  \lang1033 unsatisfactory classes. The Quidditch season was approaching, and Oliver Wood, Captain of the Gryffindor team, called a meeting one Thursday evening to discuss tactics for the new season.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There were seven people on a Quidditch team: three Chasers, whose job it was to score goals by putting the Quaffle (a red, soccer-sized ball) through one of the fifty-foot-high hoops at each end of the field; two Beaters, who were equipped with heavy bats to repel the Bludgers (two heavy black balls that zoomed around trying to attack the players); a Keeper, who defended the goal posts, and the Seeker, who had the hardest job of all, that of catch\-ing the Golden Snitch, a tiny, winged, walnut-sized ball, whose capture ended the game and earned the Seeker\rquote s team an extra one hundred and fifty points.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Oliver Wood was a burly seventeen-year-old, now in his seventh and final year at Hogwarts. There was a quiet sort of desperation in his voice as he addressed his six fellow team members in the chilly locker rooms on the edge of the darkening Quidditch field.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is our last chance \emdash  \i my\i0  last chance \emdash  to win the Quid\-ditch Cup,\rdblquote  he told them, striding up and down in front of them. \ldblquote I\rquote ll be leaving at the end of this year. I\rquote ll never get another shot at it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Gryffindor hasn\rquote t won for seven years now. Okay, so we\rquote ve had the worst luck in the world \emdash  injuries \emdash  then the tournament getting called off last year. \'85\rdblquote  Wood swallowed, as though the memory still brought a lump to his throat. \ldblquote But we also know we\rquote ve got the \i best\i0  \emdash  \i ruddy\i0  \emdash  \i team\i0  \emdash  \i in\i0  \emdash  \i the\i0  \emdash  \i school,\i0\rdblquote  he said, punching a fist into his other hand, the old manic glint back in his eye.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve got three \i superb\i0  Chasers.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Wood pointed at Alicia Spinnet, Angelina Johnson, and Katie Bell.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve got two \i unbeatable\i0  Beaters.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stop it, Oliver, you\rquote re embarrassing us,\rdblquote  said Fred and George Weasley together, pretending to blush.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And we\rquote ve got a Seeker who has \i never failed to win us a match\i0 !\rdblquote  Wood rumbled, glaring at Harry with a kind of furious pride. \ldblquote And me,\rdblquote  he added as an afterthought.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We think you\rquote re very good too, Oliver,\rdblquote  said George.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Spanking good Keeper,\rdblquote  said Fred.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The point is,\rdblquote  Wood went on, resuming his pacing, \ldblquote the Quid\-ditch Cup should have had our name on it these last two years. Ever since Harry joined the team, I\rquote ve thought the thing was in the bag. But we haven\rquote t got it, and this year\rquote s the last chance we\rquote ll get to finally see our name on the thing. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Wood spoke so dejectedly that even Fred and George looked sympathetic.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oliver, this year\rquote s our year,\rdblquote  said Fred.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ll do it, Oliver!\rdblquote  said Angelina.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Definitely,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Full of determination, the team started training sessions, three evenings a week. The weather was getting colder and wetter, the nights darker, but no amount of mud, wind, or rain could tarnish Harry\rquote s wonderful vision of finally winning the huge, silver Quid\-ditch Cup.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry returned to the Gryffindor common room one evening after training, cold and stiff but pleased with the way practice had gone, to find the room buzzing excitedly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s happened?\rdblquote  he asked Ron and Hermione, who were sit\-ting in two of the best chairs by the fireside and completing some star charts for Astronomy.\lang3081\par
