\lang1033\ldblquote Professor McGonagall told me,\rdblquote  said Lupin, passing Harry a chipped mug of tea. \ldblquote You\rquote re not worried, are you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He thought for a moment of telling Lupin about the dog he\rquote d seen in Magnolia Crescent but decided not to. He didn\rquote t want Lupin to think he was a coward, especially since Lupin already seemed to think he couldn\rquote t cope with a boggart.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Something of Harry\rquote s thoughts seemed to have shown on his face, because Lupin said, \ldblquote Anything worrying you, Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  Harry lied. He drank a bit of tea and watched the grindy\-low brandishing a fist at him. \ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  he said suddenly, putting his tea down on Lupin\rquote s desk. \ldblquote You know that day we fought the bog\-gart?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Lupin slowly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why didn\rquote t you let me fight it?\rdblquote  said Harry abruptly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin raised his eyebrows.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I would have thought that was obvious, Harry,\rdblquote  he said, sound\-ing surprised.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, who had expected Lupin to deny that he\rquote d done any such thing, was taken aback.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  he said again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Lupin, frowning slightly, \ldblquote I assumed that if the bog\-gart faced you, it would assume the shape of Lord Voldemort.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stared. Not only was this the last answer he\rquote d expected, but Lupin had said Voldemort\rquote s name. The only person Harry had ever heard say the name aloud (apart from himself) was Professor Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Clearly, I was wrong,\rdblquote  said Lupin, still frowning at Harry. \ldblquote But I didn\rquote t think it a good idea for Lord Voldemort to materialize in the staffroom. I imagined that people would panic.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t think of Voldemort,\rdblquote  said Harry honestly. \ldblquote I \emdash  I remembered those dementors.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I see,\rdblquote  said Lupin thoughtfully. \ldblquote Well, well \'85 I\rquote m impressed.\rdblquote  He smiled slightly at the look of surprise on Harry\rquote s face. \ldblquote That suggests that what you fear most of all is \emdash  fear. Very wise, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry didn\rquote t know what to say to that, so he drank some more tea.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So you\rquote ve been thinking that I didn\rquote t believe you capable of fighting the boggart?\rdblquote  said Lupin shrewdly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry. He was suddenly feeling a lot hap\-pier. \ldblquote Professor Lupin, you know the dementors \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was interrupted by a knock on the door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come in,\rdblquote  called Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door opened, and in came Snape. He was carrying a goblet, which was smoking faintly, and stopped at the sight of Harry, his black eyes narrowing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, Severus,\rdblquote  said Lupin, smiling. \ldblquote Thanks very much. Could you leave it here on the desk for me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape set down the smoking goblet, his eyes wandering between Harry and Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was just showing Harry my grindylow,\rdblquote  said Lupin pleasantly, pointing at the tank.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fascinating,\rdblquote  said Snape, without looking at it. \ldblquote You should drink that directly, Lupin.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, yes, I will,\rdblquote  said Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I made an entire cauldronful,\rdblquote  Snape continued. \ldblquote If you need more.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I should probably take some again tomorrow. Thanks very much, Severus.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not at all,\rdblquote  said Snape, but there was a look in his eye Harry didn\rquote t like. He backed out of the room, unsmiling and watchful.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked curiously at the goblet. Lupin smiled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Snape has very kindly concocted a potion for me,\rdblquote  he\lang3081  \lang1033 said. \ldblquote I have never been much of a potion-brewer and this one is particularly complex.\rdblquote  He picked up the goblet and sniffed it. \ldblquote Pity sugar makes it useless,\rdblquote  he added, taking a sip and shuddering.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why \emdash  ?\rdblquote  Harry began. Lupin looked at him and answered the unfinished question.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve been feeling a bit off-color,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote This potion is the only thing that helps. I am very lucky to be working alongside Pro\-fessor Snape; there aren\rquote t many wizards who are up to making it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Lupin took another sip and Harry had a crazy urge to knock the goblet out of his hands.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Snape\rquote s very interested in the Dark Arts,\rdblquote  he blurted out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Really?\rdblquote  said Lupin, looking only mildly interested as he took another gulp of potion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Some people reckon \emdash\rdblquote  Harry hesitated, then plunged reck\-lessly on, \ldblquote some people reckon he\rquote d do anything to get the Defense Against the Dark Arts job.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin drained the goblet and pulled a face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Disgusting,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Well, Harry, I\rquote d better get back to work. I\rquote ll see you at the feast later.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Harry, putting down his empty teacup.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The empty goblet was still smoking.\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There you go,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote We got as much as we could carry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A shower of brilliantly colored sweets fell into Harry\rquote s lap. It was dusk, and Ron and Hermione had just turned up in the common room, pink-faced from the cold wind and looking as though they\rquote d had the time of their lives.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry, picking up a packet of tiny black Pepper Imps. \ldblquote What\rquote s Hogsmeade like? Where did you go?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 By the sound of it \emdash  everywhere. Dervish and Banges, the wiz\-arding equipment shop, Zonko\rquote s Joke Shop, into the Three Broom\-sticks for foaming mugs of hot butterbeer, and many places besides.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The post office, Harry! About two hundred owls, all sitting on shelves, all color-coded depending on how fast you want your let\-ter to get there!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Honeydukes has got a new kind of fudge; they were giving out free samples, there\rquote s a bit, look \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We \i think\i0  we saw an ogre, honestly, they get all sorts at the Three Broomsticks \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wish we could have brought you some butterbeer, really warms you up \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What did you do?\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking anxious. \ldblquote Did you get any work done?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Lupin made me a cup of tea in his office. And then Snape came in. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He told them all about the goblet. Ron\rquote s mouth fell open.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Lupin drank it\i0 ?\rdblquote  he gasped. \ldblquote Is he mad?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione checked her watch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote d better go down, you know, the feast\rquote ll be starting in five minutes. \'85\rdblquote  They hurried through the portrait hole and into the crowd, still discussing Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But if he \emdash  you know\rdblquote  \emdash  Hermione dropped her voice, glancing nervously around \emdash  \ldblquote if he \i was\i0  trying to \emdash  to poison Lupin \emdash  he wouldn\rquote t have done it in front of Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, maybe,\rdblquote  said Harry as they reached the entrance hall and\lang3081  \lang1033 crossed into the Great Hall. It had been decorated with hundreds and hundreds of candle-filled pumpkins, a cloud of fluttering live bats, and many flaming orange streamers, which were swimming lazily across the stormy ceiling like brilliant watersnakes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The food was delicious; even Hermione and Ron, who were full to bursting with Honeydukes sweets, managed second helpings of everything. Harry kept glancing at the staff table. Professor Lupin looked cheerful and as well as he ever did; he was talking animat\-edly to tiny little Professor Flitwick, the Charms teacher. Harry moved his eyes along the table, to the place where Snape sat. Was he imagining it, or were Snape\rquote s eyes flickering toward Lupin more often than was natural?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The feast finished with an entertainment provided by the Hog\-warts ghosts. They popped out of the walls and tables to do a bit of formation gliding; Nearly Headless Nick, the Gryffindor ghost, had a great success with a reenactment of his own botched be\-heading.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It had been such a pleasant evening that Harry\rquote s good mood couldn\rquote t even be spoiled by Malfoy, who shouted through the crowd as they all left the hall, \ldblquote The dementors send their love, Potter!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, Ron, and Hermione followed the rest of the Gryffindors along the usual path to Gryffindor Tower, but when they reached the corridor that ended with the portrait of the Fat Lady, they found it jammed with students.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why isn\rquote t anyone going in?\rdblquote  said Ron curiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry peered over the heads in front of him. The portrait seemed to be closed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let me through, please,\rdblquote  came Percy\rquote s voice, and he came bustling importantly through the crowd. \ldblquote What\rquote s the holdup here? You can\rquote t all have forgotten the password \emdash  excuse me, I\rquote m Head Boy\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then a silence fell over the crowd, from the front first, so that a chill seemed to spread down the corridor. They heard Percy say, in a suddenly sharp voice, \ldblquote Somebody get Professor Dumble\-dore. Quick.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 People\rquote s heads turned; those at the back were standing on tip\-toe.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s going on?\rdblquote  said Ginny, who had just arrived.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A moment later, Professor Dumbledore was there, sweeping toward the portrait; the Gryffindors squeezed together to let him through, and Harry, Ron, and Hermione moved closer to see what the trouble was.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, my \emdash\rdblquote  Hermione grabbed Harry\rquote s arm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Fat Lady had vanished from her portrait, which had been slashed so viciously that strips of canvas littered the floor; great chunks of it had been torn away completely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore took one quick look at the ruined painting and turned, his eyes somber, to see Professors McGonagall, Lupin, and Snape hurrying toward him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We need to find her,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Professor McGona\-gall, please go to Mr. Filch at once and tell him to search every painting in the castle for the Fat Lady.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ll be lucky!\rdblquote  said a cackling voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was Peeves the Poltergeist, bobbing over the crowd and look\-ing delighted, as he always did, at the sight of wreckage or worry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you mean, Peeves?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore calmly, and Peeves\rquote s grin faded a little. He didn\rquote t dare taunt Dumbledore. In\-stead he adopted an oily voice that was no better than his cackle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ashamed, Your Headship, sir. Doesn\rquote t want to be seen. She\rquote s a horrible mess. Saw her running through the landscape up on the fourth floor, sir, dodging between the trees. Crying something dreadful,\rdblquote  he said happily. \ldblquote Poor thing,\rdblquote  he added unconvincingly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did she say who did it?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes, Professorhead,\rdblquote  said Peeves, with the air of one cradling a large bombshell in his arms. \ldblquote He got very angry when she wouldn\rquote t let him in, you see.\rdblquote  Peeves flipped over and grinned at Dumbledore from between his own legs. \ldblquote Nasty temper he\rquote s got, that Sirius Black.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
