Professor Dumbledore sent all the Gryffindors back to the Great Hall, where they were joined ten minutes later by the students from Hufflepuff, Ravenclaw, and Slytherin, who all looked extremely confused.\par
\ldblquote The teachers and I need to conduct a thorough search of the castle,\rdblquote  Professor Dumbledore told them as Professors McGonagall and Flitwick closed all doors into the hall. \ldblquote I\rquote m afraid that, for your own safety, you will have to spend the night here. I want the pre\-fects to stand guard over the entrances to the hall and I am leaving the Head Boy and Girl in charge. Any disturbance should be re\-ported to me immediately,\rdblquote  he added to Percy, who was looking immensely proud and important. \ldblquote Send word with one of the ghosts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Dumbledore paused, about to leave the hall, and said, \ldblquote Oh, yes, you\rquote ll be needing \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 One casual wave of his wand and the long tables flew to the edges of the hall and stood themselves against the walls; another wave, and the floor was covered with hundreds of squashy purple sleeping bags.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sleep well,\rdblquote  said Professor Dumbledore, closing the door be\-hind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The hall immediately began to buzz excitedly; the Gryffindors were telling the rest of the school what had just happened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Everyone into their sleeping bags!\rdblquote  shouted Percy. \ldblquote Come on, now, no more talking! Lights out in ten minutes!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote C\rquote mon,\rdblquote  Ron said to Harry and Hermione; they seized three sleeping bags and dragged them into a corner.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do you think Black\rquote s still in the castle?\rdblquote  Hermione whispered anxiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore obviously thinks he might be,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s very lucky he picked tonight, you know,\rdblquote  said Hermione as they climbed fully dressed into their sleeping bags and propped themselves on their elbows to talk. \ldblquote The one night we weren\rquote t in the tower. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I reckon he\rquote s lost track of time, being on the run,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Didn\rquote t realize it was Halloween. Otherwise he\rquote d have come burst\-ing in here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione shuddered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 All around them, people were asking one another the same ques\-tion: \ldblquote\i How did he get in\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe he knows how to Apparate,\rdblquote  said a Ravenclaw a few feet away. \ldblquote Just appear out of thin air, you know.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Disguised himself, probably,\rdblquote  said a Hufflepuff fifth year.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He could\rquote ve flown in,\rdblquote  suggested Dean Thomas.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Honestly, am I the \i only\i0  person who\rquote s ever bothered to read \i Hogwarts, A History\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Hermione crossly to Harry and Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Probably,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Why?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because the castle\rquote s protected by more than \i walls,\i0  you know,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote There are all sorts of enchantments on it, to stop people entering by stealth. You can\rquote t just Apparate in here. And I\rquote d like to see the disguise that could fool those dementors. They\rquote re guarding every single entrance to the grounds. They\rquote d have seen him fly in too. And Filch knows all the secret passages, they\rquote ll have them covered. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The lights are going out now!\rdblquote  Percy shouted. \ldblquote I want everyone in their sleeping bags and no more talking!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The candles all went out at once. The only light now came from the silvery ghosts, who were drifting about talking seriously to the prefects, and the enchanted ceiling, which, like the sky outside, was scattered with stars. What with that, and the whispering that still filled the hall, Harry felt as though he were sleeping outdoors in a light wind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Once every hour, a teacher would reappear in the hall to check that everything was quiet. Around three in the morning, when many students had finally fallen asleep, Professor Dumbledore came in. Harry watched him looking around for Percy, who had been prowling between the sleeping bags, telling people off for talking. Percy was only a short way away from Harry, Ron, and Hermione, who quickly pretended to be asleep as Dumbledore\rquote s footsteps drew nearer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Any sign of him, Professor?\rdblquote  asked Percy in a whisper.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No. All well here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Everything under control, sir.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good. There\rquote s no point moving them all now. I\rquote ve found a tem\-porary guardian for the Gryffindor portrait hole. You\rquote ll be able to move them back in tomorrow.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And the Fat Lady, sir?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hiding in a map of Argyllshire on the second floor. Apparently she refused to let Black in without the password, so he attacked. She\rquote s still very distressed, but once she\rquote s calmed down, I\rquote ll have Mr. Filch restore her.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry heard the door of the hall creak open again, and more footsteps.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Headmaster?\rdblquote  It was Snape. Harry kept quite still, listening hard. \ldblquote The whole of the third floor has been searched. He\rquote s not there. And Filch has done the dungeons; nothing there either.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What about the Astronomy tower? Professor Trelawney\rquote s room? The Owlery?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All searched \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well, Severus. I didn\rquote t really expect Black to linger.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Have you any theory as to how he got in, Professor?\rdblquote  asked Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry raised his head very slightly off his arms to free his other ear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Many, Severus, each of them as unlikely as the next.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry opened his eyes a fraction and squinted up to where they stood; Dumbledore\rquote s back was to him, but he could see Percy\rquote s face, rapt with attention, and Snape\rquote s profile, which looked angry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You remember the conversation we had, Headmaster, just\lang3081  \lang1033 before \emdash  ah \emdash  the start of term?\rdblquote  said Snape, who was barely open\-ing his lips, as though trying to block Percy out of the conversation.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I do, Severus,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, and there was something like warning in his voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It seems \emdash  almost impossible \emdash  that Black could have entered the school without inside help. I did express my concerns when you appointed \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I do not believe a single person inside this castle would have helped Black enter it,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, and his tone made it so clear that the subject was closed that Snape didn\rquote t reply. \ldblquote I must go down to the dementors,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote I said I would inform them when our search was complete.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Didn\rquote t they want to help, sir?\rdblquote  said Percy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore coldly. \ldblquote But I\rquote m afraid no dementor will cross the threshold of this castle while I am headmaster.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Percy looked slightly abashed. Dumbledore left the hall, walking quickly and quietly. Snape stood for a moment, watching the head\-master with an expression of deep resentment on his face; then he too left.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry glanced sideways at Ron and Hermione. Both of them had their eyes open too, reflecting the starry ceiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What was all that about?\rdblquote  Ron mouthed.\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 The school talked of nothing but Sirius Black for the next few days. The theories about how he had entered the castle became wilder and wilder; Hannah Abbott, from Hufflepuff, spent much of their next Herbology class telling anyone who\rquote d listen that Black could turn into a flowering shrub.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Fat Lady\rquote s ripped canvas had been taken off the wall and\lang3081  \lang1033 replaced with the portrait of Sir Cadogan and his fat gray pony. Nobody was very happy about this. Sir Cadogan spent half his time challenging people to duels, and the rest thinking up ridiculously complicated passwords, which he changed at least twice a day.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s a complete lunatic,\rdblquote  said Seamus Finnigan angrily to Percy. \ldblquote Can\rquote t we get anyone else?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote None of the other pictures wanted the job,\rdblquote  said Percy. \ldblquote Fright\-ened of what happened to the Fat Lady. Sir Cadogan was the only one brave enough to volunteer.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sir Cadogan, however, was the least of Harry\rquote s worries. He was now being closely watched. Teachers found excuses to walk along corridors with him, and Percy Weasley (acting, Harry suspected, on his mother\rquote s orders) was tailing him everywhere like an ex\-tremely pompous guard dog. To cap it all, Professor McGonagall summoned Harry into her office, with such a somber expression on her face Harry thought someone must have died.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s no point hiding it from you any longer, Potter,\rdblquote  she said in a very serious voice. \ldblquote I know this will come as a shock to you, but Sirius Black \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know he\rquote s after me,\rdblquote  said Harry wearily. \ldblquote I heard Ron\rquote s dad telling his mum. Mr. Weasley works for the Ministry of Magic.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor McGonagall seemed very taken aback. She stared at Harry for a moment or two, then said, \ldblquote I see! Well, in that case, Potter, you\rquote ll understand why I don\rquote t think it\rquote s a good idea for you to be practicing Quidditch in the evenings. Out on the field with only your team members, it\rquote s very exposed, Potter \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve got our first match on Saturday!\rdblquote  said Harry, outraged. \ldblquote I\rquote ve got to train, Professor!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor McGonagall considered him intently. Harry knew she\lang3081  \lang1033 was deeply interested in the Gryffindor team\rquote s prospects; it had been she, after all, who\rquote d suggested him as Seeker in the first place. He waited, holding his breath.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hmm \'85\rdblquote  Professor McGonagall stood up and stared out of the window at the Quidditch field, just visible through the rain. \ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 goodness knows, I\rquote d like to see us win the Cup at last\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 but all the same, Potter \'85 I\rquote d be happier if a teacher were present. I\rquote ll ask Madam Hooch to oversee your training sessions.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 The weather worsened steadily as the first Quidditch match drew nearer. Undaunted, the Gryffindor team was training harder than ever under the eye of Madam Hooch. Then, at their final training session before Saturday\rquote s match, Oliver Wood gave his team some unwelcome news.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re not playing Slytherin!\rdblquote  he told them, looking very angry. \ldblquote Flint\rquote s just been to see me. We\rquote re playing Hufflepuff instead.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  chorused the rest of the team.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Flint\rquote s excuse is that their Seeker\rquote s arm\rquote s still injured,\rdblquote  said Wood, grinding his teeth furiously. \ldblquote But it\rquote s obvious why they\rquote re doing it. Don\rquote t want to play in this weather. Think it\rquote ll damage their chances. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
