Madam Pomfrey insisted on keeping Harry in the hospital wing for the rest of the weekend. He didn\rquote t argue or complain, but he wouldn\rquote t let her throw away the shattered rem\-nants of his Nimbus Two Thousand. He knew he was being stupid, knew that the Nimbus was beyond repair, but Harry couldn\rquote t help it; he felt as though he\rquote d lost one of his best friends.\par
He had a stream of visitors, all intent on cheering him up. Ha\-grid sent him a bunch of earwiggy flowers that looked like yellow cabbages, and Ginny Weasley, blushing furiously, turned up with a get-well card she had made herself, which sang shrilly unless Harry kept it shut under his bowl of fruit. The Gryffindor team visited again on Sunday morning, this time accompanied by Wood, who told Harry (in a hollow, dead sort of voice) that he didn\rquote t blame him in the slightest. Ron and Hermione left Harry\rquote s bedside only at night. But nothing anyone said or did could make Harry feel any better, because they knew only half of what was troubling him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He hadn\rquote t told anyone about the Grim, not even Ron and Hermione, because he knew Ron would panic and Hermione would scoff. The fact remained, however, that it had now appeared twice, and both appearances had been followed by near-fatal acci\-dents; the first time, he had nearly been run over by the Knight Bus; the second, fallen fifty feet from his broomstick. Was the Grim going to haunt him until he actually died? Was he going to spend the rest of his life looking over his shoulder for the beast?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then there were the dementors. Harry felt sick and humili\-ated every time he thought of them. Everyone said the dementors were horrible, but no one else collapsed every time they went near one. No one else heard echoes in their head of their dying parents.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Because Harry knew who that screaming voice belonged to now. He had heard her words, heard them over and over again during the night hours in the hospital wing while he lay awake, staring at the strips of moonlight on the ceiling. When the dementors ap\-proached him, he heard the last moments of his mother\rquote s life, her attempts to protect him, Harry, from Lord Voldemort, and Volde\-mort\rquote s laughter before he murdered her. \'85 Harry dozed fitfully, sinking into dreams full of clammy, rotted hands and petrified pleading, jerking awake to dwell again on his mother\rquote s voice.\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 It was a relief to return to the noise and bustle of the main school on Monday, where he was forced to think about other things, even if he had to endure Draco Malfoy\rquote s taunting. Malfoy was almost beside himself with glee at Gryffindor\rquote s defeat. He had finally taken off his bandages, and celebrated having the full use of both arms again by doing spirited imitations of Harry falling off his broom.\lang3081  \lang1033 Malfoy spent much of their next Potions class doing dementor im\-itations across the dungeon; Ron finally cracked and flung a large, slippery crocodile heart at Malfoy, which hit him in the face and caused Snape to take fifty points from Gryffindor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If Snape\rquote s teaching Defense Against the Dark Arts again, I\rquote m skiving off,\rdblquote  said Ron as they headed toward Lupin\rquote s classroom af\-ter lunch. \ldblquote Check who\rquote s in there, Hermione.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione peered around the classroom door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s okay!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Lupin was back at work. It certainly looked as though he had been ill. His old robes were hanging more loosely on him and there were dark shadows beneath his eyes; nevertheless, he smiled at the class as they took their seats, and they burst at once into an explosion of complaints about Snape\rquote s behavior while Lupin had been ill.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s not fair, he was only filling in, why should he give us home\-work?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We don\rquote t know anything about werewolves \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  two rolls of parchment!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you tell Professor Snape we haven\rquote t covered them yet?\rdblquote  Lupin asked, frowning slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The babble broke out again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but he said we were really behind \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  he wouldn\rquote t listen \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  \i two rolls of parchment\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Lupin smiled at the look of indignation on every face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry. I\rquote ll speak to Professor Snape. You don\rquote t have to do the essay.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \i no,\i0\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking very disappointed. \ldblquote I\rquote ve al\-ready finished it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They had a very enjoyable lesson. Professor Lupin had brought along a glass box containing a hinkypunk, a little one-legged crea\-ture who looked as though he were made of wisps of smoke, rather frail and harmless-looking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lures travelers into bogs,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin as they took notes. \ldblquote You notice the lantern dangling from his hand? Hops ahead \emdash\lang3081  \lang1033 people follow the light \emdash  then \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The hinkypunk made a horrible squelching noise against the glass.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When the bell rang, everyone gathered up their things and headed for the door, Harry among them, but \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait a moment, Harry,\rdblquote  Lupin called. \ldblquote I\rquote d like a word.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry doubled back and watched Professor Lupin covering the hinkypunk\rquote s box with a cloth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I heard about the match,\rdblquote  said Lupin, turning back to his desk and starting to pile books into his briefcase, \ldblquote and I\rquote m sorry about your broomstick. Is there any chance of fixing it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote The tree smashed it to bits.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin sighed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They planted the Whomping Willow the same year that I arrived at Hogwarts. People used to play a game, trying to get near enough to touch the trunk. In the end, a boy called Davey Gudgeon nearly lost an eye, and we were forbidden to go near it. No broomstick would have a chance.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you hear about the dementors too?\rdblquote  said Harry with diffi\-culty.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin looked at him quickly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, I did. I don\rquote t think any of us have seen Professor Dumble\-dore that angry. They have been growing restless for some time \'85 furious at his refusal to let them inside the grounds. \'85 I suppose they were the reason you fell?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry. He hesitated, and then the question he had to ask burst from him before he could stop himself. \ldblquote\i Why\i0 ? Why do they affect me like that? Am I just \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It has nothing to do with weakness,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin sharply, as though he had read Harry\rquote s mind. \ldblquote The dementors af\-fect you worse than the others because there are horrors in your past that the others don\rquote t have.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A ray of wintery sunlight fell across the classroom, illuminating Lupin\rquote s gray hairs and the lines on his young face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dementors are among the foulest creatures that walk this earth. They infest the darkest, filthiest places, they glory in decay and de\-spair, they drain peace, hope, and happiness out of the air around them. Even Muggles feel their presence, though they can\rquote t see them. Get too near a dementor and every good feeling, every happy memory will be sucked out of you. If it can, the dementor will feed on you long enough to reduce you to something like it\-self \'85 soul-less and evil. You\rquote ll be left with nothing but the worst experiences of your life. And the worst that happened to \i you,\i0  Harry, is enough to make anyone fall off their broom. You have nothing to feel ashamed of.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote When they get near me \emdash\rdblquote  Harry stared at Lupin\rquote s desk, his throat tight. \ldblquote I can hear Voldemort murdering my mum.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin made a sudden motion with his arm as though to grip\lang3081  \lang1033 Harry\rquote s shoulder, but thought better of it. There was a moment\rquote s si\-lence, then \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why did they have to come to the match?\rdblquote  said Harry bitterly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re getting hungry,\rdblquote  said Lupin coolly, shutting his briefcase with a snap. \ldblquote Dumbledore won\rquote t let them into the school, so their supply of human prey has dried up. \'85 I don\rquote t think they could resist the large crowd around the Quidditch field. All that excite\-ment \'85 emotions running high \'85 it was their idea of a feast.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Azkaban must be terrible,\rdblquote  Harry muttered. Lupin nodded grimly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The fortress is set on a tiny island, way out to sea, but they don\rquote t need walls and water to keep the prisoners in, not when they\rquote re all trapped inside their own heads, incapable of a single cheerful thought. Most of them go mad within weeks.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But Sirius Black escaped from them,\rdblquote  Harry said slowly. \ldblquote He got away. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin\rquote s briefcase slipped from the desk; he had to stoop quickly to catch it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  he said, straightening up, \ldblquote Black must have found a way to fight them. I wouldn\rquote t have believed it possible. \'85 Dementors are supposed to drain a wizard of his powers if he is left with them too long. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i You\i0  made that dementor on the train back off,\rdblquote  said Harry sud\-denly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There are \emdash  certain defenses one can use,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote But there was only one dementor on the train. The more there are, the more difficult it becomes to resist.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What defenses?\rdblquote  said Harry at once. \ldblquote Can you teach me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t pretend to be an expert at fighting dementors, Harry \'85 quite the contrary. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But if the dementors come to another Quidditch match, I need to be able to fight them \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin looked into Harry\rquote s determined face, hesitated, then said, \ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 all right. I\rquote ll try and help. But it\rquote ll have to wait until next term, I\rquote m afraid. I have a lot to do before the holidays. I chose a very inconvenient time to fall ill.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 What with the promise of anti-dementor lessons from Lupin, the thought that he might never have to hear his mother\rquote s death again, and the fact that Ravenclaw flattened Hufflepuff in their Quid\-ditch match at the end of November, Harry\rquote s mood took a definite upturn. Gryffindor were not out of the running after all, although they could not afford to lose another match. Wood became repos\-sessed of his manic energy, and worked his team as hard as ever in the chilly haze of rain that persisted into December. Harry saw no hint of a dementor within the grounds. Dumbledore\rquote s anger seemed to be keeping them at their stations at the entrances.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Two weeks before the end of the term, the sky lightened sud\-denly to a dazzling, opaline white and the muddy grounds were re\-vealed one morning covered in glittering frost. Inside the castle, there was a buzz of Christmas in the air. Professor Flitwick, the Charms teacher, had already decorated his classroom with shim\-mering lights that turned out to be real, fluttering fairies. The stu\-dents were all happily discussing their plans for the holidays. Both Ron and Hermione had decided to remain at Hogwarts, and though Ron said it was because he couldn\rquote t stand two weeks with\lang3081  \lang1033 Percy, and Hermione insisted she needed to use the library, Harry wasn\rquote t fooled; they were doing it to keep him company, and he was very grateful.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 To everyone\rquote s delight except Harry\rquote s, there was to be another Hogsmeade trip on the very last weekend of the term.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We can do all our Christmas shopping there!\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Mum and Dad would really love those Toothflossing Stringmints from Honeydukes!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Resigned to the fact that he would be the only third year staying behind again, Harry borrowed a copy of \i Which Broomstick\i0  from Wood, and decided to spend the day reading up on the different makes. He had been riding one of the school brooms at team prac\-tice, an ancient Shooting Star, which was very slow and jerky; he definitely needed a new broom of his own.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 On the Saturday morning of the Hogsmeade trip, Harry bid good-bye to Ron and Hermione, who were wrapped in cloaks and scarves, then turned up the marble staircase alone, and headed back toward Gryffindor Tower. Snow had started to fall outside the win\-dows, and the castle was very still and quiet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Psst \emdash  Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He turned, halfway along the third-floor corridor, to see Fred and George peering out at him from behind a statue of a hump\-backed, one-eyed witch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you doing?\rdblquote  said Harry curiously. \ldblquote How come you\rquote re not going to Hogsmeade?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve come to give you a bit of festive cheer before we go,\rdblquote  said Fred, with a mysterious wink. \ldblquote Come in here. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He nodded toward an empty classroom to the left of the one-eyed statue. Harry followed Fred and George inside. George closed the door quietly and then turned, beaming, to look at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Early Christmas present for you, Harry,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fred pulled something from inside his cloak with a flourish and laid it on one of the desks. It was a large, square, very worn piece of parchment with nothing written on it. Harry, suspecting one of Fred and George\rquote s jokes, stared at it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s that supposed to be?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This, Harry, is the secret of our success,\rdblquote  said George, patting the parchment fondly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s a wrench, giving it to you,\rdblquote  said Fred, \ldblquote but we decided last night, your need\rquote s greater than ours.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anyway, we know it by heart,\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote We bequeath it to you. We don\rquote t really need it anymore.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And what do I need with a bit of old parchment?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A bit of old parchment!\rdblquote  said Fred, closing his eyes with a gri\-mace as though Harry had mortally offended him. \ldblquote Explain, George.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 when we were in our first year, Harry \emdash  young, care\-free, and innocent \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry snorted. He doubted whether Fred and George had ever been innocent.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  well, more innocent than we are now \emdash  we got into a spot of bother with Filch.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We let off a Dungbomb in the corridor and it upset him for some reason \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So he hauled us off to his office and started threatening us with the usual \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  detention \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  disembowelment \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and we couldn\rquote t help noticing a drawer in one of his filing cabinets marked \i Confiscated and Highly Dangerous.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t tell me \emdash\rdblquote  said Harry, starting to grin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, what would you\rquote ve done?\rdblquote  said Fred. \ldblquote George caused a diversion by dropping another Dungbomb, I whipped the drawer open, and grabbed \emdash  \i this.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s not as bad as it sounds, you know,\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote We don\rquote t reckon Filch ever found out how to work it. He probably suspected what it was, though, or he wouldn\rquote t have confiscated it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you know how to work it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes,\rdblquote  said Fred, smirking. \ldblquote This little beauty\rquote s taught us more than all the teachers in this school.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re winding me up,\rdblquote  said Harry, looking at the ragged old bit of parchment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, are we?\rdblquote  said George.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He took out his wand, touched the parchment lightly, and said, \ldblquote\i I solemnly swear that I am up to no good.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And at once, thin ink lines began to spread like a spider\rquote s web from the point that George\rquote s wand had touched. They joined each other, they crisscrossed, they fanned into every corner of the parch\-ment; then words began to blossom across the top, great, curly green words, that proclaimed:\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc Messrs. Moony, Wormtail,\lang3081  \lang1033 Padfoot, and\lang3081  \lang1033 Prongs\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Purveyors of\lang3081  Aids t\lang1033 o Magical Mischief-Makers\lang3081\par
\lang1033 are proud to present\par
The Marauder\rquote s Map\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\par
It was a map showing every detail of the Hogwarts castle and grounds. But the truly remarkable thing were the tiny ink dots moving around it, each labeled with a name in minuscule writing. Astounded, Harry bent over it. A labeled dot in the top left corner showed that Professor Dumbledore was pacing his study; the care\-taker\rquote s cat, Mrs. Norris, was prowling the second floor; and Peeves the Poltergeist was currently bouncing around the trophy room. And as Harry\rquote s eyes traveled up and down the familiar corridors, he noticed something else.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This map showed a set of passages he had never entered. And many of them seemed to lead \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right into Hogsmeade,\rdblquote  said Fred, tracing one of them with his finger. \ldblquote There are seven in all. Now, Filch knows about these four\rdblquote  \emdash  he pointed them out \emdash  \ldblquote but we\rquote re sure we\rquote re the only ones who know about \i these.\i0  Don\rquote t bother with the one behind the mirror on the fourth floor. We used it until last winter, but it\rquote s caved in \emdash  completely blocked. And we don\rquote t reckon anyone\rquote s ever used this one, because the Whomping Willow\rquote s planted right over the entrance. But this one here, this one leads right into the cellar of Honeydukes. We\rquote ve used it loads of times. And as you might\rquote ve noticed, the entrance is right outside this room, through that one-eyed old crone\rquote s hump.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Moony, Wormtail, Padfoot, and Prongs,\rdblquote  sighed George, pat\-ting the heading of the map. \ldblquote We owe them so much.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Noble men, working tirelessly to help a new generation of law-breakers,\rdblquote  said Fred solemnly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said George briskly. \ldblquote Don\rquote t forget to wipe it after you\rquote ve used it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  or anyone can read it,\rdblquote  Fred said warningly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Just tap it again and say, \lang3081\lquote\lang1033 Mischief managed!\lang3081\rquote\lang1033  And it\rquote ll go blank.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, young Harry,\rdblquote  said Fred, in an uncanny impersonation of Percy, \ldblquote mind you behave yourself.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote See you in Honeydukes,\rdblquote  said George, winking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They left the room, both smirking in a satisfied sort of way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stood there, gazing at the miraculous map. He watched the tiny ink Mrs. Norris turn left and pause to sniff at something on the floor. If Filch really didn\rquote t know \'85 he wouldn\rquote t have to pass the dementors at all. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But even as he stood there, flooded with excitement, something Harry had once heard Mr. Weasley say came floating out of his memory.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Never trust anything that can think for itself, if you can\rquote t see where it keeps its brain.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 This map was one of those dangerous magical objects Mr. Weasley had been warning against. \'85 \i Aids for Magical Mischief-Makers\i0  \'85 but then, Harry reasoned, he only wanted to use it to get into Hogsmeade, it wasn\rquote t as though he wanted to steal any\-thing or attack anyone \'85 and Fred and George had been using it for years without anything horrible happening. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry traced the secret passage to Honeydukes with his finger.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then, quite suddenly, as though following orders, he rolled up the map, stuffed it inside his robes, and hurried to the door of the classroom. He opened it a couple of inches. There was no one out\-side. Very carefully, he edged out of the room and behind the statue of the one-eyed witch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 What did he have to do? He pulled out the map again and saw,\lang3081  \lang1033 to his astonishment, that a new ink figure had appeared upon it, la\-beled \i Harry Potter.\i0  This figure was standing exactly where the real Harry was standing, about halfway down the third-floor corridor. Harry watched carefully. His little ink self appeared to be tapping the witch with his minute wand. Harry quickly took out his real wand and tapped the statue. Nothing happened. He looked back at the map. The tiniest speech bubble had appeared next to his figure. The word inside said, \ldblquote\i Dissendium.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Dissendium\i0 !\rdblquote  Harry whispered, tapping the stone witch again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At once, the statue\rquote s hump opened wide enough to admit a fairly thin person. Harry glanced quickly up and down the corridor, then tucked the map away again, hoisted himself into the hole headfirst, and pushed himself forward.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He slid a considerable way down what felt like a stone slide, then landed on cold, damp earth. He stood up, looking around. It was pitch dark. He held up his wand, muttered, \ldblquote\i Lumos\i0 !\rdblquote  and saw that he was in a very narrow, low, earthy passageway. He raised the map, tapped it with the tip of his wand, and muttered, \ldblquote Mischief man\-aged!\rdblquote  The map went blank at once. He folded it carefully, tucked it inside his robes, then, heart beating fast, both excited and appre\-hensive, he set off.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The passage twisted and turned, more like the burrow of a giant rabbit than anything else. Harry hurried along it, stumbling now and then on the uneven floor, holding his wand out in front of him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It took ages, but Harry had the thought of Honeydukes to sus\-tain him. After what felt like an hour, the passage began to rise. Panting, Harry sped up, his face hot, his feet very cold.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ten minutes later, he came to the foot of some worn stone steps, which rose out of sight above him. Careful not to make any noise, Harry began to climb. A hundred steps, two hundred steps, he lost count as he climbed, watching his feet. \'85 Then, without warn\-ing, his head hit something hard.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It seemed to be a trapdoor. Harry stood there, massaging the top of his head, listening. He couldn\rquote t hear any sounds above him. Very slowly, he pushed the trapdoor open and peered over the edge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was in a cellar, which was full of wooden crates and boxes. Harry climbed out of the trapdoor and replaced it \emdash  it blended so perfectly with the dusty floor that it was impossible to tell it was there. Harry crept slowly toward the wooden staircase that led up\-stairs. Now he could definitely hear voices, not to mention the tin\-kle of a bell and the opening and shutting of a door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Wondering what he ought to do, he suddenly heard a door open much closer at hand; somebody was about to come downstairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And get another box of Jelly Slugs, dear, they\rquote ve nearly cleaned us out \emdash\rdblquote  said a woman\rquote s voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A pair of feet was coming down the staircase. Harry leapt behind an enormous crate and waited for the footsteps to pass. He heard the man shifting boxes against the opposite wall. He might not get another chance \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Quickly and silently, Harry dodged out from his hiding place and climbed the stairs; looking back, he saw an enormous backside and shiny bald head, buried in a box. Harry reached the door at the top of the stairs, slipped through it, and found himself behind the counter of Honeydukes \emdash  he ducked, crept sideways, and then straightened up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Honeydukes was so crowded with Hogwarts students that no one looked twice at Harry. He edged among them, looking around, and suppressed a laugh as he imagined the look that would spread over Dudley\rquote s piggy face if he could see where Harry was now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There were shelves upon shelves of the most succulent-looking sweets imaginable. Creamy chunks of nougat, shimmering pink squares of coconut ice, fat, honey-colored toffees; hundreds of dif\-ferent kinds of chocolate in neat rows; there was a large barrel of Every Flavor Beans, and another of Fizzing Whizbees, the levitat\-ing sherbert balls that Ron had mentioned; along yet another wall were \lang3081\ldblquote\lang1033 Special Effects\lang3081\rdblquote\lang1033  sweets: Drooble\rquote s Best Blowing Gum (which filled a room with bluebell-colored bubbles that refused to pop for days), the strange, splintery Toothflossing Stringmints, tiny black Pepper Imps (\lang3081\ldblquote\lang1033 breathe fire for your friends!\lang3081\rdblquote\lang1033 ), Ice Mice (\lang3081\ldblquote\lang1033 hear your teeth chatter and squeak!\lang3081\rdblquote\lang1033 ), peppermint creams shaped like toads (\lang3081\ldblquote\lang1033 hop realistically in the stomach!\lang3081\rdblquote\lang1033 ), fragile sugar-spun quills, and exploding bonbons.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry squeezed himself through a crowd of sixth years and saw a sign hanging in the farthest corner of the shop (UNUSUAL TASTES). Ron and Hermione were standing underneath it, examining a tray of blood-flavored lollipops. Harry sneaked up behind them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ugh, no, Harry won\rquote t want one of those, they\rquote re for vampires, I expect,\rdblquote  Hermione was saying.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How about these?\rdblquote  said Ron, shoving a\lang3081  \lang1033 jar of Cockroach Clus\-ters under Hermione\rquote s nose.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Definitely not,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron nearly dropped the jar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Harry\i0 !\rdblquote  squealed Hermione. \ldblquote What are you doing here? How \emdash  how did you \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wow!\rdblquote  said Ron, looking very impressed, \ldblquote you\rquote ve learned to Apparate!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\ldblquote  \rquote\lang1033 Course I haven\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry. He dropped his voice so that none of the sixth years could hear him and told them all about the Marauder\rquote s Map.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How come Fred and George never gave it to \i me\i0 !\rdblquote  said Ron, outraged. \ldblquote I\rquote m their brother!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But Harry isn\rquote t going to keep it!\rdblquote  said Hermione, as though the idea were ludicrous. \ldblquote He\rquote s going to hand it in to Professor McGonagall, aren\rquote t you, Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I\rquote m not!\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you mad?\rdblquote  said Ron, goggling at Hermione. \ldblquote Hand in something that good?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If I hand it in, I\rquote ll have to say where I got it! Filch would know Fred and George had nicked it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what about Sirius Black?\rdblquote  Hermione hissed. \ldblquote He could be using one of the passages on that map to get into the castle! The teachers have got to know!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He can\rquote t be getting in through a passage,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly. \ldblquote There are seven secret tunnels on the map, right? Fred and George reckon Filch already knows about four of them. And of the other three \emdash  one of them\rquote s caved in, so no one can get through it. One of them\rquote s got the Whomping Willow planted over the entrance, so you can\rquote t get out of it. And the one I just came through \emdash  well \emdash  it\rquote s really hard to see the entrance to it down in the cellar, so unless he knew it was there \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry hesitated. What if Black did know the passage was there?\lang3081  \lang1033 Ron, however, cleared his throat significantly, and pointed to a no\-tice pasted on the inside of the sweetshop door.\lang3081\par
