\lang1033\ldblquote See?\rdblquote  said Ron quietly. \ldblquote I\rquote d like to see Black try and break into Honeydukes with dementors swarming all over the village. Any\-way, Hermione, the Honeydukes owners would hear a break-in, wouldn\rquote t they? They live over the shop!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but \emdash  but \emdash\rdblquote  Hermoine seemed to be struggling to find another problem. \ldblquote Look, Harry still shouldn\rquote t be coming into Hogsmeade. He hasn\rquote t got a signed form! If anyone finds out, he\rquote ll be in so much trouble! And it\rquote s not nightfall yet \emdash  what if Sirius Black turns up today? Now?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote d have a job spotting Harry in this,\rdblquote  said Ron, nodding through the mullioned windows at the thick, swirling snow. \ldblquote Come on, Hermione, it\rquote s Christmas. Harry deserves a break.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione bit her lip, looking extremely worried.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you going to report me?\rdblquote  Harry asked her, grinning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \emdash  of course not \emdash  but honestly, Harry \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Seen the Fizzing Whizbees, Harry?\rdblquote  said Ron, grabbing him and leading him over to their barrel. \ldblquote And the Jelly Slugs? And the Acid Pops? Fred gave me one of those when I was seven \emdash  it burnt a hole right through my tongue. I remember Mum walloping him with her broomstick.\rdblquote  Ron stared broodingly into the Acid Pop box. \ldblquote Reckon Fred\rquote d take a bit of Cockroach Cluster if I told him they were peanuts?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When Ron and Hermione had paid for all their sweets, the three of them left Honeydukes for the blizzard outside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hogsmeade looked like a Christmas card; the little thatched cot\-tages and shops were all covered in a layer of crisp snow; there were holly wreaths on the doors and strings of enchanted candles hang\-ing in the trees.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry shivered; unlike the other two, he didn\rquote t have his cloak. They headed up the street, heads bowed against the wind, Ron and Hermione shouting through their scarves.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s the post office \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Zonko\rquote s is up there \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We could go up to the Shrieking Shack \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tell you what,\rdblquote  said Ron, his teeth chattering, \ldblquote shall we go for a butterbeer in the Three Broomsticks?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was more than willing; the wind was fierce and his hands were freezing, so they crossed the road, and in a few minutes were entering the tiny inn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was extremely crowded, noisy, warm, and smoky. A curvy sort of woman with a pretty face was serving a bunch of rowdy warlocks up at the bar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s Madam Rosmerta,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote I\rquote ll get the drinks, shall I?\rdblquote  he added, going slightly red.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Hermione made their way to the back of the room, where there was a small, vacant table between the window and a handsome Christmas tree, which stood next to the fireplace. Ron came back five minutes later, carrying three foaming tankards of hot butterbeer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Merry Christmas!\rdblquote  he said happily, raising his tankard.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry drank deeply. It was the most delicious thing he\rquote d ever tasted and seemed to heat every bit of him from the inside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A sudden breeze ruffled his hair. The door of the Three Broom\-sticks had opened again. Harry looked over the rim of his tankard and choked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professors McGonagall and Flitwick had just entered the pub with a flurry of snowflakes, shortly followed by Hagrid, who was deep in conversation with a portly man in a lime-green bowler hat and a pinstriped cloak \emdash  Cornelius Fudge, Minister of Magic.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In an instant, Ron and Hermione had both placed hands on the top of Harry\rquote s head and forced him off his stool and under the table. Dripping with butterbeer and crouching out of sight, Harry clutched his empty tankard and watched the teachers\rquote  and Fudge\rquote s feet move toward the bar, pause, then turn and walk right toward him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Somewhere above him, Hermione whispered, \ldblquote\i Mobiliarbus\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Christmas tree beside their table rose a few inches off the ground, drifted sideways, and landed with a soft thump right in front of their table, hiding them from view. Staring through the dense lower branches, Harry saw four sets of chair legs move back from the table right beside theirs, then heard the grunts and sighs of the teachers and minister as they sat down.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Next he saw another pair of feet, wearing sparkly turquoise high heels, and heard a woman\rquote s voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A small gillywater \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mine,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall\rquote s voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Four pints of mulled mead \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ta, Rosmerta,\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A cherry syrup and soda with ice and umbrella \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mmm!\rdblquote  said Professor Flitwick, smacking his lips.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So you\rquote ll be the red currant rum, Minister.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you, Rosmerta, m\rquote dear,\rdblquote  said Fudge\rquote s voice. \ldblquote Lovely to see you again, I must say. Have one yourself, won\rquote t you? Come and join us. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, thank you very much, Minister.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry watched the glittering heels march away and back again. His heart was pounding uncomfortably in his throat. Why hadn\rquote t it occurred to him that this was the last weekend of term for the teach\-ers too? And how long were they going to sit there? He needed time to sneak back into Honeydukes if he wanted to return to school tonight. \'85 Hermione\rquote s leg gave a nervous twitch next to him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, what brings you to this neck of the woods, Minister?\rdblquote  came Madam Rosmerta\rquote s voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry saw the lower part of Fudge\rquote s thick body twist in his chair as though he were checking for eavesdroppers. Then he said in a quiet voice, \ldblquote What else, m\rquote dear, but Sirius Black? I daresay you heard what happened up at the school at Halloween?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I did hear a rumor,\rdblquote  admitted Madam Rosmerta.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you tell the whole pub, Hagrid?\rdblquote  said Professor McGona\-gall exasperatedly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do you think Black\rquote s still in the area, Minister?\rdblquote  whispered Madam Rosmerta.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sure of it,\rdblquote  said Fudge shortly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know that the dementors have searched the whole village twice?\rdblquote  said Madam Rosmerta, a slight edge to her voice. \ldblquote Scared all my customers away. \'85 It\rquote s very bad for business, Minister.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Rosmerta, m\rquote dear, I don\rquote t like them any more than you do,\rdblquote  said Fudge uncomfortably. \ldblquote Necessary precaution \'85 unfortunate, but there you are. \'85 I\rquote ve just met some of them. They\rquote re in a fury against Dumbledore \emdash  he won\rquote t let them inside the castle grounds.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I should think not,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall sharply. \ldblquote How are we supposed to teach with those horrors floating around?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hear, hear!\rdblquote  squeaked tiny Professor Flitwick, whose feet were dangling a foot from the ground.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All the same,\rdblquote  demurred Fudge, \ldblquote they are here to protect you all from something much worse. \'85 We all know what Black\rquote s capa\-ble of. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do you know, I still have trouble believing it,\rdblquote  said Madam Rosmerta thoughtfully. \ldblquote Of all the people to go over to the Dark Side, Sirius Black was the last I\rquote d have thought\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 I mean, I re\-member him when he was a boy at Hogwarts. If you\rquote d told me then what he was going to become, I\rquote d have said you\rquote d had too much mead.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You don\rquote t know the half of it, Rosmerta,\rdblquote  said Fudge gruffly. \ldblquote The worst he did isn\rquote t widely known.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The worst?\rdblquote  said Madam Rosmerta, her voice alive with curios\-ity. \ldblquote Worse than murdering all those poor people, you mean?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I certainly do,\rdblquote  said Fudge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t believe that. What could possibly be worse?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You say you remember him at Hogwarts, Rosmerta,\rdblquote  murmured Professor McGonagall. \ldblquote Do you remember who his best friend was?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Naturally,\rdblquote  said Madam Rosmerta, with a small laugh. \ldblquote Never saw one without the other, did you? The number of times I had them in here \emdash  ooh, they used to make me laugh. Quite the dou\-ble act, Sirius Black and James Potter!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry dropped his tankard with a loud clunk. Ron kicked him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Precisely,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall. \ldblquote Black and Potter. Ring\-leaders of their little gang. Both very bright, of course \emdash  excep\-tionally bright, in fact \emdash  but I don\rquote t think we\rquote ve ever had such a pair of troublemakers \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I dunno,\rdblquote  chuckled Hagrid. \ldblquote Fred and George Weasley could give \rquote em a run fer their money.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote d have thought Black and Potter were brothers!\rdblquote  chimed in Professor Flitwick. \ldblquote Inseparable!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course they were,\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote Potter trusted Black beyond all his other friends. Nothing changed when they left school. Black was best man when James married Lily. Then they named him god\-father to Harry. Harry has no idea, of course. You can imagine how the idea would torment him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because Black turned out to be in league with You-Know-Who?\rdblquote  whispered Madam Rosmerta.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Worse even than that, m\rquote dear. \'85\rdblquote  Fudge dropped his voice and proceeded in a sort of low rumble. \ldblquote Not many people are aware that the Potters knew You-Know-Who was after them. Dumbledore, who was of course working tirelessly against You-Know-Who, had a number of useful spies. One of them tipped him off, and he alerted James and Lily at once. He advised them to go into hiding. Well, of\lang3081  \lang1033 course, You-Know-Who wasn\rquote t an easy person to hide from. Dumble\-dore told them that their best chance was the Fidelius Charm.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How does that work?\rdblquote  said Madam Rosmerta, breathless with interest. Professor Flitwick cleared his throat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote An immensely complex spell,\rdblquote  he said squeakily, \ldblquote involving the magical concealment of a secret inside a single, living soul. The in\-formation is hidden inside the chosen person, or Secret-Keeper, and is henceforth impossible to find \emdash  unless, of course, the Secret-Keeper chooses to divulge it. As long as the Secret-Keeper refused to speak, You-Know-Who could search the village where Lily and James were staying for years and never find them, not even if he had his nose pressed against their sitting room window!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So Black was the Potters\rquote  Secret-Keeper?\rdblquote  whispered Madam Rosmerta.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Naturally,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall. \ldblquote James Potter told Dumbledore that Black would die rather than tell where they were, that Black was planning to go into hiding himself \'85 and yet, Dumbledore remained worried. I remember him offering to be the Potters\rquote  Secret-Keeper himself.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He suspected Black?\rdblquote  gasped Madam Rosmerta.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He was sure that somebody close to the Potters had been keep\-ing You-Know-Who informed of their movements,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall darkly. \ldblquote Indeed, he had suspected for some time that someone on our side had turned traitor and was passing a lot of in\-formation to You-Know-Who.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But James Potter insisted on using Black?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He did,\rdblquote  said Fudge heavily. \ldblquote And then, barely a week after the Fidelius Charm had been performed \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Black betrayed them?\rdblquote  breathed Madam Rosmerta.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He did indeed. Black was tired of his double-agent role, he was ready to declare his support openly for You-Know-Who, and he seems to have planned this for the moment of the Potters\rquote  death. But, as we all know, You-Know-Who met his downfall in little Harry Potter. Powers gone, horribly weakened, he fled. And this left Black in a very nasty position indeed. His master had fallen at the very moment when he, Black, had shown his true colors as a traitor. He had no choice but to run for it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Filthy, stinkin\rquote  turncoat!\rdblquote  Hagrid said, so loudly that half the bar went quiet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shh!\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I met him!\rdblquote  growled Hagrid. \ldblquote I musta bin the last ter see him before he killed all them people! It was me what rescued Harry from Lily an\rquote  James\rquote s house after they was killed! Jus\rquote  got him outta the ruins, poor little thing, with a great slash across his forehead, an\rquote  his parents dead \'85 an\rquote  Sirius Black turns up, on that flyin\rquote  motorbike he used ter ride. Never occurred ter me what he was doin\rquote  there. I didn\rquote  know he\rquote d bin Lily an\rquote  James\rquote s Secret-Keeper. Thought he\rquote d jus\rquote  heard the news o\rquote  You-Know-Who\rquote s attack an\rquote  come ter see what he could do. White an\rquote  shakin\rquote , he was. An\rquote  yeh know what I did? I COMFORTED THE MURDERIN\rquote  TRAITOR!\rdblquote  Hagrid roared.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid, please!\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall. \ldblquote Keep your voice down!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How was I ter know he wasn\rquote  upset abou\rquote  Lily an\rquote  James? It was You-Know-Who he cared abou\rquote ! An\rquote  then he says, \lang3081\lquote\lang1033 Give Harry ter me, Hagrid, I\rquote m his godfather, I\rquote ll look after him \emdash\lang3081\rquote\lang1033  Ha! But I\rquote d\lang3081  \lang1033 had me orders from Dumbledore, an\rquote  I told Black no, Dumbledore said Harry was ter go ter his aunt an\rquote  uncle\rquote s. Black argued, but in the end he gave in. Told me ter take his motorbike ter get Harry there. \lang3081\lquote\lang1033 I won\rquote t need it anymore,\lang3081\rquote\lang1033  he says.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I shoulda known there was somethin\rquote  fishy goin\rquote  on then. He loved that motorbike, what was he givin\rquote  it ter me for? Why wouldn\rquote  he need it anymore? Fact was, it was too easy ter trace. Dumbledore knew he\rquote d bin the Potters\rquote  Secret-Keeper. Black knew he was goin\rquote  ter have ter run fer it that night, knew it was a matter o\rquote  hours before the Ministry was after him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i But what if I\rquote d given Harry to him, eh\i0 ? I bet he\rquote d\rquote ve pitched him off the bike halfway out ter sea. His bes\rquote  friends\rquote  son! But when a wizard goes over ter the Dark Side, there\rquote s nothin\rquote  and no one that matters to \rquote em anymore. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A long silence followed Hagrid\rquote s story. Then Madam Rosmerta said with some satisfaction, \ldblquote But he didn\rquote t manage to disappear, did he? The Ministry of Magic caught up with him next day!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Alas, if only we had,\rdblquote  said Fudge bitterly. \ldblquote It was not we who found him. It was little Peter Pettigrew \emdash  another of the Potters\rquote  friends. Maddened by grief, no doubt, and knowing that Black had been the Potters\rquote  Secret-Keeper, he went after Black himself.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Pettigrew \'85 that fat little boy who was always tagging around after them at Hogwarts?\rdblquote  said Madam Rosmerta.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hero-worshipped Black and Potter,\rdblquote  said Professor McGona\-gall. \ldblquote Never quite in their league, talent-wise. I was often rather sharp with him. You can imagine how I \emdash  how I regret that now. \'85\rdblquote  She sounded as though she had a sudden head cold.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There, now, Minerva,\rdblquote  said Fudge kindly, \ldblquote Pettigrew died a\lang3081  \lang1033 hero\rquote s death. Eyewitnesses \emdash  Muggles, of course, we wiped their memories later \emdash  told us how Pettigrew cornered Black. They say he was sobbing, \lang3081\lquote\lang1033 Lily and James, Sirius! How could you?\lang3081\rquote\lang1033  And then he went for his wand. Well, of course, Black was quicker. Blew Pettigrew to smithereens. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor McGonagall blew her nose and said thickly, \ldblquote Stupid boy \'85 foolish boy \'85 he was always hopeless at dueling \'85 should have left it to the Ministry. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I tell yeh, if I\rquote d got ter Black before little Pettigrew did, I wouldn\rquote t\rquote ve messed around with wands \emdash  I\rquote d\rquote ve ripped him limb \emdash  from \emdash  limb,\rdblquote  Hagrid growled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You don\rquote t know what you\rquote re talking about, Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Fudge sharply. \ldblquote Nobody but trained Hit Wizards from the Magical Law Enforcement Squad would have stood a chance against Black once he was cornered. I was Junior Minister in the Department of Mag\-ical Catastrophes at the time, and I was one of the first on the scene after Black murdered all those people. I \emdash  I will never forget it. I still dream about it sometimes. A crater in the middle of the street, so deep it had cracked the sewer below. Bodies everywhere. Mug\-gles screaming. And Black standing there laughing, with what was left of Pettigrew in front of him \'85 a heap of bloodstained robes and a few \emdash  a few fragments \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge\rquote s voice stopped abruptly. There was the sound of five noses being blown.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, there you have it, Rosmerta,\rdblquote  said Fudge thickly. \ldblquote Black was taken away by twenty members of the Magical Law Enforce\-ment Squad and Pettigrew received the Order of Merlin, First Class, which I think was some comfort to his poor mother. Black\rquote s been in Azkaban ever since.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Madam Rosmerta let out a long sigh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is it true he\rquote s mad, Minister?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wish I could say that he was,\rdblquote  said Fudge slowly. \ldblquote I certainly believe his master\rquote s defeat unhinged him for a while. The murder of Pettigrew and all those Muggles was the action of a cornered and desperate man \emdash  cruel\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 pointless. Yet I met Black on my last inspection of Azkaban. You know, most of the prisoners in there sit muttering to themselves in the dark; there\rquote s no sense in them \'85 but I was shocked at how \i normal\i0  Black seemed. He spoke quite rationally to me. It was unnerving. You\rquote d have thought he was merely bored \emdash  asked if I\rquote d finished with my newspaper, cool as you please, said he missed doing the crossword. Yes, I was astounded at how little effect the dementors seemed to be having on him \emdash  and he was one of the most heavily guarded in the place, you know. Dementors outside his door day and night.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
