\lang1033\ldblquote Another boggart,\rdblquote  said Lupin, stripping off his cloak. \ldblquote I\rquote ve been combing the castle ever since Tuesday, and very luckily, I found this one lurking inside Mr. Filch\rquote s filing cabinet. It\rquote s the nearest we\rquote ll get to a real dementor. The boggart will turn into a dementor when he sees you, so we\rquote ll be able to practice on him. I can store him in my office when we\rquote re not using him; there\rquote s a cupboard under my desk he\rquote ll like.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  said Harry, trying to sound as though he wasn\rquote t apprehensive at all and merely glad that Lupin had found such a good substitute for a real dementor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So \'85\rdblquote  Professor Lupin had taken out his own wand, and in\-dicated that Harry should do the same. \ldblquote The spell I am going to try and teach you is highly advanced magic, Harry \emdash  well beyond Ordinary Wizarding Level. It is called the Patronus Charm.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How does it work?\rdblquote  said Harry nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, when it works correctly, it conjures up a Patronus,\rdblquote  said Lupin, \ldblquote which is a kind of anti-dementor \emdash  a guardian that acts as a shield between you and the dementor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had a sudden vision of himself crouching behind a Hagrid-sized figure holding a large club. Professor Lupin continued, \ldblquote The Patronus is a kind of positive force, a projection of the very things that the dementor feeds upon \emdash  hope, happiness, the desire to survive \emdash  but it cannot feel despair, as real humans can, so the de\-mentors can\rquote t hurt it. But I must warn you, Harry, that the charm might be too advanced for you. Many qualified wizards have diffi\-culty with it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What does a Patronus look like?\rdblquote  said Harry curiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Each one is unique to the wizard who conjures it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And how do you conjure it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote With an incantation, which will work only if you are concen\-trating, with all your might, on a single, very happy memory.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry cast his mind about for a happy memory. Certainly, nothing that had happened to him at the Dursleys\rquote  was going to do. Finally, he settled on the moment when he had first ridden a broomstick.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  he said, trying to recall as exactly as possible the won\-derful, soaring sensation of his stomach.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The incantation is this \emdash\rdblquote  Lupin cleared his throat. \ldblquote\i Expecto patronum\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Expecto patronum\i0 ,\rdblquote  Harry repeated under his breath, \ldblquote\i expecto patronum.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Concentrating hard on your happy memory?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \emdash  yeah \emdash\rdblquote  said Harry, quickly forcing his thoughts back to that first broom ride. \ldblquote\i Expecto patrono\i0  \emdash  no, \i patronum\i0  \emdash  sorry \emdash  \i expecto patronum, expecto patronum\i0  \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Something whooshed suddenly out of the end of his wand; it looked like a wisp of silvery gas.\lang3081\par
