It looked like the end of Ron and Hermione\rquote s friendship. Each was so angry with the other that Harry couldn\rquote t see how they\rquote d ever make up.\par
Ron was enraged that Hermione had never taken Crookshanks\rquote s attempts to eat Scabbers seriously, hadn\rquote t bothered to keep a close enough watch on him, and was still trying to pretend that Crook\-shanks was innocent by suggesting that Ron look for Scabbers un\-der all the boys\rquote  beds. Hermione, meanwhile, maintained fiercely that Ron had no proof that Crookshanks had eaten Scabbers, that the ginger hairs might have been there since Christmas, and that Ron had been prejudiced against her cat ever since Crookshanks had landed on Ron\rquote s head in the Magical Menagerie.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Personally, Harry was sure that Crookshanks had eaten Scab\-bers, and when he tried to point out to Hermione that the evidence all pointed that way, she lost her temper with Harry too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay, side with Ron, I knew you would!\rdblquote  she said shrilly. \ldblquote First the Firebolt, now Scabbers, everything\rquote s my fault, isn\rquote t it! Just leave me alone, Harry, I\rquote ve got a lot of work to do!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron had taken the loss of his rat very hard indeed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come on, Ron, you were always saying how boring Scabbers was,\rdblquote  said Fred bracingly \ldblquote And he\rquote s been off-color for ages, he was wasting away. It was probably better for him to snuff it quickly \emdash  one swallow \emdash  he probably didn\rquote t feel a thing.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Fred\i0 !\rdblquote  said Ginny indignantly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All he did was eat and sleep, Ron, you said it yourself,\rdblquote  said George.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He bit Goyle for us once!\rdblquote  Ron said miserably. \ldblquote Remember, Harry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, that\rquote s true,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote His finest hour,\rdblquote  said Fred, unable to keep a straight face. \ldblquote Let the scar on Goyle\rquote s finger stand as a lasting tribute to his memory. Oh, come on, Ron, get yourself down to Hogsmeade and buy a new rat, what\rquote s the point of moaning?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In a last-ditch attempt to cheer Ron up, Harry persuaded him to come along to the Gryffindor team\rquote s final practice before the Ravenclaw match, so that he could have a ride on the Firebolt after they\rquote d finished. This did seem to take Ron\rquote s mind off Scabbers for a moment (\lang3081\ldblquote\lang1033 Great! Can I try and shoot a few goals on it?\lang3081\rdblquote\lang1033 ) so they set off for the Quidditch field together.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Madam Hooch, who was still overseeing Gryffindor practices to keep an eye on Harry, was just as impressed with the Firebolt as everyone else had been. She took it in her hands before takeoff and gave them the benefit of her professional opinion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look at the balance on it! If the Nimbus series has a fault, it\rquote s a slight list to the tail end \emdash  you often find they develop a drag after a few years. They\rquote ve updated the handle too, a bit slimmer than the Cleansweeps, reminds me of the old Silver Arrows \emdash  a pity they\rquote ve stopped making them. I learned to fly on one, and a very fine old broom it was too. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She continued in this vein for some time, until Wood said, \ldblquote Er \emdash  Madam Hooch? Is it okay if Harry has the Firebolt back? We need to practice. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \emdash  right \emdash  here you are, then, Potter,\rdblquote  said Madam Hooch. \ldblquote I\rquote ll sit over here with Weasley \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She and Ron left the field to sit in the stadium, and the Gryffindor team gathered around Wood for his final instructions for tomorrow\rquote s match.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, I\rquote ve just found out who Ravenclaw is playing as Seeker. It\rquote s Cho Chang. She\rquote s a fourth year, and she\rquote s pretty good. \'85 I really hoped she wouldn\rquote t be fit, she\rquote s had some problems with in\-juries. \'85\rdblquote  Wood scowled his displeasure that Cho Chang had made a full recovery, then said, \ldblquote On the other hand, she rides a Comet Two Sixty, which is going to look like a joke next to the Firebolt.\rdblquote  He gave Harry\rquote s broom a look of fervent admiration, then said, \ldblquote Okay, everyone, let\rquote s go \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And at long last, Harry mounted his Firebolt, and kicked off from the ground.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was better than he\rquote d ever dreamed. The Firebolt turned with the lightest touch; it seemed to obey his thoughts rather than his grip; it sped across the field at such speed that the stadium turned into a green-and-gray blur; Harry turned it so sharply that Alicia\lang3081  \lang1033 Spinnet screamed, then he went into a perfectly controlled dive, brushing the grassy field with his toes before rising thirty, forty, fifty feet into the air again \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, I\rquote m letting the Snitch out!\rdblquote  Wood called.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned and raced a Bludger toward the goal posts; he out\-stripped it easily, saw the Snitch dart out from behind Wood, and within ten seconds had caught it tightly in his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The team cheered madly. Harry let the Snitch go again, gave it a minute\rquote s head start, then tore after it, weaving in and out of the others; he spotted it lurking near Katie Bell\rquote s knee, looped her eas\-ily, and caught it again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was the best practice ever; the team, inspired by the presence of the Firebolt in their midst, performed their best moves fault\-lessly, and by the time they hit the ground again, Wood didn\rquote t have a single criticism to make, which, as George Weasley pointed out, was a first.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t see what\rquote s going to stop us tomorrow!\rdblquote  said Wood. \ldblquote Not unless \emdash  Harry, you\rquote ve sorted out your dementor problem, haven\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, thinking of his feeble Patronus and wishing it were stronger.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The dementors won\rquote t turn up again, Oliver. Dumbledore\rquote d go ballistic,\rdblquote  said Fred confidently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, let\rquote s hope not,\rdblquote  said Wood. \ldblquote Anyway \emdash  good work, everyone. Let\rquote s get back to the tower \'85 turn in early \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m staying out for a bit; Ron wants a go on the Firebolt,\rdblquote  Harry told Wood, and while the rest of the team headed off to the locker rooms, Harry strode over to Ron, who vaulted the barrier to\lang3081  \lang1033 the stands and came to meet him. Madam Hooch had fallen asleep in her seat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here you go,\rdblquote  said Harry, handing Ron the Firebolt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron, an expression of ecstasy on his face, mounted the broom and zoomed off into the gathering darkness while Harry walked around the edge of the field, watching him. Night had fallen before Madam Hooch awoke with a start, told Harry and Ron off for not waking her, and insisted that they go back to the castle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry shouldered the Firebolt and he and Ron walked out of the shadowy stadium, discussing the Firebolt\rquote s superbly smooth action, its phenomenal acceleration, and its pinpoint turning. They were halfway toward the castle when Harry, glancing to his left, saw something that made his heart turn over \emdash  a pair of eyes, gleam\-ing out of the darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stopped dead, his heart banging against his ribs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s the matter?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry pointed. Ron pulled out his wand and muttered, \ldblquote\i Lumos\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A beam of light fell across the grass, hit the bottom of a tree, and illuminated its branches; there, crouching among the budding leaves, was Crookshanks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get out of here!\rdblquote  Ron roared, and he stooped down and seized a stone lying on the grass, but before he could do anything else, Crookshanks had vanished with one swish of his long ginger tail.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote See?\rdblquote  Ron said furiously, chucking the stone down again. \ldblquote She\rquote s still letting him wander about wherever he wants \emdash  probably washing down Scabbers with a couple of birds now. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry didn\rquote t say anything. He took a deep breath as relief seeped through him; he had been sure for a moment that those eyes had\lang3081  \lang1033 belonged to the Grim. They set off for the castle once more. Slightly ashamed of his moment of panic, Harry didn\rquote t say any\-thing to Ron \emdash  nor did he look left or right until they had reached the well-lit entrance hall.\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 Harry went down to breakfast the next morning with the rest of the boys in his dormitory, all of whom seemed to think the Firebolt deserved a sort of guard of honor. As Harry entered the Great Hall, heads turned in the direction of the Firebolt, and there was a good deal of excited muttering. Harry saw, with enormous satisfaction, that the Slytherin team were all looking thunder\-struck.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you see his face?\rdblquote  said Ron gleefully, looking back at Mal\-foy. \ldblquote He can\rquote t believe it! This is brilliant!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Wood, too, was basking in the reflected glory of the Firebolt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Put it here, Harry,\rdblquote  he said, laying the broom in the middle of the table and carefully turning it so that its name faced upward. People from the Ravenclaw and Hufflepuff tables were soon coming over to look. Cedric Diggory came over to congratu\-late Harry on having acquired such a superb replacement for his Nimbus, and Percy\rquote s Ravenclaw girlfriend, Penelope Clearwater, asked if she could actually hold the Firebolt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, now, Penny, no sabotage!\rdblquote  said Percy heartily as she examined the Firebolt closely \ldblquote Penelope and I have got a bet on,\rdblquote  he told the team. \ldblquote Ten Galleons on the outcome of the match!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Penelope put the Firebolt down again, thanked Harry, and went back to her table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry \emdash  make sure you win,\rdblquote  said Percy, in an urgent whisper. \ldblquote\i I\lang3081  \lang1033 haven\rquote t got ten Galleons.\i0  Yes, I\rquote m coming, Penny!\rdblquote  And he bustled off to join her in a piece of toast.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sure you can manage that broom, Potter?\rdblquote  said a cold, drawling voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Draco Malfoy had arrived for a closer look, Crabbe and Goyle right behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, reckon so,\rdblquote  said Harry casually.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Got plenty of special features, hasn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Malfoy, eyes glit\-tering maliciously. \ldblquote Shame it doesn\rquote t come with a parachute \emdash  in case you get too near a dementor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Crabbe and Goyle sniggered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Pity you can\rquote t attach an extra arm to yours, Malfoy,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Then it could catch the Snitch for you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Gryffindor team laughed loudly. Malfoy\rquote s pale eyes nar\-rowed, and he stalked away. They watched him rejoin the rest of the Slytherin team, who put their heads together, no doubt asking Malfoy whether Harry\rquote s broom really was a Firebolt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At a quarter to eleven, the Gryffindor team set off for the locker rooms. The weather couldn\rquote t have been more different from their match against Hufflepuff. It was a clear, cool day with a very light breeze; there would be no visibility problems this time, and Harry, though nervous, was starting to feel the excitement only a Quid\-ditch match could bring. They could hear the rest of the school moving into the stadium beyond. Harry took off his black school robes, removed his wand from his pocket, and stuck it inside the T-shirt he was going to wear under his Quidditch robes. He only hoped he wouldn\rquote t need it. He wondered suddenly whether Profes\-sor Lupin was in the crowd, watching.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know what we\rquote ve got to do,\rdblquote  said Wood as they prepared to leave the locker rooms. \ldblquote If we lose this match, we\rquote re out of the run\-ning. Just \emdash  just fly like you did in practice yesterday, and we\rquote ll be okay!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They walked out onto the field to tumultuous applause. The Ravenclaw team, dressed in blue, were already standing in the mid\-dle of the field. Their Seeker, Cho Chang, was the only girl on their team. She was shorter than Harry by about a head, and Harry couldn\rquote t help noticing, nervous as he was, that she was extremely pretty. She smiled at Harry as the teams faced each other behind their captains, and he felt a slight lurch in the region of his stom\-ach that he didn\rquote t think had anything to do with nerves.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wood, Davies, shake hands,\rdblquote  Madam Hooch said briskly, and Wood shook hands with the Ravenclaw Captain.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mount your brooms \'85 on my whistle \'85 three \emdash  two \emdash\lang3081  \lang1033 one \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry kicked off into the air and the Firebolt zoomed higher and faster than any other broom; he soared around the stadium and began squinting around for the Snitch, listening all the while to the commentary, which was being provided by the Weasley twins\rquote  friend Lee Jordan.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re off, and the big excitement this match is the Firebolt that Harry Potter is flying for Gryffindor. According to \i Which Broomstick,\i0  the Firebolt\rquote s going to be the broom of choice for the national teams at this year\rquote s World Championship \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Jordan, would you mind telling us what\rquote s going on in the match?\rdblquote  interrupted Professor McGonagall\rquote s voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right you are, Professor \emdash  just giving a bit of background\lang3081  \lang1033 information \emdash  the Firebolt, incidentally, has a built-in auto-brake and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Jordan!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay, okay, Gryffindor in possession, Katie Bell of Gryffindor heading for goal\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry streaked past Katie in the opposite direction, gazing around for a glint of gold and noticing that Cho Chang was tailing him closely. She was undoubtedly a very good flier \emdash  she kept cut\-ting across him, forcing him to change direction.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Show her your acceleration, Harry!\rdblquote  Fred yelled as he whooshed past in pursuit of a Bludger that was aiming for Alicia.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry urged the Firebolt forward as they rounded the Raven\-claw goal posts and Cho fell behind. Just as Katie succeeded in scoring the first goal of the match, and the Gryffindor end of the field went wild, he saw it \emdash  the Snitch was close to the ground, flitting near one of the barriers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry dived; Cho saw what he was doing and tore after him \emdash  Harry was speeding up, excitement flooding him; dives were his speciality, he was ten feet away \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then a Bludger, hit by one of the Ravenclaw Beaters, came pelt\-ing out of nowhere; Harry veered off course, avoiding it by an inch, and in those few, crucial seconds, the Snitch had vanished.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a great \ldblquote Ooooooh\rdblquote  of disappointment from the Gryffindor supporters, but much applause for their Beater from the Ravenclaw end. George Weasley vented his feelings by hitting the second Bludger directly at the offending Beater, who was forced to roll right over in midair to avoid it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Gryffindor leads by eighty points to zero, and look at that\lang3081  \lang1033 Firebolt go! Potter\rquote s really putting it through its paces now, see it turn \emdash  Chang\rquote s Comet is just no match for it, the Firebolt\rquote s precision-balance is really noticeable in these long \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote JORDAN! ARE YOU BEING PAID TO ADVERTISE FIRE\-BOLTS? GET ON WITH THE COMMENTARY!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ravenclaw was pulling back; they had now scored three goals, which put Gryffindor only fifty points ahead \emdash  if Cho got the Snitch before him, Ravenclaw would win. Harry dropped lower, narrowly avoiding a Ravenclaw Chaser, scanning the field franti\-cally \emdash  a glint of gold, a flutter of tiny wings \emdash  the Snitch was circling the Gryffindor goal post \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry accelerated, eyes fixed on the speck of gold ahead \emdash  but just then, Cho appeared out of thin air, blocking him \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote HARRY, THIS IS NO TIME TO BE A GENTLEMAN!\rdblquote  Wood roared as Harry swerved to avoid a collision. \ldblquote KNOCK HER OFF HER BROOM IF YOU HAVE TO!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned and caught sight of Cho; she was grinning. The Snitch had vanished again. Harry turned his Firebolt upward and was soon twenty feet above the game. Out of the corner of his eye, he saw Cho following him. \'85 She\rquote d decided to mark him rather than search for the Snitch herself. \'85 All right, then \'85 if she wanted to tail him, she\rquote d have to take the conse\-quences. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He dived again, and Cho, thinking he\rquote d seen the Snitch, tried to follow; Harry pulled out of the dive very sharply; she hurtled downward; he rose fast as a bullet once more, and then saw it, for the third time \emdash  the Snitch was glittering way above the field at the Ravenclaw end.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He accelerated; so, many feet below, did Cho. He was winning, gaining on the Snitch with every second \emdash  then \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh!\rdblquote  screamed Cho, pointing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Distracted, Harry looked down.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Three dementors, three tall, black, hooded dementors, were looking up at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He didn\rquote t stop to think. Plunging a hand down the neck of his robes, he whipped out his wand and roared, \ldblquote\i Expecto patronum\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Something silver-white, something enormous, erupted from the end of his wand. He knew it had shot directly at the dementors but didn\rquote t pause to watch; his mind still miraculously clear, he looked ahead \emdash  he was nearly there. He stretched out the hand still grasp\-ing his wand and just managed to close his fingers over the small, struggling Snitch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Madam Hooch\rquote s whistle sounded. Harry turned around in midair and saw six scarlet blurs bearing down on him; next mo\-ment, the whole team was hugging him so hard he was nearly pulled off his broom. Down below he could hear the roars of the Gryffindors in the crowd.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s my boy!\rdblquote  Wood kept yelling. Alicia, Angelina, and Katie had all kissed Harry; Fred had him in a grip so tight Harry felt as though his head would come off. In complete disarray, the team managed to make its way back to the ground. Harry got off his broom and looked up to see a gaggle of Gryffindor supporters sprinting onto the field, Ron in the lead. Before he knew it, he had been engulfed by the cheering crowd.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes!\rdblquote  Ron yelled, yanking Harry\rquote s arm into the air. \ldblquote Yes! Yes!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well \i done,\i0  Harry!\rdblquote  said Percy, looking delighted. \ldblquote Ten Galleons to me! Must find Penelope, excuse me \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good for you, Harry!\rdblquote  roared Seamus Finnigan.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ruddy brilliant!\rdblquote  boomed Hagrid over the heads of the milling Gryffindors.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was quite some Patronus,\rdblquote  said a voice in Harry\rquote s ear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned around to see Professor Lupin, who looked both shaken and pleased.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The dementors didn\rquote t affect me at all!\rdblquote  Harry said excitedly. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t feel a thing!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That would be because they \emdash  er \emdash  weren\rquote t dementors,\rdblquote  said Professor Lupin. \ldblquote Come and see \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He led Harry out of the crowd until they were able to see the edge of the field.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You gave Mr. Malfoy quite a fright,\rdblquote  said Lupin.\lang3081\par
