No one in Gryffindor Tower slept that night. They knew that the castle was being searched again, and the whole House stayed awake in the common room, waiting to hear whether Black had been caught. Professor McGonagall came back at dawn, to tell them that he had again escaped.\par
Throughout the day, everywhere they went they saw signs of tighter security; Professor Flitwick could be seen teaching the front doors to recognize a large picture of Sirius Black; Filch was sud\-denly bustling up and down the corridors, boarding up everything from tiny cracks in the walls to mouse holes. Sir Cadogan had been fired. His portrait had been taken back to its lonely landing on the seventh floor, and the Fat Lady was back. She had been expertly restored, but was still extremely nervous, and had agreed to return to her job only on condition that she was given extra protection. A bunch of surly security trolls had been hired to guard her. They\lang3081  \lang1033 paced the corridor in a menacing group, talking in grunts and comparing the size of their clubs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry couldn\rquote t help noticing that the statue of the one-eyed witch on the third floor remained unguarded and unblocked. It seemed that Fred and George had been right in thinking that they \emdash  and now Harry, Ron, and Hermione \emdash  were the only ones who knew about the hidden passageway within it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you reckon we should tell someone?\rdblquote  Harry asked Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We know he\rquote s not coming in through Honeyduke\rquote s,\rdblquote  said Ron dismissively \ldblquote We\rquote d\rquote ve heard if the shop had been broken into.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was glad Ron took this view. If the one-eyed witch was boarded up too, he would never be able to go into Hogsmeade again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron had become an instant celebrity. For the first time in his life, people were paying more attention to him than to Harry, and it was clear that Ron was rather enjoying the experience. Though still severely shaken by the night\rquote s events, he was happy to tell any\-one who asked what had happened, with a wealth of detail.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 I was asleep, and I heard this ripping noise, and I thought it was in my dream, you know? But then there was this draft\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 I woke up and one side of the hangings on my bed had been pulled down. \'85 I rolled over \'85 and I saw him standing over me \'85 like a skeleton, with loads of filthy hair \'85 holding this great long knife, must\rquote ve been twelve inches \'85 and he looked at me, and I looked at him, and then I yelled, and he \i scampered.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why, though?\rdblquote  Ron added to Harry as the group of second-year girls who had been listening to his chilling tale departed. \ldblquote Why did he run?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had been wondering the same thing. Why had Black, having got the wrong bed, not silenced Ron and proceeded to Harry? Black had proved twelve years ago that he didn\rquote t mind mur\-dering innocent people, and this time he had been facing five un\-armed boys, four of whom were asleep.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He must\rquote ve known he\rquote d have a job getting back out of the castle once you\rquote d yelled and woken people up,\rdblquote  said Harry thoughtfully. \ldblquote He\rquote d\rquote ve had to kill the whole House to get back through the por\-trait hole \'85 then he would\rquote ve met the teachers. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville was in total disgrace. Professor McGonagall was so furi\-ous with him she had banned him from all future Hogsmeade vis\-its, given him a detention, and forbidden anyone to give him the password into the tower. Poor Neville was forced to wait outside the common room every night for somebody to let him in, while the security trolls leered unpleasantly at him. None of these pun\-ishments, however, came close to matching the one his grand\-mother had in store for him. Two days after Black\rquote s break-in, she sent Neville the very worst thing a Hogwarts student could receive over breakfast \emdash  a Howler.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The school owls swooped into the Great Hall carrying the mail as usual, and Neville choked as a huge barn owl landed in front of him, a scarlet envelope clutched in its beak. Harry and Ron, who were sitting opposite him, recognized the letter as a Howler at once \emdash  Ron had got one from his mother the year before.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Run for it, Neville,\rdblquote  Ron advised.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville didn\rquote t need telling twice. He seized the envelope, and holding it before him like a bomb, sprinted out of the hall, while the Slytherin table exploded with laughter at the sight of him. They\lang3081  \lang1033 heard the Howler go off in the entrance hall \emdash  Neville\rquote s grand\-mother\rquote s voice, magically magnified to a hundred times its usual volume, shrieking about how he had brought shame on the whole family.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was too busy feeling sorry for Neville to notice immedi\-ately that he had a letter too. Hedwig got his attention by nipping him sharply on the wrist.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ouch! Oh \emdash  thanks, Hedwig.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
