\lang1033 The Easter holidays were not exactly relaxing. The third years had never had so much homework. Neville Longbottom seemed close to a nervous collapse, and he wasn\rquote t the only one.\lang3081\par
\lang1033  \ldblquote Call this a holiday!\rdblquote  Seamus Finnigan roared at the common room one afternoon. \ldblquote The exams are ages away, what\rquote re they play\-ing at?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But nobody had as much to do as Hermione. Even without Div\-ination, she was taking more subjects than anybody else. She was usually last to leave the common room at night, first to arrive at the library the next morning; she had shadows like Lupin\rquote s under her eyes, and seemed constantly close to tears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron had taken over responsibility for Buckbeak\rquote s appeal. When he wasn\rquote t doing his own work, he was poring over enormously thick volumes with names like \i The Handbook of Hippogriff Psy\-chology\i0  and \i Fowl or Foul\i0 ?\i  A Study of Hippogriff Brutality.\i0  He was so absorbed, he even forgot to be horrible to Crookshanks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, meanwhile, had to fit in his homework around Quid\-ditch practice every day, not to mention endless discussions of tac\-tics with Wood. The Gryffindor-Slytherin match would take place on the first Saturday after the Easter holidays. Slytherin was lead\-ing the tournament by exactly two hundred points. This meant (as Wood constantly reminded his team) that they needed to win the match by more than that amount to win the Cup. It also meant that the burden of winning fell largely on Harry, because capturing the Snitch was worth one hundred and fifty points.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So you must catch it \i only\i0  if we\rquote re \i more than\i0  fifty points up,\rdblquote  Wood told Harry constantly. \ldblquote Only if we\rquote re more than fifty points up, Harry, or we win the match but lose the Cup. You\rquote ve got that, haven\rquote t you? You must catch the Snitch only if we\rquote re \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I KNOW, OLIVER!\rdblquote  Harry yelled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The whole of Gryffindor House was obsessed with the coming\lang3081  \lang1033 match. Gryffindor hadn\rquote t won the Quidditch Cup since the leg\-endary Charlie Weasley (Ron\rquote s second oldest brother) had been Seeker. But Harry doubted whether any of them, even Wood, wanted to win as much as he did. The enmity between Harry and Malfoy was at its highest point ever. Malfoy was still smarting about the mud-throwing incident in Hogsmeade and was even more furious that Harry had somehow wormed his way out of punishment. Harry hadn\rquote t forgotten Malfoy\rquote s attempt to sabotage him in the match against Ravenclaw, but it was the matter of Buck\-beak that made him most determined to beat Malfoy in front of the entire school.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Never, in anyone\rquote s memory, had a match approached in such a highly charged atmosphere. By the time the holidays were over, tension between the two teams and their Houses was at the break\-ing point. A number of small scuffles broke out in the corridors, culminating in a nasty incident in which a Gryffindor fourth year and a Slytherin sixth year ended up in the hospital wing with leeks sprouting out of their ears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was having a particularly bad time of it. He couldn\rquote t walk to class without Slytherins sticking out their legs and trying to trip him up; Crabbe and Goyle kept popping up wherever he went, and slouching away looking disappointed when they saw him sur\-rounded by people. Wood had given instructions that Harry should be accompanied everywhere he went, in case the Slytherins tried to put him out of action. The whole of Gryffindor House took up the challenge enthusiastically, so that it was impossible for Harry to get to classes on time because he was surrounded by a vast, chattering crowd. Harry was more concerned for his Firebolt\rquote s\lang3081  \lang1033 safety than his own. When he wasn\rquote t flying it, he locked it securely in his trunk and frequently dashed back up to Gryffindor Tower at break times to check that it was still there.\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 All usual pursuits were abandoned in the Gryffindor common room the night before the match. Even Hermione had put down her books.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t work, I can\rquote t concentrate,\rdblquote  she said nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a great deal of noise. Fred and George Weasley were dealing with the pressure by being louder and more exuberant than ever. Oliver Wood was crouched over a model of a Quidditch field in the corner, prodding little figures across it with his wand and muttering to himself. Angelina, Alicia, and Katie were laughing at Fred\rquote s and George\rquote s jokes. Harry was sitting with Ron and Her\-mione, removed from the center of things, trying not to think about the next day, because every time he did, he had the horrible sensation that something very large was fighting to get out of his stomach.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re going to be fine,\rdblquote  Hermione told him, though she looked positively terrified.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ve got a \i Firebolt\i0 !\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85 ,\rdblquote  said Harry, his stomach writhing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It came as a relief when Wood suddenly stood up and yelled, \ldblquote Team! Bed!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 Harry slept badly. First he dreamed that he had overslept, and that Wood was yelling, \ldblquote Where were you? We had to use Neville in\-stead!\rdblquote  Then he dreamed that Malfoy and the rest of the Slytherin team arrived for the match riding dragons. He was flying at\lang3081  \lang1033 breakneck speed, trying to avoid a spurt of flames from Malfoy\rquote s steed\rquote s mouth, when he realized he had forgotten his Firebolt. He fell through the air and woke with a start.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was a few seconds before Harry remembered that the match hadn\rquote t taken place yet, that he was safe in bed, and that the Slytherin team definitely wouldn\rquote t be allowed to play on dragons. He was feeling very thirsty. Quietly as he could, he got out of his four-poster and went to pour himself some water from the silver jug beneath the window.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The grounds were still and quiet. No breath of wind disturbed the treetops in the Forbidden Forest; the Whomping Willow was motionless and innocent-looking. It looked as though the condi\-tions for the match would be perfect.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry set down his goblet and was about to turn back to his bed when something caught his eye. An animal of some kind was prowling across the silvery lawn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry dashed to his bedside table, snatched up his glasses, and put them on, then hurried back to the window. It couldn\rquote t be the Grim \emdash  not now \emdash  not right before the match \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He peered out at the grounds again and, after a minute\rquote s frantic searching, spotted it. It was skirting the edge of the forest now. \'85 It wasn\rquote t the Grim at all\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 it was a cat. \'85 Harry clutched the window ledge in relief as he recognized the bottlebrush tail. It was only Crookshanks. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Or \i was\i0  it only Crookshanks? Harry squinted, pressing his nose flat against the glass. Crookshanks seemed to have come to a halt. Harry was sure he could see something else moving in the shadow of the trees too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And just then, it emerged \emdash  a gigantic, shaggy black dog,\lang3081  \lang1033 moving stealthily across the lawn, Crookshanks trotting at its side. Harry stared. What did this mean? If Crookshanks could see the dog as well, how could it be an omen of Harry\rquote s death?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron!\rdblquote  Harry hissed. \ldblquote Ron! Wake up!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Huh?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I need you to tell me if you can see something!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote S\rquote all dark, Harry,\rdblquote  Ron muttered thickly. \ldblquote What\rquote re you on about?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Down here \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked quickly back out of the window.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Crookshanks and the dog had vanished. Harry climbed onto the windowsill to look right down into the shadows of the castle, but they weren\rquote t there. Where had they gone?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A loud snore told him Ron had fallen asleep again.\lang3081\par
