Harry\rquote s euphoria at finally winning the Quidditch Cup lasted at least a week. Even the weather seemed to be cel\-ebrating; as June approached, the days became cloudless and sultry, and all anybody felt like doing was strolling onto the grounds and flopping down on the grass with several pints of iced pumpkin juice, perhaps playing a casual game of Gobstones or watching the giant squid propel itself dreamily across the surface of the lake.\par
But they couldn\rquote t. Exams were nearly upon them, and instead of lazing around outside, the students were forced to remain inside the castle, trying to bully their brains into concentrating while en\-ticing wafts of summer air drifted in through the windows. Even Fred and George Weasley had been spotted working; they were about to take their O.W.L.s (Ordinary Wizarding Levels). Percy was getting ready to take his N.E.W.T.s (Nastily Exhausting Wiz\-arding Tests), the highest qualification Hogwarts offered. As Percy\lang3081  \lang1033 hoped to enter the Ministry of Magic, he needed top grades. He was becoming increasingly edgy, and gave very severe punishments to anybody who disturbed the quiet of the common room in the evenings. In fact, the only person who seemed more anxious than Percy was Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Ron had given up asking her how she was managing to attend several classes at once, but they couldn\rquote t restrain them\-selves when they saw the exam schedule she had drawn up for her\-self. The first column read:\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033\i Monday\lang3081\par
\lang1033 9\lang3081  o\rquote clock, Arithmancy\par
\lang1033 9\lang3081  o\rquote clock,\lang1033  Transfiguration\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lunch\lang3081\par
1 o\rquote clock, Charms\par
\lang1033 1 \lang3081 o\rquote clock,\lang1033   Ancient\lang3081  Runes\par
\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione?\rdblquote  Ron said cautiously, because she was liable to explode when interrupted these days. \ldblquote Er \emdash  are you sure you\rquote ve copied down these times right?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  snapped Hermione, picking up the exam schedule and examining it. \ldblquote Yes, of course I have.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is there any point asking how you\rquote re going to sit for two exams at once?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Hermione shortly. \ldblquote Have either of you seen my copy of \i Numerology and Gramatica\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, yeah, I borrowed it for a bit of bedtime reading,\rdblquote  said Ron, but very quietly. Hermione started shifting heaps of parchment\lang3081  \lang1033 around on her table, looking for the book. Just then, there was a rustle at the window and Hedwig fluttered through it, a note clutched tight in her beak.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s from Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Harry, ripping the note open. \ldblquote Buck\-beak\rquote s appeal \emdash  it\rquote s set for the sixth.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s the day we finish our exams,\rdblquote  said Hermione, still look\-ing everywhere for her Arithmancy book.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And they\rquote re coming up here to do it,\rdblquote  said Harry, still reading from the letter. \ldblquote Someone from the Ministry of Magic and \emdash  and an executioner.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione looked up, startled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re bringing the executioner to the appeal! But that sounds as though they\rquote ve already decided!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, it does,\rdblquote  said Harry slowly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They can\rquote t!\rdblquote  Ron howled. \ldblquote I\rquote ve spent \i ages \i0 reading up on stuff for him; they can\rquote t just ignore it all!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Harry had a horrible feeling that the Committee for the Disposal of Dangerous Creatures had had its mind made up for it by Mr. Malfoy. Draco, who had been noticeably subdued since Gryffindor\rquote s triumph in the Quidditch final, seemed to regain some of his old swagger over the next few days. From sneering comments Harry overheard, Malfoy was certain Buckbeak was go\-ing to be killed, and seemed thoroughly pleased with himself for bringing it about. It was all Harry could do to stop himself imitat\-ing Hermione and hitting Malfoy in the face on these occasions. And the worst thing of all was that they had no time or opportu\-nity to go and see Hagrid, because the strict new security measures had not been lifted, and Harry didn\rquote t dare retrieve his Invisibility Cloak from below the one-eyed witch.\par
