\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Exam week began and an unnatural hush fell over the castle. The third years emerged from Transfiguration at lunchtime on Monday, limp and ashen-faced, comparing results and bemoaning the diffi\-culty of the tasks they had been set, which had included turning a teapot into a tortoise. Hermione irritated the rest by fussing about how her tortoise had looked more like a turtle, which was the least of everyone else\rquote s worries.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mine still had a spout for a tail, what a nightmare. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Were the tortoises \i supposed\i0  to breathe steam?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It still had a willow-patterned shell, d\rquote you think that\rquote ll count against me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then, after a hasty lunch, it was straight back upstairs for the Charms exam. Hermione had been right; Professor Flitwick did in\-deed test them on Cheering Charms. Harry slightly overdid his out of nerves and Ron, who was partnering him, ended up in fits of hysterical laughter and had to be led away to a quiet room for an hour before he was ready to perform the charm himself. After din\-ner, the students hurried back to their common rooms, not to re\-lax, but to start studying for Care of Magical Creatures, Potions, and Astronomy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid presided over the Care of Magical Creatures exam the following morning with a very preoccupied air indeed; his heart didn\rquote t seem to be in it at all. He had provided a large tub of fresh flobberworms for the class, and told them that to pass the test, their flobberworm had to still be alive at the end of one hour. As flobberworms flourished best if left to their own devices, it was the easiest exam any of them had ever taken, and also gave\lang3081  \lang1033 Harry, Ron, and Hermione plenty of opportunity to speak to Hagrid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Beaky\rquote s gettin\rquote  a bit depressed,\rdblquote  Hagrid told them, bending low on the pretense of checking that Harry\rquote s flobberworm was still alive. \ldblquote Bin cooped up too long. But still \'85 we\rquote ll know day after tomorrow \emdash  one way or the other \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They had Potions that afternoon, which was an unqualified dis\-aster. Try as Harry might, he couldn\rquote t get his Confusing Concoc\-tion to thicken, and Snape, standing watch with an air of vindictive pleasure, scribbled something that looked suspiciously like a zero onto his notes before moving away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then came Astronomy at midnight, up on the tallest tower; History of Magic on Wednesday morning, in which Harry scribbled everything Florean Fortescue had ever told him about medieval witch-hunts, while wishing he could have had one of Fortescue\rquote s choco-nut sundaes with him in the stifling classroom. Wednesday afternoon meant Herbology, in the greenhouses under a baking-hot sun; then back to the common room once more, with sunburnt necks, thinking longingly of this time next day, when it would all be over.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Their second to last exam, on Thursday morning, was Defense Against the Dark Arts. Professor Lupin had compiled the most un\-usual exam any of them had ever taken; a sort of obstacle course outside in the sun, where they had to wade across a deep paddling pool containing a grindylow, cross a series of potholes full of Red Caps, squish their way across a patch of marsh while ignoring mis\-leading directions from a hinkypunk, then climb into an old trunk and battle with a new boggart.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excellent, Harry,\rdblquote  Lupin muttered as Harry climbed out of the trunk, grinning. \ldblquote Full marks.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Flushed with his success, Harry hung around to watch Ron and Hermione. Ron did very well until he reached the hinkypunk, which successfully confused him into sinking waist-high into the quagmire. Hermione did everything perfectly until she reached the trunk with the boggart in it. After about a minute inside it, she burst out again, screaming.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hermione!\rdblquote  said Lupin, startled. \ldblquote What\rquote s the matter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote P \emdash  P \emdash  Professor McGonagall!\rdblquote  Hermione gasped, pointing into the trunk. \ldblquote Sh \emdash  she said I\rquote d failed everything!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It took a little while to calm Hermione down. When at last she had regained a grip on herself, she, Harry, and Ron went back to the castle. Ron was still slightly inclined to laugh at Hermione\rquote s boggart, but an argument was averted by the sight that met them on the top of the steps.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Cornelius Fudge, sweating slightly in his pinstriped cloak, was standing there staring out at the grounds. He started at the sight of Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hello there, Harry!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Just had an exam, I expect? Nearly finished?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry. Hermione and Ron, not being on speaking terms with the Minister of Magic, hovered awkwardly in the back\-ground.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lovely day,\rdblquote  said Fudge, casting an eye over the lake. \ldblquote Pity \'85 pity \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He sighed deeply and looked down at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m here on an unpleasant mission, Harry. The Committee for\lang3081  \lang1033 the Disposal of Dangerous Creatures required a witness to the exe\-cution of a mad hippogriff. As I needed to visit Hogwarts to check on the Black situation, I was asked to step in.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Does that mean the appeal\rquote s already happened?\rdblquote  Ron inter\-rupted, stepping forward.\lang3081\par
