It took a few seconds for the absurdity of this statement to sink in. Then Ron voiced what Harry was thinking.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re both mental.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ridiculous!\rdblquote  said Hermione faintly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Peter Pettigrew\rquote s \i dead\i0 !\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote\i He\i0  killed him twelve years ago!\rdblquote  He pointed at Black, whose face twitched convulsively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I meant to,\rdblquote  he growled, his yellow teeth bared, \ldblquote but little Peter got the better of me \'85 not this time, though!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And Crookshanks was thrown to the floor as Black lunged at Scabbers; Ron yelled with pain as Black\rquote s weight fell on his broken leg.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sirius, NO!\rdblquote  Lupin yelled, launching himself forwards and dragging Black away from Ron again, \ldblquote WAIT! You can\rquote t do it just like that \emdash  they need to understand \emdash  we\rquote ve got to explain \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We can explain afterwards!\rdblquote  snarled Black, trying to throw\lang3081  \lang1033 Lupin off. One hand was still clawing the air as it tried to reach Scabbers, who was squealing like a piglet, scratching Ron\rquote s face and neck as he tried to escape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote ve \emdash  got \emdash  a \emdash  right \emdash  to \emdash  know \emdash  everything!\rdblquote  Lupin panted, still trying to restrain Black. \ldblquote Ron\rquote s kept him as a pet! There are parts of it even I don\rquote t understand! And Harry \emdash  you owe Harry the truth, Sirius!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Black stopped struggling, though his hollowed eyes were still fixed on Scabbers, who was clamped tightly under Ron\rquote s bitten, scratched, and bleeding hands.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right, then,\rdblquote  Black said, without taking his eyes off the rat. \ldblquote Tell them whatever you like. But make it quick, Remus. I want to commit the murder I was imprisoned for. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re nutters, both of you,\rdblquote  said Ron shakily, looking round at Harry and Hermione for support. \ldblquote I\rquote ve had enough of this. I\rquote m off.\rdblquote\par
He tried to heave himself up on his good leg, but Lupin raised his wand again, pointing it at Scabbers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re going to hear me out, Ron,\rdblquote  he said quietly. \ldblquote Just keep a tight hold on Peter while you listen.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote HE\rquote S NOT PETER, HE\rquote S SCABBERS!\rdblquote  Ron yelled, trying to force the rat back into his front pocket, but Scabbers was fighting too hard; Ron swayed and overbalanced, and Harry caught him and pushed him back down to the bed. Then, ignoring Black, Harry turned to Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There were witnesses who saw Pettigrew die,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote A whole street full of them \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They didn\rquote t see what they thought they saw!\rdblquote  said Black sav\-agely, still watching Scabbers struggling in Ron\rquote s hands.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Everyone thought Sirius killed Peter,\rdblquote  said Lupin, nodding. \ldblquote I believed it myself\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  until I saw the map tonight. Because the Ma\-rauder\rquote s map never lies\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 Peter\rquote s alive. Ron\rquote s holding him, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked down at Ron, and as their eyes met, they agreed, silently: Black and Lupin were both out of their minds. Their story made no sense whatsoever. How could Scabbers be Peter Pettigrew? Azkaban must have unhinged Black after all \emdash  but why was Lupin playing along with him?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then Hermione spoke, in a trembling, would-be calm sort of voice, as though trying to will Professor Lupin to talk sensibly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But Professor Lupin \'85 Scabbers can\rquote t be Pettigrew \'85 it just can\rquote t be true, you know it can\rquote t \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why can\rquote t it be true?\rdblquote  Lupin said calmly, as though they were in class, and Hermione had simply spotted a problem in an experi\-ment with grindylows.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because \'85 because people would \i know\i0  if Peter Pettigrew had been an Animagus. We did Animagi in class with Professor McGonagall. And I looked them up when I did my homework \emdash  the Ministry of Magic keeps tabs on witches and wizards who can become animals; there\rquote s a register showing what animal they be\-come, and their markings and things \'85 and I went and looked Professor McGonagall up on the register, and there have been only seven Animagi this century, and Pettigrew\rquote s name wasn\rquote t on the list \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had barely had time to marvel inwardly at the effort Hermione put into her homework, when Lupin started to laugh.\lang3081  \lang1033\ldblquote Right again, Hermione!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote But the Ministry never knew that there used to be three unregistered Animagi running around Hogwarts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If you\rquote re going to tell them the story, get a move on, Remus,\rdblquote  snarled Black, who was still watching Scabbers\rquote s every desper\-ate move. \ldblquote I\rquote ve waited twelve years, I\rquote m not going to wait much longer.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 but you\rquote ll need to help me, Sirius,\rdblquote  said Lupin, \ldblquote I only know how it began \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin broke off. There had been a loud creak behind him. The bedroom door had opened of its own accord. All five of them stared at it. Then Lupin strode toward it and looked out into the landing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No one there \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This place is haunted!\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s not,\rdblquote  said Lupin, still looking at the door in a puzzled way. \ldblquote The Shrieking Shack was never haunted. \'85 The screams and howls the villagers used to hear were made by me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He pushed his graying hair out of his eyes, thought for a mo\-ment, then said, \ldblquote That\rquote s where all of this starts \emdash  with my becom\-ing a werewolf. None of this could have happened if I hadn\rquote t been bitten \'85 and if I hadn\rquote t been so foolhardy. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked sober and tired. Ron started to interrupt, but Her\-mione said, \ldblquote Shh!\rdblquote  She was watching Lupin very intently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was a very small boy when I received the bite. My parents tried everything, but in those days there was no cure. The potion that Professor Snape has been making for me is a very recent dis\-covery. It makes me safe, you see. As long as I take it in the week\lang3081  \lang1033 preceding the full moon, I keep my mind when I transform. \'85 I am able to curl up in my office, a harmless wolf, and wait for the moon to wane again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Before the Wolfsbane Potion was discovered, however, I be\-came a fully fledged monster once a month. It seemed impossible that I would be able to come to Hogwarts. Other parents weren\rquote t likely to want their children exposed to me.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But then Dumbledore became Headmaster, and he was sympa\-thetic. He said that as long as we took certain precautions, there was no reason I shouldn\rquote t come to school. \'85\rdblquote  Lupin sighed, and looked directly at Harry. \ldblquote I told you, months ago, that the Whomp\-ing Willow was planted the year I came to Hogwarts. The truth is that it was planted \i because\i0  I came to Hogwarts. This house\rdblquote  \emdash  Lupin looked miserably around the room, \emdash  \ldblquote the tunnel that leads to it \emdash  they were built for my use. Once a month, I was smuggled out of the castle, into this place, to transform. The tree was placed at the tunnel mouth to stop anyone coming across me while I was dangerous.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry couldn\rquote t see where this story was going, but he was listen\-ing raptly all the same. The only sound apart from Lupin\rquote s voice was Scabbers\rquote s frightened squeaking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My transformations in those days were \emdash  were terrible. It is very painful to turn into a werewolf. I was separated from humans to bite, so I bit and scratched myself instead. The villagers heard the noise and the screaming and thought they were hearing partic\-ularly violent spirits. Dumbledore encouraged the rumor. \'85 Even now, when the house has been silent for years, the villagers don\rquote t dare approach it. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But apart from my transformations, I was happier than I had ever been in my life. For the first time ever, I had friends, three great friends. Sirius Black \'85 Peter Pettigrew \'85 and, of course, your father, Harry \emdash  James Potter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, my three friends could hardly fail to notice that I disap\-peared once a month. I made up all sorts of stories. I told them my mother was ill, and that I had to go home to see her. \'85 I was terrified they would desert me the moment they found out what I was. But of course, they, like you, Hermione, worked out the truth. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And they didn\rquote t desert me at all. Instead, they did something for me that would make my transformations not only bearable, but the best times of my life. They became Animagi.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My dad too?\rdblquote  said Harry, astounded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, indeed,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote It took them the best part of three years to work out how to do it. Your father and Sirius here were the cleverest students in the school, and lucky they were, because the Animagus transformation can go horribly wrong \emdash  one reason the Ministry keeps a close watch on those attempting to do it. Peter needed all the help he could get from James and Sirius. Finally, in our fifth year, they managed it. They could each turn into a differ\-ent animal at will.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But how did that help you?\rdblquote  said Hermione, sounding puzzled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They couldn\rquote t keep me company as humans, so they kept me company as animals,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote A werewolf is only a danger to people. They sneaked out of the castle every month under James\rquote s Invisibility Cloak. They transformed \'85 Peter, as the smallest, could slip beneath the Willow\rquote s attacking branches and touch the knot that freezes it. They would then slip down the tunnel and join\lang3081  \lang1033 me. Under their influence, I became less dangerous. My body was still wolfish, but my mind seemed to become less so while I was with them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hurry up, Remus,\rdblquote  snarled Black, who was still watching Scab\-bers with a horrible sort of hunger on his face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m getting there, Sirius, I\rquote m getting there \'85 well, highly ex\-citing possibilities were open to us now that we could all transform. Soon we were leaving the Shrieking Shack and roaming the school grounds and the village by night. Sirius and James transformed into such large animals, they were able to keep a werewolf in check. I doubt whether any Hogwarts students ever found out more about the Hogwarts grounds and Hogsmeade than we did. \'85 And that\rquote s how we came to write the Marauder\rquote s Map, and sign it with our nicknames. Sirius is Padfoot. Peter is Wormtail. James was Prongs.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What sort of animal \emdash  ?\rdblquote  Harry began, but Hermione cut him off.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was still really dangerous! Running around in the dark with a werewolf! What if you\rquote d given the others the slip, and bitten somebody?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A thought that still haunts me,\rdblquote  said Lupin heavily. \ldblquote And there were near misses, many of them. We laughed about them after\-wards. We were young, thoughtless \emdash  carried away with our own cleverness.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I sometimes felt guilty about betraying Dumbledore\rquote s trust, of course \'85 he had admitted me to Hogwarts when no other head\-master would have done so, and he had no idea I was breaking the rules he had set down for my own and others\rquote  safety. He never knew I had led three fellow students into becoming Animagi ille\-gally. But I always managed to forget my guilty feelings every time\lang3081  \lang1033 we sat down to plan our next month\rquote s adventure. And I haven\rquote t changed \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin\rquote s face had hardened, and there was self-disgust in his voice. \ldblquote All this year, I have been battling with myself, wondering whether I should tell Dumbledore that Sirius was an Animagus. But I didn\rquote t do it. Why? Because I was too cowardly. It would have meant admitting that I\rquote d betrayed his trust while I was at school, admit\-ting that I\rquote d led others along with me \'85 and Dumbledore\rquote s trust has meant everything to me. He let me into Hogwarts as a boy, and he gave me a job when I have been shunned all my adult life, un\-able to find paid work because of what I am. And so I convinced myself that Sirius was getting into the school using dark arts he learned from Voldemort, that being an Animagus had nothing to do with it\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 so, in a way, Snape\rquote s been right about me all along.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Snape?\rdblquote  said Black harshly, taking his eyes off Scabbers for the first time in minutes and looking up at Lupin. \ldblquote What\rquote s Snape got to do with it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s here, Sirius,\rdblquote  said Lupin heavily. \ldblquote He\rquote s teaching here as well.\rdblquote  He looked up at Harry, Ron, and Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Snape was at school with us. He fought very hard against my appointment to the Defense Against the Dark Arts job. He has been telling Dumbledore all year that I am not to be trusted. He has his reasons \'85 you see, Sirius here played a trick on him which nearly killed him, a trick which involved me \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Black made a derisive noise.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It served him right,\rdblquote  he sneered. \ldblquote Sneaking around, trying to find out what we were up to \'85 hoping he could get us ex\-pelled. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Severus was very interested in where I went every month.\rdblquote  Lupin told Harry, Ron, and Hermione. \ldblquote We were in the same year, you know, and we \emdash  er \emdash  didn\rquote t like each other very much. He especially disliked James. Jealous, I think, of James\rquote s talent on the Quidditch field \'85 anyway Snape had seen me crossing the grounds with Madam Pomfrey one evening as she led me toward the Whomping Willow to transform. Sirius thought it would be \emdash  er \emdash  amusing, to tell Snape all he had to do was prod the knot on the tree trunk with a long stick, and he\rquote d be able to get in after me. Well, of course, Snape tried it \emdash  if he\rquote d got as far as this house, he\rquote d have met a fully grown werewolf\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  but your father, who\rquote d heard what Sirius had done, went after Snape and pulled him back, at great risk to his life \'85 Snape glimpsed me, though, at the end of the tunnel. He was forbidden by Dumbledore to tell anybody, but from that time on he knew what I was. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So that\rquote s why Snape doesn\rquote t like you,\rdblquote  said Harry slowly, \ldblquote be\-cause he thought you were in on the joke?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right,\rdblquote  sneered a cold voice from the wall behind Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Severus Snape was pulling off the Invisibility Cloak, his wand pointing directly at Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\fs36\page Chapter 19\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc The Servant of Lord Voldemort\par
