\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85 I bet the Dursleys\rquote d be pleased to let me come \'85 especially after what I did to Aunt Marge. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Feeling considerably more cheerful, Harry joined Ron and Hermione in several games of Exploding Snap, and when the witch with the tea cart arrived, he bought himself a very large lunch, though nothing with chocolate in it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But it was late in the afternoon before the thing that made him truly happy turned up. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermione suddenly, peering over his shoulder. \ldblquote What\rquote s that thing outside your window?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned to look outside. Something very small and gray was bobbing in and out of sight beyond the glass. He stood up for a better look and saw that it was a tiny owl, carrying a letter that was much too big for it. The owl was so small, in fact, that it kept tumbling over in the air, buffeted this way and that in the train\rquote s slipstream. Harry quickly pulled down the window, stretched out\lang3081  \lang1033 his arm, and caught it. It felt like a very fluffy Snitch. He brought it carefully inside. The owl dropped its letter onto Harry\rquote s seat and began zooming around their compartment, apparently very pleased with itself for accomplishing its task. Hedwig clicked her beak with a sort of dignified disapproval. Crookshanks sat up in his seat, following the owl with his great yellow eyes. Ron, noticing this, snatched the owl safely out of harm\rquote s way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry picked up the letter. It was addressed to him. He ripped open the letter, and shouted, \ldblquote It\rquote s from Sirius!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Ron and Hermione excitedly. \ldblquote Read it aloud!\rdblquote\par
\lang3081\par
